<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton still not set on nominating team  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton is
learning that dealing with New York's fractious Democrats can
sometimes seem as challenging as taking on a big-name Republican
like Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton's campaign was unable to say who would
nominate her at next week's state party convention. In fact, the
campaign wasn't sure if President Clinton would attend the Albany
event.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll have an announcement soon,'' Clinton aide Howard Wolfson
said.
</P>
<P>
   It has been known since mid-April that Giuliani would be
nominated at the state GOP convention on May 30 in Buffalo by Gov.
George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The major question on Republican minds now is whether the New
York City mayor will still be in the race by then. He announced
April 27 that he had been diagnosed with treatable prostate cancer
and was uncertain if he could remain in the race. The mayor has
promised a decision on that before the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   Still on Giuliani's campaign schedule were two fund-raising
events for his Senate campaign in New York this week. Uncertain,
however, was whether he would head to California next week for
fund-raising events Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson's comment about Clinton's nomination came after the New
York Daily News reported Tuesday that state Comptroller H. Carl
McCall and federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, both eyeing a
run for governor in 2002, are battling to be the one who nominates
the first lady at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   McCall told the newspaper that he hoped he would be considered
for the nominating role, ''but I understand their problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, the son of former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, said there
wasn't any battle that he knew about over who would nominate
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never asked anyone about nominating the first lady and
nobody talked to me about it either,'' Cuomo said in a telephone
interview from Virginia. ''I'll do whatever they think is
helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said he would attend the convention and did plan to speak
at it.
</P>
<P>
   Party sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
likely solution to Clinton's dilemma would be having her nominated
by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring from the Senate at
the end of this year and whose seat Clinton is seeking, and by Sen.
Charles Schumer. Moynihan took on the duties of introducing the
first lady at her formal campaign announcement in February.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the situation, a spokesman for state Democratic
Chairwoman Judith Hope, Peter Kauffmann, said ''there's so much
talent in the Democratic Party, of course there are talented
leaders who want to nominate Hillary. I wouldn't call that
jockeying.''
</P>
<P>
   Kauffmann said he did not yet know who would be handling the
nominating chores or even how many speakers would be taking the
podium at next week's convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's being worked out this week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton did attend his wife's campaign announcement in
February, but did not speak at the event. The first lady has said
she must establish an identity separate from the White House if she
is to win a Senate seat. Her first 30-second television
advertisement, unveiled last week, makes no mention of the
president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
