<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Immigrant groups protest English Regents standards  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Veronica Kerscaek says she is lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old who came to New York from Romania three years
ago took the English language arts Regents exam in January and got
a score of 57. It was just two points above the minimum requirement
for a local diploma, but it ensured that she would graduate from
high school and pursue a college education.
</P>
<P>
   Kerscaek, a student at the Manhattan Comprehensive Day and Night
School, said many of her friends still don't have the adequate
language skills to pass the English exam.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need more time,'' she told more than 100 people from
different immigrant groups rallying in front of the state Education
Department Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The groups chanted, ''Learning first, testing second,'' and
urged the state Education Department to delay imposing the English
exam requirement for English language learners.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new standards are totally unfair to immigrant students
coming into this country trying to learn English,'' said Margie
McHugh, executive director of the New York Immigration Coalition.
''Students need to have a chance to learn before they get tested.''
</P>
<P>
   McHugh said there are simply not enough qualified teachers,
facilities and resources to accomplish that goal. More funding is
necessary, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the stricter education standards set by the Board of
Regents, seniors who plan to graduate this June must get at least a
score of 55 on their English language arts exam to get a local
diploma and a 65 for a Regents diploma. The new requirement does
not exempt English-language learners.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition said it takes between four to seven years before
foreign-born students can be proficient enough in English to pass
the Regents exam. The groups asked the state Education Department
to let these students graduate this year without passing the new
English exam and instead allow a safety net -- letting students take
the easier Regents competency exams administered in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   The Regents in 1998 passed a ''12-step action plan'' to prepare
English language learners for the new exams, but McHugh said many
schools received waivers and did not follow the guidelines of the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ray, a spokesman for the Education Department, denied that
charge, saying that school districts reported that they are
adhering to the plan and no waivers were given. He added that to
help these students, the Regents have required double or triple the
English instruction time.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important for students to learn English because they will
need it to go to college or to get a good job. It is important that
they learn it in high school,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, where 80 percent of the state's
English-language learners live, between 600 to 700 of the 2,200
foreign-born seniors still need to pass the exam as of January, Ray
said. Some students took the exam in April, and those are still
being graded. Students can still take the exam in June and if they
fail, they could take more English in the summer and try again in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said the department has also made various accommodations for
English-language learners, like extending test-taking time to nine
hours for the two-day, six-hour English exam. Students can also use
a bilingual dictionary and have listening comprehension questions
read to them three times instead of just once. Aside from the
English exam, students can take other Regents tests in their native
language or with the help of a translator.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Peter Rivera, D-Bronx, said he is proposing a
bill that would waive the English exam requirement for
English-language learners. Under the measure, students would be
awarded a local diploma if they pass the Regents competency exam in
their native languages, pass an English proficiency exam and
fulfill other graduation requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would be effective until June 30, 2003,
providing time for the Education Department to institute permanent
policy changes regarding the English requirement for foreign born
students.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our children have the same right to graduate as anybody else.
There are options, there are alternatives,'' Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Assemblyman Adriano Espaillat, a Manhattan Democrat and
co-sponsor of the bill: ''I don't know if Einstein ever got to
master the English language, but he really got to do some wonderful
things for the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-10-00 0014 </TRAILER>
