<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Andrew Cuomo: If I want to run, the party will listen  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York's race for the governorship on the
Democratic side is heating up even though the election is still
more than two years away and there are no declared candidates.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo said state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall's attempt to sew up the 2002 Democratic
nomination early won't work. And, Cuomo declared: ''If Andrew Cuomo
says, 'I want to run,' the party will listen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cuomo, the son of former Gov. Mario Cuomo, still wouldn't
say if he will run for the gubernatorial nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm seriously considering it,'' he said, adding that he would
not rule out a primary against McCall.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Cuomo said it was too early to campaign for governor
and that he was concentrating his efforts on getting Al Gore
elected president and Hillary Rodham Clinton elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's way too early to start working on any 2002 race,'' Cuomo
said in a telephone interview from Virginia. ''I think it's a
distraction from what the party should be doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall, the only black to be elected to statewide office in New
York, has been working for several months at lining up support for
a possible run for governor. He has told supporters privately that
he will run. Publicly, he says he will make a decision after this
November's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't made any comments about a potential primary, nor do
I intend to,'' McCall said in a statement, declining further
comment. ''I haven't announced that I'm running for governor and I
don't know who else will run if I do.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall already has the support of state Attorney General Eliot
Spitzer, state Assembly Majority Leader Michael Bragman and former
Lt. Gov. Stan Lundine, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo loyalists, meanwhile, have been urging New York Democrats
not to get behind McCall.
</P>
<P>
   That effort has met with limited success and Cuomo said Tuesday
that lining up the support of the party leaders and elected
officials couldn't deliver the nomination for McCall.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't work that way anymore -- that you can close out a
person by gaining the support of the clubhouse. Politics doesn't
work that way anymore,'' Cuomo said. ''Bradley showed us that.
McCain showed us that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that former Sen. Bill Bradley and Sen. John McCain both
lost their party's nominations for president to Gore and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, respectively, in large part because the two winners
had a lock on party organizational support, Cuomo brushed that
aside.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bush was in many ways a party outsider to the national
process,'' Cuomo said. ''I would argue McCain was more of an
insider.''
</P>
<P>
   And, the former governor's eldest son said that while McCall
might have organizational support, that couldn't block someone with
money or, like him, with name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said that he considered himself in the same light as such
other New York party luminaries as Spitzer and Sen. Charles Schumer
-- people the party would also listen to because of their
reputations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm saying I'm just like these other guys,'' Cuomo said in a
follow-up interview.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Cuomo, seeking a fourth, four-year term, lost the 1994
governor's race to Republican George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has said he is considering running for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cuomo has been rumored as a possible White House chief of
staff should Gore win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Cuomo said: ''My heart is in New York. That's
where I want to be. I've been here (in Washington) for seven years
... I've done this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
