<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCall: All public retiree pension funds favor boost  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, 
o0143nyc--
r n PM-NY--PensionIncreases Bjt   05-10 0660
PM-NY--Pension Increases, Bjt,0635   
McCall: All public retiree pension funds favor boost   
By JOEL STASHENKO
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Support appears to be growing for automatic
cost-of-living benefit increases for retirees from state and local
government jobs in New York.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller H. Carl McCall said Tuesday that
administrators of all eight pension funds covering retired public
employees are behind the idea of recurring cost-of-living
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The other systems are on board,'' H. Carl McCall said before
attending a rally of about 10,000 current and retired public
employees near the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   McCall administers the largest of the funds, the $127 billion
Common Retirement Fund. All told, the eight funds have assets of
more than $300 billion and all have grown significantly in recent
years thanks to the prolonged boom on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, representing all major public unions in New
York, gathered to push the state Legislature and Gov. George Pataki
to approve a cost-of-living-adjustment (COLA) bill covering all
public employee pensions this session. Lawmakers are expected to be
meeting for six or seven more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Permanent COLA is long overdue,'' Denis Hughes, president of
the state AFL-CIO, said. ''Our pension funds are awash in cash. ...
We have enough money to do this. It's fair. And it's about time.''
</P>
<P>
   Top officials of the largest unions representing public
employees appeared at a news conference before the rally to promote
the pension boost. They included Randi Weingarten of the United
Federation of Teachers, Thomas Hobart of New York State United
Teachers, Danny Donohue of the Civil Service Employees Association,
Roger Benson of the Public Employees Federation and Greg Nash of
the National Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue called the failure to enact a COLA provision in public
retirement systems ''obscene'' and he said that 60 percent of those
covered by the state's Common Retirement System are getting less
than $10,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven other states have COLAs for public retirees, but
New York is among ''Mississippi, Alabama and some of those other
states'' that do not, Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
   A task force appointed by Pataki recommended a permanent COLA
tied to some gauge of increases in the cost of living, such as the
Consumer Price Index. The governor announced last week he agreed
with the task force's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   The labor leaders said Tuesday any increases should also take
into consideration how long employees worked and how long they've
been retired, with the oldest retirees getting larger increases.
They could provide no specifics, however, about what a COLA should
provide to a typical retired public employee in the state.
</P>
<P>
   McCall had proposed ''performance-based'' COLAs, meaning that if
the pension funds did strongly, pensioners would benefit. The labor
leaders, however, said the pension funds have become so lucrative
there is no need to prohibit increases if they have an off year.
</P>
<P>
   And McCall said Tuesday all the pension systems can afford
increases without first passing a performance test.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally, held under a sweltering midday sun, state Senate
Majority leader Joseph Bruno repeatedly told the retirees, ''Now,
it's your turn'' for a pension increase. State Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver also promised to give retirees the COLAs they are
pushing for.
</P>
<P>
   The pension funds for former New York City employees are
separate from the state retirees. But a pension law enacted by the
Legislature and governor would affect all eight systems in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Weingarten said the labor leaders were rallying in Albany,
despite the apparent unanimous agreement here for COLAs, because
the ''legislation is here.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Albany controls pension legislation, not New York City,'' she
said. ''New York City can afford this. ... New York City is awash
in money and it can afford it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
