<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court tries to halt jurors from providing own testimony tocolleagues  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Jurors in New York from now on will likely
hear an additional instruction from the judge when they go into
deliberations: Your expert testimony is not welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The state's highest court on Tuesday called on judges to
''direct that jurors may not use their professional expertise to
insert facts and evidence'' as they ruled for a retrial in a
homicide case in which two jurors apparently did just that.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-member Court of Appeals panel said that two nurses
should not have provided medical opinions to fellow jurors in an
Orange County trial. The unanimous opinion was written by Judge
Joseph Bellacosa.
</P>
<P>
   The decision concerns the case of Michael Maragh, 26, who was
convicted of criminally negligent homicide in Orange County Court
November 1997 in the death of May DeGroat, his girlfriend and
mother of his two children.
</P>
<P>
   His attorneys argued that the 26-year-old DeGroat died of an air
embolism caused by having sexual intercourse too soon after giving
birth. She had the couple's second child nine days earlier.
Prosecutors contended Maragh beat the woman in the couple's
Middletown apartment and that the blood loss killed her.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses, according to court documents, offered to the entire
jury their own professional opinions on the case, which they came
to after sharing a room while sequestered. One offered her own
calculation on the effect of DeGroat's blood loss. The jury
convicted Maragh on its second day of deliberations. Another juror
later testified that the nurses' opinions directly affected the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The court wrote Tuesday that when jurors who have professional
knowledge ''take the additional, forbidden step beyond the evidence
of the cases'' of advising jurors, ''that would violate the rights
of litigants to have their cases decided only on the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The nurses' remarks came to light through reports in The Times
Herald-Record in Middletown. Later, a county court judge called for
a retrial but the district attorney's office asked for a reversal
from the Appellate Division of state Supreme Court, which
reinstated Maragh's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office had argued that the county
judge's instructions that the jurors could utilize ''personal
experience'' in deciding the facts of the case entitled medical
professionals to share that knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Maragh was originally sentenced to 1-1/3 to four years in prison
and has served about 16 months already.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to jail March 31 following the reinstatement of his
conviction and has not been allowed to see his two young sons since
his arrest in March 1997, said attorney Ben Ostrer.
</P>
<P>
   Orange County District Attorney Frank Phillips said he will
press to get Maragh convicted again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-10-00 0016 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
