<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DEC gave landfill site poor review  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- As city officials ponder a lucrative offer to
accept New York City garbage, environmental issues have suddenly
loomed as a threat to trash the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   According to 7-year-old agency documents, the site for the
proposed garbage landfill was not a good location. The DEC, which
grants solid waste management facility permits for landfills, soon
may have the power to make or break the offer by Albany-based
Greenbrier Management Corp. to open a landfill on 550 acres in
Rome's rural northwest corner.
</P>
<P>
   ''The site does have issues,'' Sandra LeBarron of the DEC said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the DeMarma Corp. proposed a privately owned
mixed-waste landfill on some of the same land on which Greenbrier
wants to build a facility to take in 5,000 tons of New York City
trash every day for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But DEC officials had reservations about the site, according to
a letter written in response to a preliminary site assessment
submitted to the department by DeMarma.
</P>
<P>
   ''While under the new Part 360 regulations, it may be
technically possible for DeMarma to construct the required landfill
site conditions, based on the information you submitted, we still
do not believe this is a good site for a landfill,'' the letter
stated.
</P>
<P>
   Part 360 regulates solid waste management practices under state
law.
</P>
<P>
   Prior letters from the DEC to DeMarma raised questions about
groundwater flow and possible aquifers, archaeological sites and
endangered species, including the ''secretive Bog Turtle,'' in the
area of the site.
</P>
<P>
   LeBarron said she could not comment further until the DEC
receives a permit application from the company. Greenbrier Vice
President James McGuire said he was unaware of the department's
findings.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the work we have done so far ... we are confident the
site is physically suitable for what we propose,'' McGuire said.
''We looked at this site very thoroughly under today's standards.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company would not apply for a DEC permit unless Rome
approves its landfill offer. The company, which wants an answer by
June, has tentatively offered the city incentives worth about $7
million a year if it approves the offer. That represents more than
half the city's $12.2 million tax levy for this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, we're waiting on the city to see what they want to
do on this,'' McGuire said.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire said if everything is approved, Greenbrier would build
the dump by 2004 and maintain the site. However, he said once it is
built one of three major New York City haulers -- Allied Waste
Industries, IESI, or Waste Management -- would own it and be
responsible for hauling trash to the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire referred to the waste, which would be transported by
rail, as residential garbage. ''It's what you and I throw away,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
