<HEADLINE> Former plastic surgeon pleads innocent to poisoning wife  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- A former plastic surgeon who gained
celebrity for his ''snap-on hair'' invention and then went to
prison over the death of a patient denies he poisoned his wife with
arsenic, as prosecutors claim.
</P>
<P>
   In a case Erie County District Attorney Frank Clark termed
''bizarre,'' Anthony Pignataro was charged Tuesday with attempted
murder, assault and unrelated drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities allege Pignataro, 42, slowly poisoned his wife of 15
years between June and August last year after the couple reunited
following a separation. The arsenic, common in rat poison, was
discovered after Deborah Pignataro was hospitalized with numbness,
vomiting and other symptoms. The mother of two remains confined to
a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Pignataro's attorney said prosecutors have no case.
</P>
<P>
   ''The grand jury can indict a ham sandwich if they want to,''
Joel Daniels said. ''It's one thing to indict the ham sandwich.
It's another thing to convict it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark acknowledged prosecutors will be challenged because there
are no witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a situation like this we're arguing to the jury, if not
him, who? We only had four people in the household, the father, the
mother and the children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pignataro was ordered held without bail after pleading innocent
Tuesday in state Supreme Court. He has been imprisoned since March
for using heroin in violation of his probation from a 1998
conviction of criminally negligent homicide.
</P>
<P>
   The homicide charge arose from the death of a 26-year-old
patient who suffered a heart attack while undergoing
breast-augmentation surgery in 1997. Pignataro served six months in
prison and lost his medical license.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of trying to kill his estranged wife he could face
up to 25 years in prison. Unrelated to the attempted murder charge
in the indictment unsealed Tuesday were three drug charges accusing
Pignataro of possessing heroin in March and July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pignataros still face a joint child-neglect trial in Erie
County Family Court in June for allegedly exposing their children
to arsenic last year. Then 9 and 12, the children were tested for
the poison after their mother became ill. While arsenic, present in
nature, was detected, ''it was well within normal range,'' Clark
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pignataro attracted attention in the mid-1990s for his invention
of a hairpiece that attaches to snaps surgically implanted in the
scalp. His own first patient and test case, he demonstrated his
snap-on hair on late-night television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
