<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists: Eyeglasses are windows to radon exposure  </HEADLINE>
By RIK STEVENS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) -- The best radon detectors could be right
before your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have discovered some eyeglass lenses make reliable
recorders of a person's exposure to radon, a naturally occurring
gas linked to as many as 30,000 lung cancer deaths every year in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Fleischer, a geology professor at Union College, led a
team that examined 17 sets of lenses using regular and electron
microscopy, measuring and mapping the tiny, conical dents made when
radioactive particles of a decaying radon molecule smash into
lenses made of CR-39 plastic.
</P>
<P>
   By comparing the ''etchings'' -- less than a few thousandths of
an inch deep -- to constant markings created in a radon chamber,
Fleischer determined how much radon the wearer was exposed to since
he or she first started wearing glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer expects the research will be of use in health studies
aimed at shoring up the link between radon and lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1980s, when radon was positively connected to
lung cancer, detectors that cost about $20 have been used to
measure how much of the gas is in a given area of a building. Since
few people live exclusively in the basement where radon
concentration is highest, the detectors are of little value in
determining a person's lifetime exposure, Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   There are other problems with using environmental measures alone
to study the link between radon and cancer, according to the
Environmental Protection Agency. People move and it can be
impossible to track down every past address; older houses are
remodeled or even demolished, destroying or altering the radon
record.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said there are several benefits to using the
eyeglasses as personal dosimeters:
</P>
<P>
   -- Because opticians keep records of when eyeglasses were
prescribed, researchers can establish a baseline for radon exposure
over a definite time period.
</P>
<P>
   -- The glass is ground for a specific prescription, creating a
new surface when the wearer orders the glasses, a clean slate on
which to record particle etchings.
</P>
<P>
   -- The eyeglasses give researchers a long-term record of exposure
to radon particles, which can be detected for 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cleaning the lenses will remove only a few ''minutes'' of
exposure over the course of 30-plus years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it puts us in much more direct contact with
establishing how much radon causes how much cancer,'' Fleischer
said. ''You get information on people rather than on the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer will present his findings May 16 in Hiroshima, Japan,
at a meeting of the International Radiation Protection Association.
He also will publish the research in the scientific journal Health
Physics later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Radon is produced when underground uranium decays. The gas seeps
into homes through cracks in foundations then breaks down into
solid particles that can either be directly inhaled or attached to
dust and drawn into the lungs. Because radon particles love to
cling to surfaces, the branched network of bronchioles in the lungs
offers an ample target.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a national residential radon survey completed in 1991,
the average indoor radon level is 1.3 picocuries per liter in the
United States, the Environmental Protection Agency says. The
average outdoor level is 0.4 pCi/L.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials say homeowners who find radon levels higher
than 4 picocuries per liter should take action such as sealing
cracks in basements walls and floors or running a pipe from the
foundation through the house up to the attic.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA estimates radon contributes to 7,000-30,000 lung cancer
deaths every year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. R. William Field, a cancer epidemiologist at the University
of Iowa, said Fleischer's research will work best in conjunction
with environmental studies to provide a better idea of radon's
affect on lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hardest part of a radon epidemiology study is you have to
know what the retrospective radon exposure was,'' Field said.
''These give us better dose estimates. When we have better dose
estimates we can make better risk projections concerning the health
risks posed by home exposure. It's very innovative.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal dosimeters have been used for decades to measure
exposure to certain radioactive particles such as gamma rays, but
the idea of a radon gauge is new, Field said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It does provide a good reference to what the person has been
exposed to during the time that the person has worn glasses,'' said
Field, who recently completed a study into radon exposures of
people who lived in a house for at least 20 years. The results of
that study are due to be released May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer's eyeglass work began three years ago and included
Union students Stephen A. Hadley and Nicholas R. Meyer, and Dr.
Alfred Cavallo of the Environmental Measurements Laboratory, a U.S.
Department of Energy facility in New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-10-00 0017 </TRAILER>
