<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aetna Low-Cost Health Plan Falters  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A year ago, the nation's largest health insurer
thought it would make a small dent in American's uninsured problem
by offering a cut-rate plan with minimal benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna Inc. officials thought people would be better off with at
least a basic health insurance plan than no coverage at all.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, many of the 43 million uninsured think otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Aetna officials acknowledged that initial sales have
been slow, though they refused to disclose how many people have
signed up for the plan. Aetna blamed the slow start on the time it
has taken state regulators to approve the plan, which is now sold
in 32 states and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   But industry observers fault the plan's poor benefits and lack
of coverage for catastrophic illness, and say the absence of a
major promotional campaign from Aetna has hampered its success.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Aetna's then-chairman Richard Huber announced the
Affordable HealthChoices program amid much fanfare. Huber said the
program was not the complete answer to the problem of the growing
number of uninsured, but did show that the nation's largest health
insurer was taking the lead in attacking the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Affordable HealthChoices offers three types of plans designed
for companies with five or fewer workers. All of the options have
no deductibles and cost considerably less than most health
insurance plans, with monthly premiums ranging from $46 to $91 for
an individual and $156 to $275 for a family. As with all insurance,
an employer could pick up part of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   But the plans provide much smaller benefits than typical
insurance. For instance, under all the options, a patient would get
a maximum $50 toward a doctor's visit, no matter how much the
doctor charged.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital benefits vary. Under one option, the insurance pays
$750 a day for the first three days, $350 a day for the next seven
days and $100 a day for the rest of the stay. That's not likely to
cover most hospital bills, particularly for patients undergoing
major surgery or needing intensive care.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of consumers believe that having a bare-bones policy is
no better than having no policy at all,'' said Pat Schoeni,
spokeswoman for the National Coalition on Health Care, a
nonpartisan group that seeks to help the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Viewpoints differ on whether Aetna offered the program as a way
to deal with the uninsured, or to score points with federal
lawmakers. Aetna and other managed care plans have faced heavy
criticism for raising premiums beyond reach of many working
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Part of me says they did this because it sounds like a good
piece of PR (public relations) and that they have decided not to
push it because they could not sell it or make money from it,''
Schoeni said.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Amaral, national director of healthcare for National
Federal of Independent Businesses, which represents small
businesses, said the Aetna plan was a bad idea from the start.
Employers who offered the program would have difficulty explaining
the plan's many limitations, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't think it offered much value, even for the low
price,'' Amaral said. ''The last thing employers want is to give
their employees a health plan they can complain about.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with the plan was Aetna's decision to sell it
through its network of insurance brokers, she said. Because Aetna
only pays its agents about 3 percent of the first year's premium,
the agents have little financial incentive to offer it compared to
more expensive plans, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her criticisms, Amaral said she gives Aetna credit for
at least developing a new product. ''It was a valiant effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna spokeswoman Jill Griffiths said the company is still
trying to determine the best way to sell the plan. ''We are very
aware of the criticisms of the program,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since Affordable HealthChoices was launched, Aetna
has been a company in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Huber resigned earlier this spring amid pressure from investors
discouraged by the company's poor stock performance. And after the
company rejected a takeover offer, Aetna decided to split into two
publicly traded companies, one for health care and one for
financial services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0024 </TRAILER>
