<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alabama Coach Robert Scott Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- Alabama assistant men's basketball coach
Robert Scott died of cancer Tuesday. He was 42.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, a former All-SEC player with the Crimson Tide, died at
DCH Regional Medical Center in Tuscaloosa, the school said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was diagnosed with stomach cancer in September 1999 and
continued to attend Crimson Tide games while undergoing treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like if I can just come in, sit down and watch,'' he
told The Birmingham News in February, ''it's better than not being
here. If I can get up and say one or two things, I want to try and
do something. That just keeps me going.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott was picked in the fourth round by Golden State in the 1980
NBA draft and played professionally overseas for six years.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Alabama to begin his coaching career at the high
school level and was assistant coach at Alabama-Birmingham from
1996-98. Scott was hired by Alabama in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
