<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nebraska AG Wins GOP Primary  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN O'HANLON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Nebraska Attorney General Don Stenberg took
the first step Tuesday toward reclaiming Sen. Bob Kerrey's seat for
the Republicans, easily defeating the secretary of state and two
other candidates in the GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
   With 89 percent of precincts reporting, Stenberg had 83,449
votes, or 50 percent, far more than Secretary of State Scott
Moore's 36,839 votes, or 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stenberg will take on popular former Gov. Ben Nelson, who left
office in 1999 after two terms. Nelson easily beat a homeless man
who was his only opponent in the Democratic primary for Kerrey's
seat.
</P>
<P>
   In other elections Tuesday, former University of Nebraska
football coach Tom Osborne routed his two opponents in a GOP
congressional primary. Osborne is adored in football-crazy
Nebraska, though issues such as the struggling farm economy and
bringing technology to rural areas dominated his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question I had a name recognition advantage, but as
time went on people started to focus on the issues and not who was
a football coach and who wasn't,'' Osborne told 150 supporters at
an election night party on a private ranch.
</P>
<P>
   There were presidential primaries in Nebraska and West Virginia,
but both were essentially meaningless since George W. Bush and Al
Gore have sealed their parties' nominations.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia Gov. Cecil Underwood, who was elected to his first
term as governor in 1956 and to his second term in 1996, easily won
the GOP nomination for a third term Tuesday. At 77, Underwood is
the nation's oldest governor. He is also the only Republican in a
statewide office in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The more dramatic West Virginia race was for the House seat
being left by nine-term Rep. Bob Wise, who won the Democratic
primary to challenge Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   Four Democrats vied for Wise's seat, including 85-year-old
Secretary of State Ken Hechler, who has already spent 18 years in
Congress, from 1959 through 1977. Hechler finished third, well
behind lawyer Jim Humphreys, who spent $3 million of his own money.
</P>
<P>
   Hechler spent about $300,000 of his own money and said anything
over $1 million in a primary is ''overkill.'' He ran a TV ad Monday
urging voters to cast their ballot for anyone but Humphreys.
</P>
<P>
   With 86 percent of precincts reporting, Humphreys had 31,169
votes, or 42 percent, while state Sen. Martha Yeager Walker had
21,317 votes, or 29 percent. Hechler had 17,769 votes -- 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Humphreys will be heavily favored in deeply Democratic West
Virginia to beat Republican Shelley Moore Capito this fall. Capito,
a member of the state House of Delegates, is the daughter of former
three-term Gov. Arch Moore Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, the only Democrat in Nebraska's congressional
delegation, decided not to run for a third term and will instead
become president of New School University in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Stenberg recently defended Nebraska's ban on so-called partial
birth abortions before the Supreme Court. He beat Moore despite the
secretary of state's edge in fund raising this year. Moore had
collected $224,000 to Stenberg's $144,000.
</P>
<P>
   After coaching Nebraska for 25 years and leading the Cornhuskers
to three national championships in the 1990s, Osborne, 63, is
running for the House seat held for five terms by Republican Bill
Barrett, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   With 91 percent of precincts reporting, Osborne had 44,619 votes
-- 70 percent. Longtime state GOP leader John Gale followed with
11,205 votes, or 18 percent, and state Board of Education member
Kathy Wilmot had 7,838 votes -- 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne will face Democrat Rollie Reynolds, a real estate
investor, in November.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his self-imposed limit on campaign contributions over
$300 and his refusal to accept money from political action
committees, Osborne had raised $112,285 by mid-April. About half
was unsolicited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
