<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, May 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nebraska AG Wins GOP Primary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Nebraska Attorney General Don Stenberg took the first
step Tuesday toward reclaiming Sen. Bob Kerrey's seat for the Republicans,
easily defeating the secretary of state and two other candidates in the GOP
primary. With 38 percent of precincts reporting, Stenberg had 43,168 votes, or
50 percent, far more than Secretary of State Scott Moore's 20,737 votes, or 24
percent. Stenberg will take on popular former Gov. Ben Nelson, who left office
in 1999 after two terms. Nelson easily beat a homeless man who was his only
opponent in the Democratic primary for Kerrey's seat.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Big Game Jackpot Hits $350 Million
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- People who wouldn't know a quick-pick from a scratch-off
ticket got a piece of the action in Tuesday night's Big Game lottery, swelling
the jackpot to $350 million -- the richest in U.S. history. Thomas Carter, a
clerk at the Quik Trip in Decatur, said his thumbs hurt from punching in so many
Big Game ticket requests for so many first-time lottery players Tuesday morning.
The numbers drawn were 1, 2, 12, 33, 37, Big Ball 4. Word on whether anyone held
a jackpot-winning ticket was expected Wednesday morning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Backs Bush, Nixes Sharing Ticket
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- While comparing the action to taking a dose of medicine,
Sen. John McCain Tuesday endorsed George W. Bush, his rival in the Republican
primaries. McCain said that he doesn't want to be Bush's running mate. Behind
their smiles, the strains from a bitter Republican primary fight were still
apparent. Even as McCain said he looked forward to ''enthusiastically
campaigning'' for the presumptive GOP nominee, the vanquished rival had to be
prompted before using the word ''endorse.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Navy Commandos Near Sierra Leone
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Navy has commandos aboard a patrol boat in the
waters off West Africa as a ''precautionary measure'' in light of the
intensifying crisis in Sierra Leone, a Pentagon spokesman said Tuesday. Kenneth
Bacon, spokesman for Defense Secretary William Cohen, said the Cyclone-class
patrol boat USS Thunderbolt was not directly off the coast of Sierra Leone but
was ''in the area and will remain there.'' In the last week, clashes have broken
out intermittently between United Nations' peacekeepers and rebels, with some
500 peacekeepers being held hostage.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Law Catches Up With Ex-Louisiana Gov.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Former Gov. Edwin Edwards, who was known for
nod-and-a-wink politics but always evaded prosecutors, was convicted for the
first time Tuesday, on charges he extorted hundreds of thousands of dollars from
businessmen applying for riverboat casino licenses. The former four-term
Democratic governor was found guilty along with his son Stephen of fraud and
racketeering. The scheme took place during Edwards' final term and after he left
office in 1996, when he still wielded considerable influence in Louisiana
politics.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Gets Support on China Trade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an extraordinary assembly of Republican and Democratic
administrations spanning three decades, former Presidents Ford and Carter closed
ranks Tuesday with President Clinton to push for a China trade deal that appears
increasingly likely to pass. ''We want the voice of this meeting to echo across
the country and to embrace the Congress,'' Clinton told more than 200 VIPs in
the chandeliered East Room. Two weeks before the House opens debate on granting
China permanent trade benefits, supporters of the proposal are optimistic about
winning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Koreas Continue To Discuss Summit Agenda
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The two Koreas have agreed to continue discussion
on the agenda and other details of a summit of their leaders through documents
instead of meetings, South Korean officials said Wednesday. The change came
after the two sides failed to iron out differences over the agenda and other
details of the summit at a fourth round of talks on their border on Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Wednesday with the Nikkei shedding 254.98
points to 17,589.56 in early trading. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 66.88 to 10,536.75.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees 4, Devil Rays 3, 10 Innings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Chuck Knoblauch, back in the lineup for the first time in
more than a week, doubled to set up Paul O'Neill's bases-loaded walk in the 10th
inning Tuesday night and the New York Yankees beat Tampa Bay 4-3. The Yankees
won for the eighth time in nine games. The Devil Rays have lost eight of 10.
Knoblauch had been sidelined since May 1 by a sprained left wrist, an injury he
originally sustained April 23 while swinging a weighted bat.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
