<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYC police commissioner has cancer  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- When Mayor Rudolph Giuliani made his
announcement less than two weeks ago that he has prostate cancer,
his good friend Police Commissioner Howard Safir was at his side
offering support.
</P>
<P>
   Little did the commissioner know that on Tuesday, the roles
would be reversed: Safir announced he has been diagnosed with the
disease while Giuliani and the commissioner's wife looked on.
</P>
<P>
   Safir, 58, learned of the diagnosis last week. He said his
condition is treatable. He also said he had no plans to step down
as commissioner but would take a day or two off when he needs to go
for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first thing that I asked my doctor is if I'm going to die
from this, and he said, 'No, you're not,' and I said, 'Good,'''
Safir recounted. ''It is curable, according to my doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Giuliani, Safir said his disease was detected at a ''very
early stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir underwent a routine physical a couple of weeks ago. A
blood test showed that his prostate specific antigen, or PSA,
levels were elevated, and he was told to go for follow-up tests,
which led to the diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   This is not Safir's first medical crisis since being appointed
commissioner in 1996. In March 1997, he underwent triple bypass
heart surgery but soon recovered and returned to work. He also
resumed the sports he's passionate for: in-line skating, kayaking
and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, he said he still takes part in those
activities and that he's in great shape otherwise. There is no
history of prostate cancer in his family.
</P>
<P>
   ''You ask yourself, 'Why me?' But life is not fair that way,''
Safir said. ''You just get along with it. It's just a bump in the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Safir, who embraced her husband as he spoke, said she was
''very upset'' when she learned of the diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I believe that the next month or so of treatment ... this
will be behind us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On April 27, Giuliani announced he has treatable prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At Safir's side on Tuesday, the mayor was upbeat about his
friend's prognosis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure Howard is going to be fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both men laughed when asked if maybe the water at City Hall is
tainted, since both were diagnosed with the same disease within
weeks. Safir is being treated at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer
Center, Giuliani at Mount Sinai Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the prostate, a gland involved in semen production, is
the second most common type of cancer found in American men. Early
detection greatly increases the chance of successful treatment.
About 179,300 men were diagnosed with the disease in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have survived prostate cancer are former Sen.
Bob Dole and New York Yankees manager Joe Torre. Treatments can
include removal of the prostate and/or radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Safir was appointed the city's 39th police commissioner by
Giuliani after a stint as fire commissioner. He had spent 26 years
in federal law enforcement, serving as operations chief of the U.S.
Marshals Service in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Safir replaced William Bratton, who resigned under pressure
after Giuliani ordered an investigation into trips Bratton took at
the expense of corporate honchos.
</P>
<P>
   Safir has served at a time when the New York Police Department
has been under intense scrutiny for the fatal police shooting of
Amadou Diallo in 1999 and the police torture of Abner Louima in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   And Safir himself seemed a lightning rod for controversy. Last
year, he took an all-expenses-paid trip to the Academy Awards
ceremony, courtesy of a Revlon executive friend, leaving town amid
the protests over Diallo's death.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscars trip prompted the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association
-- the union representing more than 26,000 police officers -- to
issue its first no-confidence vote against a commissioner. Safir
refused to quit and reiterated a statement he has made many times
during his tenure: ''Crime has gone down more under my stewardship
than any time in the history of this city. ... It is a safer
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir held a variety of positions in the Drug Enforcement
Administration from 1965 to 1979 before moving to the Marshals
Service. From 1979 to 1990, he headed the service's witness
security division and was a director of operations.
</P>
<P>
   He then formed his own security consulting firm, Safir
Associates. In 1994, the Bronx native returned to the city to serve
as fire commissioner under Giuliani, before moving on to the NYPD's
top job in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Safir graduated from Hofstra University in 1963 with a bachelor
of arts degree in history and political science and went on to
Brooklyn Law School. He and his wife have been married for 34
years. Besides their son, Adam, they have a daughter, Jennifer.
Both children are married.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
