<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Peacekeepers Retreat in S. Leone  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA ZAVIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Nerves in the capital of this
beleaguered West African nation were on edge today after word of a
retreat by U.N. peacekeepers and rumors about the whereabouts of
rebel leader Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers withdrew from Masiaka, 45 miles east of
Freetown, on Monday after exchanging gunfire with unknown attackers
and running out of ammunition, U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst said.
News of the retreat did not reach Freetown until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While rebels belonging to the Revolutionary United Front are
believed to be in the area, it was unclear if they were
responsible. Helicopter reconnaissance showed the city was
completely empty Tuesday afternoon. Hundreds of refugees from the
Masiaka area had reached the edge of Freetown by Tuesday, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Moseray, a civil servant, said he was worried because he
''heard that the rebels had attacked Masiaka, and Masiaka is so
close to the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the latest bad news, Wimhurst said: ''Freetown is not
going to fall to the RUF.''
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh had been under U.N. guard before Monday's shooting
outside his Freetown home. Sierra Leonean army soldiers, who under
a July peace plan are supposed to be disarmed, and fighters from
the pro-government Kamajor militia fought the rebels for hours at
Sankoh's home after a demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor mill had Sankoh anywhere from the Sierra Leonean
jungle to an army safehouse, but U.N. officials said they did not
know where he was.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are anxious to find a way to contact him,'' Wimhurst told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Sierra Leone has become increasingly chaotic
since a Nigerian-led regional intervention force pulled out last
week. Since then, clashes have broken out intermittently between
peacekeepers and rebels, and 500 peacekeepers are being held
hostage by the RUF. At least one peacekeeper is believed to be
dead.
</P>
<P>
   In Abuja, Nigeria, presidents from around the region met Tuesday
to try to defuse the crisis. They condemned the recent rebel moves
but fell short of ordering additional troops into Sierra Leone.
Instead, they called for a ministerial summit to be held next week
in Nigeria to discuss the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   A statement signed by nine presidents said they ''expressed
their determination to use all means at their disposal, including
the military option, to foil any attempt to take over power through
the use of force.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the United States had sent a ''fact-finding'' team
to Nigeria on Monday to assess what help the U.S. military might
provide if Nigeria or other African nations decide to augment their
peacekeeping role in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the United
States was not considering sending any combat troops to Sierra
Leone, but he confirmed news reports that the Clinton
administration has told the United Nations it is willing to provide
air transportation for a battalion of 700 to 800 peacekeepers from
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the United States might also help transport
additional peacekeepers from Jordan and India. He said it was not
yet clear what other kinds of military assistance the United States
might provide.
</P>
<P>
   ''Specifically, the types of help we will provide remain to be
determined because it depends on what the U.N. and the
international community, including the regional countries in West
Africa, decide to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a U.N. spokesman said three remaining battalions
appear ready to deploy by next week, which would bring the U.N.
force up to its full strength of 11,100.
</P>
<P>
   British helicopters, meanwhile, continued swooping into Freetown
on Tuesday, ferrying out frightened people.
</P>
<P>
   In London, a Ministry of Defense spokeswoman said 320 British,
European Union and Commonwealth citizens had been evacuated so far.
They were flown to Sierra Leone's main airport, and then most were
taken by airplane to Dakar, the capital of Senegal, U.N. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone, among the world's poorest countries despite vast
diamond resources, was brutalized during eight years of civil war,
which ended with a peace accord last July that created a
power-sharing government. In principle, that deal included the
rebels and Sankoh, whose forces killed and maimed thousands during
the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
