<HEADLINE> Farmers Hope Rain Improves Soil  </HEADLINE>
By KEN THOMAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- When Bill Radke talks to his neighbors
about the dry conditions this spring, one year keeps coming up --
1977.
</P>
<P>
   During that dry summer, Radke couldn't salvage his corn crop and
was only saved by a decent soybean crop. He says conditions have
been equally dry this spring, so arid that he decided to double his
crop insurance for the first time after nearly 40 years of farming.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains -- the first in weeks -- woke Radke and his wife early
this week, pounding his 820 acre farm in Van Meter with about one
inch of rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   ''That will help things get started,'' said Radke, 64, a farmer
since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa has experienced one of its driest planting seasons since
1989, raising concerns among farmers that it could hurt crop
yields.
</P>
<P>
   Recent rains moistened topsoil, but much of the state still lags
behind in precipitation totals.
</P>
<P>
   Sioux City, for example, is about 2 inches short of normal for
this time of year. Before the rains, both topsoil and subsoil
moisture were short or very short in more than 80 percent of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   State Climatologist Harry Hillaker said the weather has brought
the driest conditions in parts of central and northwest Iowa since
1977.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa has been averaging about one-third of an inch of rain each
week, well below the nearly 1 inch per week the state normally
gets. The clouds will need to release about 1\ inch to an 1{ inch
of rain to get soil conditions back to normal, Hillaker said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This time of year, they could still make some good progress
and get moisture in the ground before we get to full-time
summertime temperatures in the area,'' Hillaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Radke said dry conditions last August were cushioned by a moist
subsoil. Without much snow this winter and scant rainfall, he said
the intense heat of summer could hurt crop outputs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now we have no subsoil. If we get rains when we need it
... we'll get along until August comes,'' Radke said. ''When August
comes and we have no subsoil ... it will burn it up for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Strong domestic and international
competition may sour the Oregon strawberry and raspberry harvest
this year, but the outlook for blueberries and Marionberries is
sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   A flood of California strawberries already worries Oregon
growers and processors, said Roy Malensky of Oregon Berry Packing
in Hillsboro, a leader in the Oregon berry industry.
</P>
<P>
   California ''has so many strawberries they don't know what to do
with them,'' Malensky said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in the Oregon harvest is labor costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a difficult time competing with other states,''
Malensky said. ''The cost of labor in Oregon is comparable only to
Washington and Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the harvest and acreage has been shrinking
steadily.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1993, strawberry acreage in the state was about 6,200
acres. Now it's around 3,400 and dropping, Malensky said.
</P>
<P>
   Red raspberry acreage dropped from about 4,000 acres in 1992 to
about 3,000 and is still falling. Prices are low, along with
intense competition from Northern Washington, and from
high-yielding countries such as Hungary, Poland, Yugoslavia and
Chile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
