<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Crushes Competition In Ratings  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Four celebrity editions of ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' gave ABC its best week in the ratings since the Super
Bowl and a commanding lead in the important May ''sweeps'' period.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's average prime-time audience of 18.2 million people last
week easily outdistanced second-place CBS and its 11.6 million
viewers, Nielsen Media Research said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplishment came even though 3.5 million Time Warner
customers lost access to ABC on May 1 because of the cable
company's dispute with ABC's parent, the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity editions of ''Millionaire'' each drew an audience
of 34.6 million to 36 million. Last Wednesday's episode, where
longtime fan of the show Rosie O'Donnell won $500,000 for charity,
was the game show's most-watched episode ever.
</P>
<P>
   ABC beat NBC on Thursday night for the first time in a ratings
sweeps month since 1994. The victory came after ''Millionaire'' ran
eight minutes long, cutting in to the audience for NBC's ''ER,'' a
move that raised some eyebrows in the industry. An NBC spokeswoman
refused to comment on the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   A regular edition of ''Millionaire'' and ''The Practice'' also
beat two made-for-TV movies on rival networks Sunday. CBS could at
least brag that its ''Cupid and Cate'' movie was more popular than
the first part of NBC's miniseries, ''Jason and the Argonauts.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC saw another high-priced miniseries, ''The '70s,'' finish
fourth at the 9 p.m. hour on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had an 11.7 rating and 20 share for the week, with CBS at
8.2 and 14. NBC had 11.4 million viewers (8.1 rating, 14 share),
Fox had 7.4 million viewers (5.0, 8), UPN had 3.7 million (2.8, 5),
the WB had 3.2 million (2.4, 4) and Pax TV had 990,000 viewers
(0.7, 1).
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ''Nightly News'' and ABC's ''World News Tonight'' finished
in a virtual tie in the evening news ratings race. NBC had an
average of 10,000 more viewers (9.03 million viewers to 9.02
million), but ABC (7.0 rating, 16 share) bested NBC (6.9, 15) in
the ratings. The ''CBS Evening News'' had 7 million viewers (5.5,
12).
</P>
<P>
   A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show.
</P>
<P>
   For the week of May 1-7, the top 10 shows, their networks and
ratings were ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Tuesday), ABC,
23.6; ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Wednesday), ABC, 22.6;
''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (Monday), ABC, 22.5; ''Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire'' (Thursday), ABC, 22.1; ''ER,'' NBC, 18.0; ''Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Sunday), ABC, 17.1; ''The Practice,''
ABC, 14.1; ''Friends,'' NBC, 13.7; ''20/20 Downtown,'' ABC, 13.5;
''Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' ABC, 12.9; ''Friends'' special, NBC, 12.9.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nielsenmedia.com
</P>
</TEXT>
