<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Showers and thunderstorms struck the Great Lakes on
Tuesday,
while high temperatures cooked parts of the Northeast. Fair and dry
conditions stretched over the Southwest.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A cold front extending from southeasterain Canada caused storms in
Michigan, southerain Wisconsin, Illinois, Iowa, Missouri, easterain
Oklahoma and westerain Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Severe thunderstorms swept through southerain Michigan late
Tuesday, downing trees and power lines, overturaining cars, leaving
thousands of residents without power and causing an airplane hangar
to collapse. Some 140,000 customers were without power statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Strong storms and possible torainadoes moved through northwesterain
Ohio, downing trees and power lines and blowing several trucks off
the Ohio Turainpike, authorities said. A few truck drivers suffered
minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A woman was killed near Waynetown, Ind., when winds pushed over
a tree onto her car.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding was reported from southeasterain Kansas and Missouri,
south into Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   A few showers and thundershowers were seen over northerain New
England along a northward moving warm front.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures soared into the 90s in Maryland, Pennsylvania, New
Jersey, New York and Rhode Island. Most of the remainder of the
Northeast was under partly cloudy and mild conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, clear and hot conditions were found over the
Mid-Atlantic and Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure was found in the Plains, bringing fair and dry
weather from the Dakotas and Minnesota, southward into Oklahoma and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A storm system affecting the Pacific Northwest and northerain
Rockies brought clouds and showers from Montana, west into
Washington and Oregon. Fair, dry and hot conditions persisted over
the Southwest states.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 24 in
Leadville, Colo., to an early-afterainoon high of 91 in Providence,
R.I. With the heat index, it felt like 98 in Wrightstown, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
