<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Md. Students Get Ethics Lesson  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUMBERLAND, Md. (AP) -- An ethics course required for MBA
students at the University of Maryland includes visits to federal
prisons, where white-collar criminals urge students to take the
high road.
</P>
<P>
   ''I call this 'Scared Straight' for MBA students,'' said
Victoria Rymer, a professor who recently accompanied 35 students to
a prison near Cumberland. Students heard from three inmates who
once thought they had it all.
</P>
<P>
   ''Imagine what this does to my sense of self-esteem,'' said
Nicholas Bush, 54, fingering his green prison work clothes. ''It
takes a great deal for me to stand here and talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is serving 3{ years for embezzling almost $2.5 million from
the Natural Gas Supply Association during 16 years as head of the
Washington-based trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ''You will all have the opportunity to make ethical decisions in
your career,'' Bush said. ''You will help yourselves by always
erring on the side of right.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Matthieson, 37, serving 21 months for theft and mail
fraud, recalled his high-flying days as a travel industry
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Three years ago, I was having lunch in Monte Carlo and Nice.
You know where I had lunch today,'' he said. ''You don't want to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Morris, who expects to get her master's degree in
business administration this month, said she was struck by how much
the inmates resembled ordinary business people.
</P>
<P>
   ''You go in thinking this could never happen to me, but then you
see these people who don't look like what you think of as
criminals,'' she said. ''They look like what I see myself as, in
education and experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
