<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kennedy May Not Have GOP Challenger  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE LeBLANC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Massachusetts Republicans could be on the verge of
a political milestone but none of the party faithful are
celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1916, the year United States senators
began being popularly elected, a Massachusetts Democrat faces the
possibility of a campaign without a Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Jack E. Robinson had hoped to be the Republican to take on Sen.
Edward Kennedy in November.
</P>
<P>
   But by 5 p.m. Tuesday, the deadline to turn in 10,000 signatures
needed to get his name on the ballot, Robinson was well short. He
had submitted at least 5,122 signatures, Secretary of State William
Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   That number could increase, because not all towns are connected
to the state computer system that tracks the signatures, Galvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson planned to announce today that he had collected well
over 10,000 signatures, the Boston Herald reported.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson -- a young, black Republican and former Eastern Airlines
executive now running a cellular phone business -- also is
struggling to regain the backing of his party's leaders, including
Gov. Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   Some top state Republicans withdrew their endorsements in March
after the 39-year-old political neophyte released a detailed
11-page personal history. In it, Robinson outlined a drunken
driving arrest -- he was eventually cleared -- and a relationship
with a girlfriend who took out a restraining order against him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still think there's some pretty big questions he's left
unanswered,'' Cellucci said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Since releasing the so-called ''Robinson Report,'' the candidate
has kept a low profile, but vowed to fight on without the help of
the party.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his popularity among Massachusetts voters, Kennedy has
faced a Republican foe in every campaign since he was first elected
to the Senate seat that had been held by his brother John F.
Kennedy. Each time -- in 1964, 1970, 1976, 1982, 1988 and 1994 --
Kennedy fended off those challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy faced his toughest re-election battle in 1994, against
wealthy Republican businessman Mitt Romney. Early polls showed the
two in a virtual tie, but Kennedy ended up winning, 58 percent to
41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A Kennedy aide declined comment on Robinson's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Election Commission reports for the period between
January and March show Kennedy had more than $3.7 million on hand.
Robinson has so far loaned his campaign $39,000 and spent all but
$600.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier GOP challenger, Plymouth County District Attorney
Michael Sullivan, bowed out of the race, citing satisfaction with
his current job and his desire to spend time with his four
school-age children.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Robinson, Kennedy may not be alone on the November
ballot. Carla Howell, a candidate for the Libertarian Party, and
Philip Lawler, a candidate for the Constitution Party, are running.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Robinson campaign site: http://www.robinson2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy campaign site: http://www.kennedy200.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
