<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Seeking New Chapter With UN  </HEADLINE>
By DAFNA LINZER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- After years of isolation and strain,
Israel is hoping that its compliance with a 22-year-old U.N.
resolution to withdraw from Lebanese soil will help warm ties with
the world body that gave it life.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's ambassador to the United Nations, Yehuda Lankry, told
The Associated Press that Israel has been enjoying rare cooperation
with the United Nations in preparation for a pullout by July.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has yet to comply with other U.N. resolutions calling for
it to withdraw from additional war-won territories, but Lankry said
Israel's acceptance of the Lebanon resolution was a good first step
in improving relations.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's foreign minister arrives in New York on Friday for
talks with U.N. officials on the future role of peacekeepers in
southern Lebanon. And Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
the subject was high on the agenda during talks she held with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Israel wants the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon, or
UNIFIL, to do more than take up the reins when Israel vacates this
summer after an 18-year presence there.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expect that after Israel implements its withdrawal from
south Lebanon, that UNIFIL will help to restore Lebanese
sovereignty and to ensure a situation of stability,'' Lankry said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, after Israel first entered Lebanese territory to drive
back guerrillas from the border, the Security Council passed
resolution 425 calling for its withdrawal and for the establishment
of a U.N. peacekeeping force to confirm the withdrawal, restore
peace to the region and help the Lebanese government regain its
authority in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Israel briefly withdrew but invaded Lebanon again in 1982 to
oust the PLO. Three years later, it pulled back to a southern strip
it has patrolled ever since to prevent cross-border attacks on its
northern communities.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, Israel has often found itself alone,
supported only by the United States, when facing dozens of Arab and
Muslim states. It has been a difficult relationship that both sides
say they would like to change.
</P>
<P>
   Annan has been outspoken in his criticism of member states who
continue to block Israel from taking part in U.N. groupings and
committees. Those actions and others ''have given a regrettable
impression of bias and one-sidedness,'' he said last December.
</P>
<P>
   It was upon the ashes of the Holocaust, when Europe's Jews were
nearly wiped out by Nazi Germany in World War II, that the United
Nations voted in 1947 to carve out a homeland for the Jews in
Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   In its younger years, Israel was an active member of the United
Nations. But after its victories in the 1967 and 1973 wars, a
coalition of developing nations in the Mideast, Africa and Asia
began concerted attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the General Assembly voted to equate Zionism with
racism, a move that all but shattered relations. Nine years ago it
was repealed but ''even so, deep and painful scars remain,'' for
both sides, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   Lankry believes relations with the world body are finally
starting to heal. He was hesitant to link Israel's proposed entry
into a grouping of mostly West European nations at the United
Nations with its acceptance of the Lebanon resolution. But
''psychologically, it helps,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a new chapter with the United Nations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there were signs that Israel was looking to the United
Nations in ways it had not before. Lankry credited Annan and the
new U.N. envoy to the region, Terje Roed-Larsen, for stepping in --
at Israel's request -- during fighting last week between Israel and
Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''The U.N. was immediately instrumental in exploiting the fact
that Larsen was in the area and was able to reach the Lebanese and
the Syrians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Close cooperation has been rather rare,'' he added, ''so we
are very satisfied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0121 </TRAILER>
