<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush To Propose Nursing Home Bill  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Iowa (AP) -- Returning to the state that delivered his
first presidential victory, Republican George W. Bush was
continuing his move onto traditionally Democratic turf by proposing
tax incentives to buy insurance for nursing home care and financial
relief for people who care for a parent or elderly person at home.
</P>
<P>
   The two ideas, being unveiled today, were fueled by statistics
showing that half of older women and one-third of older men are
likely to need nursing home care. A cost estimate was not provided.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today a person goes into a nursing home and a lifetime of
savings can be gone in an instant,'' Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes
said Tuesday, offering the general outlines of the presumptive GOP
presidential nominee's speech at the Ridgecrest Village Senior
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Bush wants to encourage people to prepare for that by
buying insurance,'' she added. ''He will also recognize the
financial burden on those who provide care at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost five months after winning the Iowa caucuses, Bush's
speech marked the beginning of a series of addresses on improving
families' financial security, part of a plan by the Texas governor
to undercut traditionally Democratic themes like social welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Since besting Arizona Sen. John McCain for the nomination in
mid-March, Bush has offered an array of proposals for improving
schools, protecting teachers, encouraging savings by low-income
families and making housing more affordable for them. Some of the
proposals have been accompanied by significant new spending. For
others, Bush has relied on tax incentives and other lures so that
individuals or private industry -- not the government -- achieve his
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential rival Al Gore, meanwhile, supports the
Clinton-Gore administration's proposal to give a $1,000 tax credit
to some 2 million families caring for ill or disabled relatives,
and to expand Medicaid to cover in-home and community-based long
term care services that would help keep people out of expensive
nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech today was to be a follow-up to the most widely
anticipated component of his family security package: plans for
reforming Social Security. The main component would allow younger
workers to invest a portion of their Social Security payroll taxes
as they choose.
</P>
<P>
   He was to have given that speech on Monday, but postponed it to
attend the funeral of New York's Cardinal John O'Connor. It has
been rescheduled for May 15 in Los Angeles. Two days later in
Seattle, Bush plans a major address on trade.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush began with a 90-minute summit in Pittsburgh
with McCain, where the Arizona senator endorsed his former
presidential opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush later said he hoped McCain would campaign for Republicans
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there are two really good roles for John. One is to
campaign with me, and I'd appreciate that. But the other role is
for John to campaign for members of the United States Congress,''
Bush said on CNN's ''Larry King Live.'' ''I think it's important to
have a Congress ... with which I can work. And I think John's
willing to do both.''
</P>
<P>
   From Pittsburgh, Bush headed for an education discussion at High
Point Elementary School in Atlanta. One of the most diverse schools
in the Fulton County system, more than 30 percent of its students
are served by English-as-a-second-language programs.
</P>
<P>
   He participated in a round-table discussion with the principal
and several teachers next to a campaign banner that said: ''No
child left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Hailing the school, Bush said: ''It's important for America to
hear that the best school reforms bubble from the bottom up.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he attended a private reception with guests who have
raised or pledged to raise $100,000 for the Republican National
Committee or the Georgia Republican Party. In Pittsburgh on Monday,
Bush helped raise $800,000 to $1 million on behalf of the national
and state parties.
</P>
<P>
   He was returning home to Texas after visiting Iowa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0128 </TRAILER>
