<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Defends China Trade Deal  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore, who's been something of a stealth
supporter of the proposed trade deal with China, has finally flown
a few sorties visible on everyone's radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   With a tough House vote on the deal two weeks away, the
Democratic presidential candidate on Tuesday gave his most robust
defense yet of the deal to give China normal trading status on a
permanent basis, despite the fierce opposition of unions,
environmentalists and human rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is right for American jobs,'' the vice president declared
as President Clinton, two former presidents and a bipartisan group
of dignitaries looked on at the White House. ''It is right for the
cause of reform in China and I believe it will move us closer to
the strong and stable world community that we all seek to create.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, questions remain about whether his heart is in the
effort, and whether a Gore administration would do much to expand
free trade. ''I don't think he's motivated on this,'' says Gary
Hufbauer, an economist who backs lowered trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Republican rival George W. Bush agree at least
theoretically that free trade deals have been good for America and
that more should be negotiated. Their main opponents in the
primaries, Bill Bradley and John McCain, felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   So has a seamless succession of presidents, as the notion of a
North American Free Trade Agreement promoted by Ronald Reagan was
handed off to Bush's father to build and then, across party lines,
to Clinton to complete. Former presidents Ford and Carter joined
Clinton and Gore at the White House on Tuesday to add their weight
to the fight for congressional approval of the China deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the presidential campaign, third-party candidates Pat
Buchanan of the Reform Party and Ralph Nader of the Green Party
have been lone voices against the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement before Congress would end the congressional review
now required to renew China's trading status from year to year.
Congress must grant China permanent normal trade relations in order
for U.S. exporters to receive the market-opening benefits China is
offering to get into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, exhorting Americans to choose ''between the politics of
fear and the politics of hope,'' Gore took on Reform Party founder
Ross Perot and his charts in a debate performance judged so
effective that hopes for NAFTA's passage instantly soared and the
Mexican stock market hit record highs the next day.
</P>
<P>
   But on China, with an eye on constituencies important to him in
the presidential election, Gore has been practicing the politics of
caution.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting congressional Democrats just as a divided Congress was
preparing to take up the China agreement, he avoided discord by
avoiding the subject.
</P>
<P>
   He says he's called members of Congress to urge them to support
the deal but his campaign staff repeatedly has declined to identify
them or say how many he's contacted. A meeting with labor leaders
earlier this year raised questions about his commitment to the
agreement; he said later he was fully behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's trying to have it both ways,'' said Hufbauer, of the
Institute for International Economics. ''I see him as a very
low-energy pusher of this agenda. I think his compass is pointed
momentarily for the benefit of White House harmony on the issue,
and his real instincts are elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's remarks at the White House followed similar comments, in
response to questions, a day earlier at an Associated Press meeting
of newspaper publishers and editors. As well, he denounced trade
protectionism in a recent foreign policy speech that summoned some
of the free-trade passions of his past.
</P>
<P>
   His most common refrain, however, has been that he supports
''free and fair trade,'' a combination that offends no one because
it depends entirely on how ''fair'' is defined.
</P>
<P>
   The unions mounting a massive campaign to defeat the coming
House vote define fair to mean, in part, the maintenance of stiff
anti-dumping laws to keep underpriced imports from killing U.S.
manufacturing jobs. Critics also want U.S. trading partners
subjected to labor, environmental and human rights safeguards
missing in liberalized trade agreements worked out by the Clinton
administration so far.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Dave Obey of Wisconsin, an opponent of the China
deal, accused organized labor of employing a ''strategic double
standard'' -- going easy on Gore while running ads attacking the
Democratic members of Congress who agree with the vice president on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's disappointing that while refraining from criticizing the
general, they are too willing to beat up on the infantry,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0128 </TRAILER>
