<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Shakes Up 2004 Olympic Panel  </HEADLINE>
By ELENA BECATOROS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- The woman who led Greece's winning bid for
the 2004 Olympics is being asked to reorganize the troubled
organizing committee after it was criticized for delays and
stagnant bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   The move to bring back Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki was the
first bold step by Greek officials trying to restore international
confidence in Athens' ability to stage a successful modern games.
She is the first woman to head an Olympic organizing team.
</P>
<P>
   International Olympic Committee President Juan Antonio
Samaranch, who last month slammed Athens for falling behind in
planning, called the appointment ''a turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The IOC is very, very pleased,'' Samaranch told The Associated
Press from Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's pointman for Athens' preparations was equally positive
over the decision to bring back the 44-year-old lawyer to replace
central banker Panagiotis Thomopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am very glad,'' Jacques Rogge, the head of the IOC panel
overseeing the Athens Olympics, told the AP.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's an intelligent, energetic woman, and I'm quite sure she
will give the Athens organizing committee the momentum and dynamism
that is needed,'' said Rogge, who is in Athens for an inspection
visit later this week with other IOC envoys.
</P>
<P>
   Her public relations savvy and determination was considered
instrumental in Athens' successful bid after the bitter 1996 loss
to Atlanta. For the 2004 games, Athens faced strong competition
from Rome and Cape Town. Athens played host to the first modern
Olympiad in 1896.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has always been a big supporter of
Angelopoulos-Daskalaki. In 1997, Samaranch expressed hope that she
would lead the organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now she is the president -- finally,'' Samaranch said. ''She is
the right person for me. She is a great leader. She always has the
right people around her. She did a wonderful job during the Athens
bid.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Samaranch blasted Athens for organizational problems
and delays that he said could jeopardize the games. He urged
''drastic action'' to rectify problems in accommodation, traffic,
security, communications, construction, venues and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Thomopoulos offered his resignation after Greece's April 9
parliamentary elections, saying he was unable to devote his time to
the Olympics due to his role as deputy governor of the Bank of
Greece. It was widely rumored that the government would turn to
Angelopoulos-Daskalaki, wife of a multimillionaire Greek
industrialist.
</P>
<P>
   Angelopoulos-Daskalaki reportedly turned down a post on the
committee after Athens was awarded the games in 1997 because the
government would not guarantee her wide autonomy to build her own
organizational team. Since then, she has been serving as the
country's ambassador-at-large reporting directly to the premier and
the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   While maintaining a distance from all preparations after 1997,
she broke a long silence last month in an interview with a Greek
television station, offering to help organizers put preparations
back on track.
</P>
<P>
   She is the third person to be appointed to lead preparations for
the games since early 1998. The first committee leader, Stratis
Stratigis, stepped down in July 1999 after an uneasy 18-month
tenure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0134 </TRAILER>
