<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preparation for Hurricane Season  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Like a football team that had a couple rough
games the year before, the nation's weather forecasters are facing
the upcoming hurricane season with a new quarterback, new equipment
and an improving record.
</P>
<P>
   If the nation's top long-range hurricane forecaster is right,
they'll get plenty of chances to test their mettle.
</P>
<P>
   The official hurricane season gets under way June 1 and leaders
of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the
Federal Emergency Management Agency were holding a briefing today
to discuss the outlook and potential impacts on the country.
</P>
<P>
   That session was to include the man likely to become a familiar
fixture on Americans television screens when storms threaten, Max
Mayfield, the new director of the National Hurricane Center in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, who was named last week to replace Jerry Jarrell, will
have a new eye in the sky to help him quarterback the forecast
team.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a new weather satellite was launched that can be
pressed into service this summer if needed. The $220 million GOES-L
satellite had been delayed a year.
</P>
<P>
   The forecasters rely on two Geostationary Operational
Environmental Satellites to monitor tropical storms and other
severe weather. The East Coast's GOES-8, however, is a year beyond
its design lifetime. Although still working, it could break down at
any moment. GOES-L is a crucial backup.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gray of Colorado State University, one of the few willing
to make long-range storm predictions, says the increased storm
activity over the last five years should continue, perhaps for the
next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, Gray has predicted 11 named storms, including seven
hurricanes, three of them major, meaning they have sustained winds
of 110 miles per hour or more.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Gray predicted 14 named storms and said he expected
nine of them to become hurricanes and four of to be classified as
major. Her was close: There were 12 named storms, eight became
hurricanes and five ranked as major.
</P>
<P>
   Gray has been studying hurricane patterns in history and says
the trend of more and fewer storms is cyclical and not related to
pollution or global warming.
</P>
<P>
   A major difference between now and the busy storm period in the
early part of this century, Gray observed, is that many more people
now live in harm's way. According to Census figures, the population
in Gulf and Atlantic coast states from Texas to Virginia rose from
a little more than 24 million in 1930 to about 64 million in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three decades forecasters have gotten better at
predicting where the storms will go, researchers Colin McAdie and
Miles Lawrence report in the May issue of the Bulletin of the
American Meteorological Society.
</P>
<P>
   They found that from 1970 to 1998 track forecast errors
decreased by about 1 percent per year for the 24-hour forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ''On a yearly basis, it's a small improvement, but one that
yields a cumulative benefit,'' said McAdie, a research
meteorologist at NOAA's Tropical Prediction Center in Miami. ''The
24 hour forecast error expected 30 years ago of about 140 miles has
been reduced to about 100 miles today.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters and emergency managers hope to avoid a repeat of the
destruction from last year's Hurricane Floyd, which inundated North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The storm wavered along the coast, seeming to tease forecasters,
leading to the evacuation of thousands in Florida, Georgia and the
Carolinas along roads that became jammed with traffic.
</P>
<P>
   When Floyd finally came ashore it lingered, pouring out
record-setting rains that resulted in more than 50 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials and local agencies were unprepared for many of
the problems, the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention said in a report.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said two-thirds of the deaths were drownings, mostly
from cars swept away by the floodwaters. Others died in car
crashes, heart attacks and fires. Seven people died in capsized
boats and five rescue workers lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
   When comparing the weeks after the hurricane to the same period
the previous year, the CDC found that hypothermia, carbon monoxide
poisonings, dog bites, violent crimes, diarrhea and asthma cases
were all up significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration:
http://www.noaa.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov
</P>
<P>
   Gray's Colorado State site:
http://tropical.atmos.colostate.edu/forecasts
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0136 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U. S. Playing Hockey Russian Style  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA BULMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia (AP) -- Even if the star-studded host team
made its earliest exit from the World Hockey Championships,
Russia's hockey style still survives in every team left in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, while the Finnish, Swedish, Latvian teams have always
reflected the influence of the Russian or Soviet hockey culture,
this year's American team integrates it even more visibly.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, a team half stocked with NHL workmen and the
rest scavenged from European pro, minor and college leagues, has
been a surprise from the start with its organized, disciplined play
and controlled passing game.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Americans have looked more Russian than the
Russians did.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Lou Vairo has combined NHL-like intensity with the Russian
style of skating, passing and reading the game.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on a blend of youth and experience, the underdog
Americans generated an unusual sort of chemistry, which has
resulted in an unbeaten record (3-0-2) and an unexpected place in
the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts, billed as the ''Dream Team'' of the tournament and
stacked with 14 NHL stars -- including the NHL's leading goal
scorer, Pavel Bure, and Alexei Yashin -- were simply unable to get
off the ground. The Russians absorbed four defeats and just one
victory over a weak France before finally beating Sweden 4-2 in
their final appearance at the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking the time-tested qualities of Russian hockey such as
spirit, excellent strategy and team chemistry, the host team was
derided following it 3-0 defeat to the United States and 3-2 loss
to lightweight Switzerland in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians were further scorned following their 3-2 loss to
tiny Latvia and their subsequent elimination from medal contention,
before sinking even further with their 1-0 fall to Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   Vairo is familiar with Russian hockey through his close
friendship with the late coaching great Anatoli Tarasov, who guided
the Soviet team for 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   Under Tarasov's leadership, the Soviet national team won gold at
every world championship from 1962-71. His teams also won the 1964,
1968 and 1972 Olympics. More than 30 hockey players from different
Tarasov teams have won Olympic and world gold medals
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Tarasov) felt players should be specialists, individually
outstanding at their specific job. That goes for forwards,
defensemen and goalies,'' said Vairo. ''He talked about raising
their level, making the game more fascinating by using individual
abilities to be creative, because you could only skate so fast and
shoot so hard. There are physical limits.
</P>
<P>
   ''He believed there were other countries gaining on Russia
especially the Czechs, and he believed Sweden was real close,''
Vairo added. ''Tarasov thought the U.S. could be a world power in
hockey with our facilities and population if we could get more of
our top athletes to play the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Vairo said the United States had a long way to go to even come
close reaching the level of Russian hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our hockey is recreational, by and large,'' explained Vairo,
who worked behind the U.S. bench at the 1984 Olympics in Sarajevo.
''We're at a huge disadvantage internationally compared to the
Europeans, who have a club system.
</P>
<P>
   ''Young players come, try out, get selected and the kids that
don't get selected have to find someplace to play,'' he said.
''Kids start at seven, eight, nine years old, whereas in the United
States you pay to play hockey and many start too old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0136 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
