<DOCNO> APW20000510.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Back to the golf course for losing plaintiff  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Nancy Saunders was back on the links, giving her
all for the Westchester Country Club's women's golf team, just
hours after losing her 11-year battle to prove illegal sex
discrimination at the swanky private club.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if golfing helped ease the disappointment, she said, ''I
wouldn't read too much into it. Golfing is what I would be doing
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief administrative law judge at the state Human Rights
Division, James T. King, agreed Tuesday that Saunders had been
discriminated against ''solely because of her gender.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said she had to sue within a year after becoming aware of
it -- by 1986 at the latest. Saunders sued in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also found that state human rights laws did not apply
to the club before 1994 because it was ''distinctly private.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saunders' lawyer is crying foul because the judge who issued
the decision is not the judge who heard the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something's wrong here,'' said attorney Susan Slavin.
''Where's the judge who tried the case? This is an absolutely
devastating decision, it is a tragedy, and it bears no resemblance
to what took place at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decision -- actually a recommendation to state Human
Rights Commissioner Jerome Blue -- King said Saunders should have
filed her suit within a year of joining the club or within a year
of when the club allegedly terminated her membership in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that although the club is the host for the PGA
Tour's Buick Classic, it is not ''a place of public accommodation''
that would have been subject to the human rights law before 1994,
the period covered by the suit.
</P>
<P>
   King also ruled that Saunders' claim of retaliation by the club
against her husband was not proven.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders' lawyer said she would object to the recommendations
within the 21 days provided and would appeal the case if the
commissioner accepted them.
</P>
<P>
   ''This decision was not rendered by a judge who sat and observed
the demeanor of the witnesses and the credibility of the
witnesses,'' she said. ''You can't tell from a cold record whether
somebody is truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge who conducted the hearings last fall, Denise
Washington, was dismissed in January. She said it was because she
testified in federal court that the Human Rights Division needed 25
to 30 more judges to cut into a six-year backlog of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Ellison, spokeswoman for the division, said it is
''within our authority and jurisdiction'' to assign a new judge to
a case.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders, 50, testified at the hearings that from the time she
joined the club in Harrison in 1982, she was barred, as a woman,
from the club's prestigious West Course for long stretches of time
each Wednesday, Friday, Saturday and Sunday. She also could not get
into the Men's Grill, which she said cost her business
opportunities. And when she married a fellow member, she claimed,
the club ended her membership on the ground that the husband is
always the member.
</P>
<P>
   The club now charges $45,000 for initiation fees and $5,500 a
year for dues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm disappointed because I still believe in this, and I know
what happened,'' said Saunders, who lives in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Miller, president of the club, said the club ''does not
discriminate against people by gender, race, religion or in any
other manner.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a real vindication,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-10-00 0137 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson Doing His Job For Pacers  </HEADLINE>
By HANK LOWENKRON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Mark Jackson, never recognized as a
tenacious defender in a 13-year NBA career, is answering the
skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is being asked to guard Allen Iverson, the league's
second-leading scorer this season, in the Eastern Conference
semifinals. Jackson's defense, in addition to his often uncanny
passing ability, are big reasons the Indiana Pacers were heading
into tonight's game at Philadelphia with a 2-0 advantage in the
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's an underrated defensive player,'' teammate Jalen Rose
said. ''Nobody talks about Mark being a great defender. He'll tell
you that he's not, but he's doing what we need him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson has scored 56 points in the two games, but he's taken 45
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just trying to work. People are going to say a bunch of
things. I don't pay attention to that. I have a heart just as big
as anyone else and I try to fill it with a will to win,'' said
Jackson, who has scored only seven points and is 3-for-17 from the
field in the two games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with 24 assists and three turnovers in two games, he's
been valuable to Indiana offensively as the Pacers head into
tonight's game two victories short of making their fifth trip to
the conference finals in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly, I don't worry about my points. We've got plenty of
guys who can score. Me getting them the ball for an open shot is
what being a point guard is all about,'' Jackson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I get points, that's a bonus. That has been lost in this
day and time. My job is to distribute the ball and be an extension
of the coach on the court, control the tempo, and I feel
comfortable with what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers have jumped off to big leads in both games to get
into position to sweep the 76ers for a second consecutive year in
the conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had six assists in the opening quarter of Game 1, when
Indiana shot 67 percent in the period to take 34-15 lead. In the
first quarter of Monday night's Game 2, Jackson had eight assists
as Indiana shot 68 percent in the period and took a lead it never
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Travis Best, who share the point guard role, have
combined for 31 assists with only four turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our second unit is more of a transition, running up and down,
and that's Travis' game,'' Reggie Miller said. ''The first unit,
since we're a little bit older, our execution is probably our top
priority, and that's where Mark is more efficient. It's a good
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana has won three straight playoff games, including a 96-95
squeaker against Milwaukee in Game 5 of the first round. In those
three games, Jackson has 32 assists and just three turnovers. Best
had 13 assists, four steals and only one turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's doing his job. That's what he's known for, running the
team, especially in the half-court offense. He's done a great job
as far as assists to turnovers,'' Austin Croshere said of Jackson.
''In the post, he looks to himself as a decoy to get a double-team
going and then he swings the ball to find guys for open shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose has been a major beneficiary of Jackson's precision passes,
scoring 70 points in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mark is doing a great job of distributing the ball,'' Rose
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0137 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
