<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blackhawks Looking for Head Coach  </HEADLINE>
By JIM PAUL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Launching a search for a coach has become as
common to the Chicago Blackhawks as missing the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks, who have failed to reach the postseason the last
three years, fired Lorne Molleken on Tuesday. The team has had four
coaches over the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked myself, 'Do I have the confidence that Lorne would get
us into the playoffs next year as head coach?''' general manager
Mike Smith said at a United Center news conference. ''That answer
was 'I don't know.' To me, that wasn't decisive enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Molleken wasn't present when the announcement was made and was
not available for comment. Smith said Molleken took the news ''with
a lot of class.''
</P>
<P>
   The former coach denied the opportunity to stay with the team
and speak with his replacement about a job on the new coaching
staff. Interim coach Bob Pulford will return to his senior vice
president role and will not be back behind the bench next season.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he has a ''short list'' of candidates. He would not
identify any candidates and said none are involved with teams still
alive in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to have been a head coach,'' Smith said of what
he's looking for in a new coach. ''I also think it's important to
have worked in the NHL and worked with NHL players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks fired Craig Hartsburg after missing the playoffs
in 1998 for the first time since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Graham replaced Hartsburg, but he was fired midway through
the next season. Molleken was named interim coach and earned the
job by leading the Hawks to a 13-6-4 finish.
</P>
<P>
   That finish sparked optimism heading into this season, but hopes
were dashed when the Blackhawks struggled to a 5-14-4 record in
October and November. The sluggish start triggered a shakeup that
saw general manager Bob Murray lose his job on Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Murray was replaced by Pulford, who also took over as head
coach, demoting Molleken to associate coach.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, Smith was hired by owner William Wirtz. Pulford
retained the general manager title, but Smith was given the task of
rebuilding the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks improved after the changes but still finished
33-39-10 with 78 points, 11th out of the 13-team Western
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he wants to hire a new coach within the next two to
four weeks. He did not rule out other changes before next season,
both on the ice and off.
</P>
<P>
   ''Coaching is part of it but it's not the only part of it,''
Smith said. ''Things really do in fact need to be operated
differently here.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackhawks vice president Peter J. Wirtz, the owner's son, said
hiring a new coach is entirely in Smith's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mike knows what we need, and we're going to back his
decisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
