<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mets 2, Pirates 0  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- New York Mets starter Mike Hampton's wrist had
the imprint of a baseball. His knee was bruised from a collision on
the bases. His shoulder was packed in ice to minimize the wear and
tear of throwing 126 pitches in a close game.
</P>
<P>
   And all Hampton could talk about was how comfortable he felt.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (3-4) had his best outing of the season as he held the
Pittsburgh Pirates to six hits in 8 1-3 innings, helping the Mets
to a 2-0 win Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton said he discarded all the baggage that dragged him down
in the first month of the season. The left-hander was acquired from
the Houston Astros last winter to be the Mets' No. 1 starter, and
he hadn't looked much like one until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's adjustments you have to make throughout a season and
throughout a career,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   He was reminded of that over the weekend when Hall of Famer Tom
Seaver, a Mets broadcaster and occasional instructor, had a
15-minute talk with Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told me that some of the greatest pitchers in the world
have had this,'' Hampton said. ''You have to go out there, focus,
concentrate and relax. That's the biggest thing. There are ups and
downs and for me there was a big down period. You have to shorten
those, go out and make pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's biggest inning was the fifth, when the Pirates got
runners at second and third with nobody out and didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton used a strikeout and two ground balls to escape the jam.
The last grounder was a sharply hit comebacker than caught Hampton
on his wrist. His hand went numb, and he threw to first base on a
bounce.
</P>
<P>
   Mets manager Bobby Valentine said the ball struck hard enough to
leave the imprint of its seams on Hampton's wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hit me flush,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   In the same inning, Hampton tagged out 240-pound Pirates first
baseman Kevin Young in a rundown after a football-like collision.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why Hampton is one of my favorites,'' Young said.
''He's such a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton got all the offensive support he needed in the third
inning when Edgardo Alfonzo and Derek Bell homered on consecutive
pitches from Kris Benson (2-4).
</P>
<P>
   ''Kris was outstanding,'' Pirates manager Gene Lamont said.
''The stuff he had was good enough to win most games. He just
happened to run into a guy who pitched an outstanding game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton knows now his challenge is to build on Tuesday's start
and become the kind of solid pitcher the Mets thought he'd be when
they traded for him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It felt good, and I like the feeling,'' Hampton said. ''I want
to do what it takes to continue this. Just go out there and
execute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
