<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees 4, Devil Rays 3, 10 Innings  </HEADLINE>
By BEN WALKER, AP Baseball Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Told by manager Joe Torre that he would start,
Chuck Knoblauch's face lit up.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch eagerly joined his teammates in a pregame jog, joked
with Derek Jeter in the batting cage and playfully slapped the ball
away from Scott Brosius as he bounded around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a lot of energy after not playing for a week,''
Knoblauch said.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing for the New York Yankees he saved some of it for
Tuesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the lineup after missing more than a week because of a
sprained left wrist, Knoblauch doubled to set up a bases-loaded
walk to Paul O'Neill in the 10th inning that lifted the Yankees
over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're never amazed around here because things like that keep
happening,'' Knoblauch said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won for the eighth time in nine games. The Devil
Rays have lost three in a row and eight of 10.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was saying before the game that hopefully I'd get in the box
and it would click. I was glad to get in there and not mess
anything up and keep the winning going,'' he said. ''I was lucky, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius drew a one-out walk from Rick White (0-2) in the 10th
and Knoblauch blooped an opposite-field double that bounced into
the right-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   ''It actually jammed me a little bit, but I put it in the right
spot,'' Knoblauch said.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch originally hurt himself April 23 at Toronto while
swinging a weighted bat, then re-injured his wrist last week at
Cleveland. The leadoff man went 2-for-5 in his return, and was
flawless in six chances at second base.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt all right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After an intentional walk to Derek Jeter, Jim Morris relieved
White. O'Neill walked on four pitches to force home the winning
run.
</P>
<P>
   ''They brought in a lefty to get a lefty out and I didn't do
it,'' Morris said. ''It was my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No, I wasn't nervous,'' he said. ''I just didn't get it done.
They're very disciplined. They stay in the game until they make
someone else make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed hitters are only 3-for-18 against Morris this
season. The Yankees had scored their previous 13 runs on homers,
and were glad to get a run this way.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you have the bases loaded, you have to make him throw
strikes,'' O'Neill said. ''It's a great spot to be in. These are
the at-bats that are fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson (6-0) pitched two perfect innings and tied Toronto's
David Wells and Chicago's James Baldwin for the AL victory lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never expected to be 6-0 this early. It's just because we've
been scoring late and I happened to be in the games,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won despite Jeter going 0-for-4, leaving him hitless
in 12 at-bats. He has gone three straight games without a hit for
the first time since April 1997, when he went four in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada led off the seventh with a home run to dead center
field off Esteban Yan, tying it at 3. Posada also doubled, giving
him 12 hits in 17 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer hit a two-run homer in the Yankees fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Vaughn hit his 10th homer, a two-run drive in the third
that put the Devil Rays ahead 3-0. He has nine career home runs at
Yankee Stadium, including two for San Diego in Game 1 of the 1998
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Fred McGriff walked in the second and scored on Vinny Castilla's
RBI double off David Cone.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Vaughn did not hit his 10th homer last year until May 31.
He was nearly traded from San Diego to the Yankees on July 4, 1997,
for Kenny Rogers and Mariano Duncan. The Yankees voided the deal,
saying Vaughn was injured. ... Vaughn is 16-for-33 with runners in
scoring position. ... The Yankees are 3-0 in extra innings after
going 7-2 last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
