<HEADLINE> FCC Close To Deciding Cable Deal  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Communications regulators soon are expected
to decide on AT&AMP;T's massive cable purchase of MediaOne -- a deal
that makes the phone giant also the nation's top cable TV company.
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations are now before the five commissioners at the
Federal Communications Commission on how the merger could be
completed while still complying with federal rules that limit how
many cable households one entity may reach.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC could decide the matter in the very near future, the
agency's chief said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''That merger is on the front burner at the FCC,'' said
commission Chairman William Kennard, addressing a cable industry
convention here. ''I think we're really talking about a matter of
days.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger also must be cleared by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said the commissioners are focused on the proposal and
are adopting final details.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're actively engaged in working out what I believe are the
final issues now,'' Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which also would make AT&AMP;T a leading provider of
high-speed Internet services delivered over cable lines, has
trigged FCC regulations prohibiting a single cable company from
controlling more than 30 percent of the multichannel video market.
</P>
<P>
   That market comprises both cable and its competitors such as
direct broadcast satellite, and AT&AMP;T's deal with MediaOne would
exceed the 30 percent cap.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T and MediaOne deal would create the nation's largest
provider of cable TV company and high-speed cable Internet
services. For that reason, critics have raised flags that the
combined business would gain a stranglehold on the programming that
reaches consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Agency staff has offered steps for how the merger could go
through without violating the limit. For example, AT&AMP;T could sell
MediaOne's 25 percent stake in cable systems owned by Time Warner
Inc. or separate themselves from subsidiaries that sell programming
to Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 percent Time Warner share has drawn fire from consumer
groups for another reason: It would link the proposed AOL-Time
Warner with AT&AMP;T, connecting the nation's top cable providers.
</P>
<P>
   Public interest advocates have argued that AT&AMP;T's merger review
should be consolidated with evaluation of the deal between Time
Warner and AOL to make sure enough distance remains between the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   FCC officials said Tuesday the commission will rule on that idea
in the context of its AT&AMP;T-MediaOne merger decision.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Communications Commission site:
http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0159 </TRAILER>
