<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor, Wall Street exec announce Nassau financial rescue plan  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- A financial rescue plan for Nassau
County, announced by Gov. George Pataki and Wall Street's Frank
Zarb, won almost immediate bipartisan praise from both county and
state officials who will have to sign off on it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a Republican solution or a Democratic solution, it is
a good government solution,'' said Assemblyman Thomas DiNapoli,
chairman of the Nassau County Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Pataki, Zarb and Republican state Sen. Dean Skelos at
a press conference Tuesday to announce the plan, which calls for
the creation of an interim authority to refinance part of the
county's long-term debt, as well as $100 million in aid from the
state over five years in a bailout of one of the richest
communities in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we are trying to do here is to provide a road map out of
the fiscal difficulties and also a helping hand,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb, chairman of the National Association of Securities
Dealers, was appointed by Pataki in March to review the extent of
the county's financial woes, which were created, in part, from
years of increasing expenses as property taxes remained steady.
</P>
<P>
   He determined that with cuts already made, the county faces
about a $117 million shortfall this year. Unless further action is
taken, the deficit would grow to $321 million by 2003, he warned.
</P>
<P>
   ''We came to the conclusion that it's all manageable,'' Zarb
said Tuesday. ''And it can be done without people bleeding in the
streets and without being draconian and without doing things that
are really going to destroy the county's ability to grow and
prosper in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   If the county fails to act by June 30, Wall Street credit
agencies have warned they will downgrade the county's rating to
junk status, which would then create the need for a financial
control board.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki-Zarb proposal creates what they call
''control-lite,'' an interim financing board that would be
authorized to refinance part of the county's debt by utilizing
lower financing costs. The savings this year alone could be $40
million to $50 million, Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides $100 million in state funding -- $25 million in each of
the first two years -- the plan also requires the county to make $50
million in further spending cuts. Also, Pataki wants to spend $5
million to help the county erase a backlog of cases that challenge
its tax assessment system.
</P>
<P>
   The bailout plan requires the approval of both the state and
county legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think in the overall picture we're looking at a very
positive development in the road to fiscal health for Nassau
County,'' said Judy Jacobs, presiding officer of the county
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The financial mess in Nassau County, where the median household
income is $58,155, helped spark a political revolt last November
that saw Democrats oust the Republicans from control of the county
legislature for the first time since World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans suffered another embarrassing defeat last week, when
Democrat Craig Johnson won a special election to the Nassau County
Legislature, filling the seat previously held by his mother,
Barbara Johnson, who died of breast cancer earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the seat had been held by a Democrat, the high-profile
election to determine which party would gain a 10-9 majority in the
legislature was seen as yet another GOP setback.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor said Tuesday he would leave it to the
political pundits to muse about his or anyone else's motivation --
even as numerous GOP members of the Nassau state Senate delegation
sat in the front row at the news conference. Each of the senators
is up for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   County Executive Thomas Gulotta, a fellow Republican who did not
attend the Pataki press conference, said later Tuesday that the
plan was ''perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It puts the issue behind us once and for all and ensures the
county's future fiscal health and does so without the necessity of
a tax increase,'' Gulotta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
