<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Bill International Sex Trade  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress is moving legislation to help tens of
thousands of foreign women and children escape sexual servitude
while imposing tougher penalties on those who enslave them.
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday passed by voice vote and sent to the Senate
legislation that would give sex industry victims a safe haven in
this country rather than expose them to jail sentences or
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   ''More than 50,000 human beings, mostly women and children, are
trafficked into the United States each year,'' said Rep. Sam
Gejdenson, D-Conn., a co-sponsor with Rep. Christopher Smith,
R-N.J. ''It is intolerable that at the beginning of the 21st
century, people are still being sold into modern-day slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that worldwide as many as 2 million people, the great
majority women and children, are forced into the sex industry every
year. As an example, he said traffickers in Russia pay orphanages
$12,000 to take a group of children to the local McDonalds, never
to return.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he and Gejdenson recently talked to several women who
had been held as ''virtual slaves'' in the Washington area by
foreign diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is by far one of the worst human rights violations of our
time,'' said Rep. Jan Schakowsky, D-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would double to 20 years the maximum penalty for
enticing and selling people into involuntary servitude, and add the
possibility of life imprisonment when violations result in death or
involve kidnapping or sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It makes trafficking victims eligible for the federal Witness
Protection Plan and creates a new visa status for victims who
cooperate with law enforcement. Those entering this program, which
would be capped at 5,000 people a year, would be able to apply for
permanent residence after three years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also directs the State Department in its annual country
reports on human rights to include information on the levels to
which countries combat or tolerate human trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The president would have the authority, beginning in 2002, to
withhold nonhumanitarian aid to countries that fail to meet minimum
standards in eliminating the sex trade. The Clinton administration
opposes the bill based on this provision, but Smith stressed that
the president would also have the discretion to waive this
authority.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 3244.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Rep. Smith's Web site:
http://www.house.gov/chrissmith/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0211 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
