<HEADLINE> Railroad Killer Prosecution Rests  </HEADLINE>
By MARK BABINECK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Defense attorneys now have the chance to try and
prove that an alleged rail-riding serial killer was mentally ill
and therefore not responsible for the beating and stabbing death of
a Houston-area doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors rested their case Tuesday against Angel Maturino
Resendiz, after racing through 19 witnesses in two days. The
40-year-old suspect faces the death penalty if he is convicted of
the December 1998 murder of Dr. Claudia Benton of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   She is one of six people that the Mexican citizen is accused of
killing in Texas. Authorities say he also killed two people in
Illinois and another person in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Allen Tanner told jurors in opening statements
Monday that his client committed all nine killings, but should be
found innocent of Benton's murder by reason of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner and co-counsel Rudy Duarte were expected to call two
psychiatrists to testify that Maturino Resendiz was mentally ill
when he killed Benton. It remained unclear whether Maturino
Resendiz will testify.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Ranger Sgt. Drew Carter highlighted Tuesday's testimony,
which also included the introduction of DNA evidence linking
Maturino Resendiz to Benton's rape.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who arrested Maturino Resendiz at the Texas-Mexico
border last summer, described how his search began in February 1999
and blossomed into an international manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   ''As time went on, I learned a lot about him, but I learned more
about his nomadic nature and that there was really no good place to
start,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   He struck up a relationship with Maturino Resendiz's sister,
Manuela Maturino Karkiewicz. The work paid off on July 11, 1999,
when Karkiewicz called Carter and said her brother was ready to
surrender.
</P>
</TEXT>
