<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreas' Summit Preparation Praised  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The United States today praised
preparations for a first-ever summit between the leaders of South
Korea and North Korea, which have held four rounds of talks since
April 22.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States feels very confident in the way that the
summit is being approached,'' U.S. State Department counselor Wendy
Sherman said at the end of three days of talks with South Korean
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The United States believes direct dialogue between the Koreas is
the only way to bring stability to the Korean Peninsula. The two
adversaries signed an armistice, not a permanent peace treaty, at
the end of the 1950-1953 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Communist North Korea previously shunned most government
contacts with South Korea, which it dismissed as a puppet state
controlled by the United States. Pyongyang was more willing to
negotiate with Washington in a policy widely viewed as an attempt
to split the U.S.-South Korean alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said the planned summit between North Korean leader Kim
Jong Il and South Korean President Kim Dae-jung was an affirmation
of close ties between the United States, South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States is absolutely gratified that indeed this
historic event will take place in June because it really reinforces
the shared objectives of all three of our countries,'' Sherman said
before flying to China, a traditional ally of North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the North alarmed the region by test-firing a rocket
that flew over Japan and landed in the Pacific. In September,
Washington lifted some economic sanctions against Pyongyang in
exchange for its pledge to freeze missile tests.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, South Korean officials said they and their North
Korean counterparts would no longer hold preparatory meetings for
the summit in the border village of Panmunjom. Instead, they will
communicate via documents and telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ''The change is meant for effectiveness,'' Kim Hyon-doo, a
spokesman for Seoul's Unification Ministry, said without
elaborating.
</P>
<P>
   After a long day of talks Monday, South Korea proposed a fifth
round of negotiations on Tuesday. But the North Koreans declined.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators have made progress, but two issues remain
unresolved: the language of the agenda for the talks and the size
of the press corps that will accompany the South Korean president.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea had proposed an agenda calling for economic
cooperation, peace measures, the reunion of separated family
members and the establishment of a permanent channel of government
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials later said privately they would agree to
a broadly worded North Korean proposal which stresses peace and
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea proposed sending an 80-member press corps but North
Korea, which has accused the South's media of biased reporting,
asked that the number be halved.
</P>
<P>
   Today, South Korean Unification Minister Park Jae-kyu said his
president would ask Kim Jong Il to visit Seoul by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is scheduled to hold talks on improving ties
with North Korea in Rome on May 24 in a continuation of discussions
that adjourned in New York in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 0231 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
