<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday, May 10, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Envoy Heads to Muslim Rebel Camp
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- A Libyan envoy headed into the Philippine jungle
today to talk with Muslim separatists holding 21 Western and Asian hostages and
to press for the release of an ill German woman. A doctor accompanying him had
medicine, oxygen, food, clothing, and chocolate for the captives. She was also
taking stretchers in case the rebels agreed to free two captives: a German woman
who has suffered two strokes, according to her family, and a French man with a
urinary infection. The hostages -- three Germans, two French, two South
Africans, two Finns, a Lebanese, nine Malaysians and two Filipinos -- were
snatched from a diving resort on the Malaysian island of Sipadan on April 23 and
taken to Jolo, an hour's boat ride away
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. To Pay Volunteer Peacekeepers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Peacekeepers from around the world put themselves at
risk in faraway countries every day, but not for free. The United Nations
promises $1,000 per person, per month to countries that volunteer troops for
peace missions. That money can be helpful for poorer nations, such as Zambia and
Guinea. But the flat rate won't cover the costs for better-trained western
forces, who seem unwilling to lose money on high-risk missions in areas where
they have little at stake. In Sierra Leone, 500 U.N. personnel have been taken
hostage by rebels of the Revolutionary United Front. At least one peacekeeper is
believed to be dead, and 12 others have been injured.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Big Game Jackpot Hits $350 Million
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- ATLANTA (AP) -- With the richest lottery jackpot in U.S.
history at stake, millions of people who snapped up Big Game tickets already
knew today that they hadn't won. Their only hope was that no one else had the
winning ticket, which would mean the $350 million jackpot will grow even larger.
The winning numbers were 1, 2, 12, 33, 37 and Big Money Ball 4. Lottery
officials were expected to announce today whether any jackpot-winning tickets
were sold. After taxes, based on federal and Georgia state taxes, the Big Game
payout on a single winning ticket is either $8.9 million a year for 26 years, or
a one-time payment of $114 million.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't Drafts New Medicaid Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some states could lose millions in Medicaid payments for
nursing homes under a government proposal aimed at ending accounting gimmicks
that help states increase their share of federal matching funds without raising
their own contributions. The Health Care Financing Administration, which
administers Medicaid, has proposed altering regulations that help determine how
much federal Medicaid money nursing homes receive. The change would dramatically
reduce federal matching funds in many states that have come to rely on the money
to shore up struggling county-run nursing facilities, state officials say.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Seeking New Chapter With UN
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- After years of isolation and strain, Israel is hoping
that its compliance with a 22-year-old U.N. resolution to withdraw from Lebanese
soil will help warm ties with the world body that gave it life. Israel's
ambassador to the United Nations, Yehuda Lankry, told The Associated Press that
Israel has been enjoying rare cooperation with the United Nations in preparation
for a pullout by July. Israel has yet to comply with other U.N. resolutions
calling for it to withdraw from additional war-won territories, but Lankry said
Israel's acceptance of the Lebanon resolution was a good first step in improving
relations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Congress Probes Way To Stop Computer Viruses
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House lawmakers plan to take the bite out of the next
"Love Bug" by bringing experts in to explain how the government can protect its
computers from mass-mailed computer viruses. The "Love Bug" virus, which has
been called the fastest-spreading and most destructive computer virus ever,
caused a flood of e-mails with the subject line "ILOVEYOU" to course through
computer systems worldwide. The easiest way is to educate people about computer
hygiene, including not opening unexpected e-mail attachments, said Harris
Miller, president of the computer group Information Technology Association of
America. Agencies should also continually update their antivirus protection, he
said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei shed 143.07 points to close at 17,701.47. On Wall
Street, the Dow fell 66.88 to 10,536.75.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Diamondbacks Beat Dodgers 11-7 12 Innings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PHOENIX (AP) -- Damian Miller hit a game-winning grand slam off Orel
Hershiser in the 12th inning, his second home run of the game, as the Arizona
Diamondbacks rallied past the Los Angeles Dodgers 11-7 Tuesday night. Todd
Hollandsworth, who homered leading off the game, had put the Dodgers ahead in
the 12th against Vincente Padilla (1-0) with an RBI grounder. Erubiel Durazo
loaded the bases with a single, and Steve Finley's sacrifice fly to shallow left
tied it, with Bell sliding home ahead of Gary Sheffield's throw.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</SUBHEAD>
