<DOCNO> APW20000510.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 05:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Sought in Embassy Bombing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno has authorized
federal prosecutors to seek the death penalty against at least one
person charged in the 1998 bombings of two U.S. embassies in
Africa, The New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
   The decision would result in the first U.S. death penalty case
involving an act of international terrorism, lawyers in the case
told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant is Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-'Owhali, who is accused
of riding in the truck carrying the bomb that exploded at the U.S.
Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, on Aug. 7, 1998. That bombing, and a
simultaneous one at the embassy in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, killed
224 people, including 12 Americans. More than 5,000 people were
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali, the first suspect brought to New York from Africa
after the bombings, has acknowledged that he rode in the truck and
that the bombing was intended as a ''martyrdom operation,''
according to federal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali is one of three defendants eligible for the death
penalty in the case. No penalty decision has been made regarding
the other two, the Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   All three defendants, in custody in New York, have pleaded
innocent to murder conspiracy charges.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali's lawyer David Bruck called Reno's decision
''folly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The government claims this young man has already tried to
detonate himself into paradise,'' Bruck said. ''Now it's offering
to do the job itself, providing him with a glorious death while the
world watches. Is this how to deter terrorism?''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White declined to comment
to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bombings, federal prosecutors have indicted a total of
17 men, including Saudi exile Osama bin Laden, on charges they
conspired to kill Americans outside the United States. Eight of
those charged are fugitives, including bin Laden.
</P>
</TEXT>
