<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 9:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Wednesday, May 10, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft To Present Counter-Proposal
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft is about to get its chance to rebut
a government's proposal to rip the company in two. Today, Microsoft
will respond to the proposal made last month by the Justice
Department and 17 state attorneys to split it into one company that
sells the dominant Windows operating system and another selling
virtually everything else. Microsoft's response to the government
proposal will include its objections to the plan, as well as its
own proposed remedies. Sources told The Associated Press last week
that Microsoft may ask the judge to scrap most of the government's
plan because it is improperly based on evidence that wasn't
presented during trial.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Earnings Top Expectations
</P>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Internet equipment provider Cisco
Systems Inc. continues to show strong quarterly gains as a string
of acquisitions and internal development helps meet red-hot demand
for Web and data-routing services. For the three months ended April
29, the company reported net income of $662 million, or 9 cents per
share, up from $636 million, or 9 cents per share, in the year-ago
period. The numbers include $488 million in research and
development write-offs as well as several other one-time items.
Excluding those numbers, Cisco earned $1.03 billion, or 14 cents a
share. As has been a pattern, Cisco's earnings yesterday exceeded
expectations by a penny a share. Analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial had expected the company to earn 13 cents a
share, excluding charges.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq To Invest $100M in S. Korea
</P>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Compaq Computer Corp. of the United
States said today it will invest $100 million in South Korean
Internet companies this year. The global computer maker said the
money will be spent on forming strategic alliances with Korean
Internet service providers, strengthening its service and
consulting in the Internet area through mergers and acquisitions or
partnerships. It also said it will enhance e-commerce and
electronic banking activities in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sega Game To Include Web Phone Use
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Sega Enterprises is joining with a
Singapore company to allow users of its Dreamcast game console to
make low-cost phone calls over the Internet while playing. The
service will roll out first in Japan in August, followed shortly
thereafter in the United States, the company said in a statement.
Sega will hold a 20 percent stake in the company, while its
Japanese affiliate will own 30 percent. The closely held InnoMedia,
which uses the Internet to make phone calls and transmit data, will
own 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Earnings Rise
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s first-quarter earnings
rose sharply from a year ago, and the world's biggest retailer said
it expects to maintain healthy sales and profit growth for the
remainder of the year. The chain reported yesterday that it earned
$1.326 billion, or 30 cents a share, for the quarter ended April
30, compared with $916 million, or 20 cents a share, a year ago.
Last year's results include a 4 cent charge for a change in the
company's accounting practices. Wal-Mart's results topped Wall
Street analysts estimates of 28 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Asian Stock Prices Fall
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets tumbled today, hurt by
recent losses on Wall Street and concerns about an expected U.S.
interest rate hike. Japan's 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell
143.07 points, or 0.8 percent, to close at 17,701.47. The Hang Seng
Index plunged 283.98 points, or 1.9 percent, to 14,492.92, the
lowest since Nov. 12. The Taiwan Weighted Stock Price Index slid
75.97 points, or 0.9 percent, to 8,559.87. The Stock Exchange of
Thailand Composite Index plummeted 14.24 points, or 4 percent, to
close at 343.53, the lowest since March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Falls 84, Dow Drops 66
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell again yesterday. The Nasdaq
composite index closed down 84.37 at 3,585.01 while the Dow Jones
industrial average fell 66.88 to 10,536.75. The Nasdaq is now down
11.9 percent from the beginning of the year and 29 percent below
its record close of 5,048.62 reached on March 10. Broader stock
indicators also fell. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index dropped 12.03
to 1,412.14, and the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell
9.22 to 490.86.
</P>
