<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Falls 135; Dow Drops 103  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply in early trading today, with
technology names leading the declines as investors punished Cisco
Systems despite a profit report that topped Wall Street's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 103.40 at 10433.35.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Nasdaq composite
index was down 135.02 at 3,449.99, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was off 21.25 at 1,390.89.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco was down 2[ to 60|. After the close of trading Tuesday,
the Internet equipment provider reported net income of $662
million, or 9 cents per share. That beat Wall Street analysts'
expectations by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   But shares of Cisco have been out of favor all week after a
story in Barron's magazine said the stock is overvalued and
acquisitions will prove increasingly difficult because of
escalating purchase prices of smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Motorola fell 12 15/16 to 92.
Salomon Smith Barney cut its rating on the stock to ''outperform''
from ''buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Volume was fairly light, continuing a string of quiet sessions.
Many market players have retreated to the sidelines ahead of the
Federal Reserve's next meeting on May 16. The Fed is expected to
raise interest rates as much as a half-percentage point in its
continuing bid to slow the pace of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the NYSE came to 113.52 million shares, behind
Tuesday's early pace. Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a
9-to-5 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 8.13 to 482.73.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.8 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was down 1.5 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.04 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 1.1 percent.
</P>
