<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Wednesday, May 10, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feds Defend Microsoft Breakup Plan
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department defended the proposal
to break up Microsoft Corp. into two companies as the best way of
preserving competition in the computer software industry. Assistant
Attorney General Joel Klein, speaking in advance of today's
deadline for Microsoft's counterproposal, said the Microsoft case
resembles the government's case against AT&AMP;T in the early 1980s. ''
... The divestiture in the AT&AMP;T case ... has unleashed
unprecedented competition, innovation and consumer benefit,'' Klein
said, referring to the growth in wireless communications, broadband
services and fiber optics.
</P>
<P>
   Investors Not Satisfied With Cisco
</P>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Investors weren't satisfied by a strong
quarterly earnings report from Cisco Systems Inc., sending shares
down 3{, or 6 percent, to 59\ in morning trading on the Nasdaq
Stock Market. Shares of Cisco have been out of favor all week after
a story in Barron's magazine said the stock is overvalued and
acquisitions will prove increasingly difficult because of
escalating purchase prices of smaller companies. Yesterday,
however, the Internet equipment provider reported solid gains as a
string of acquisitions and internal development helped meet demand
for Web and data-routing services.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Plans New England Expansion
</P>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. (AP) -- Cisco Systems Inc. plans a major expansion
into New Hampshire that could bring 2,500 new jobs into the state.
The Internet network equipment provider said today it has agreed to
buy about 110 acres and a building in Salem near the Massachusetts
border for a New England Manufacturing Center. The move is part of
Cisco's plans for expansion and substantial growth in New England,
and closely follows word that the company is opening a New England
Development Center in Massachusetts. The new center will be used to
test and assemble products and distribute them worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings Up at Federated Stores
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Federated Department Stores Inc.'s
first-quarter earnings rose 2 percent from a year ago, fueled by
strong sales at its department stores, which include the Macy's and
Bloomingdale's chains. The chain reported today that it earned $89
million, or 41 cents a share, in the quarter ended April 29,
compared with $87 million, or 40 cents a share, a year ago. Sales
were $4.03 billion, up from $3.6 billion in the first quarter of
1999. The gains helped offset costs associated with stepping up its
e-commerce business. The retailer's stock was up [ to 36{ this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Drops 98; Nasdaq Falls 134
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply in early trading today, with
technology names leading the declines as investors punished Cisco
Systems. Motorola also fell 14} to 89}. Salomon Smith Barney cut
its rating on the stock to ''outperform'' from ''buy.'' Just before
11 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were down 98.18 at 10,438.57. On
the NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,587-770. The Nasdaq was down
134.44 at 3,450.57. Volume was fairly light, continuing a string of
quiet sessions.
</P>
