   Sega Game To Include Web Phone Use
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Sega Enterprises is joining with a
Singapore company to allow users of its Dreamcast game console to
make low-cost phone calls over the Internet while playing. The
service will roll out first in Japan in August, followed shortly
thereafter in the United States. Sega will hold a 20 percent stake
in the company, while its Japanese affiliate will own 30 percent.
The closely held InnoMedia, which uses the Internet to make phone
calls and transmit data, will own 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two Paper Cos. Boost Champion Bids
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Both suitors for Champion International raised
their bids for the Connecticut-based paper maker today.
International Paper, which made a cash-and-stock bid of $64 a share
two weeks ago, upped the ante to $75 a share and increased the cash
component of the offer to from $43 to $50. UPM-Kymmene of Finland
also increased its offer, bidding $70 per share in cash. UPM,
Europe's largest paper company, had already entered an all-stock
agreement to acquire Champion in February, but a slide in UPM's
stock price diminished the value of that offer.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed To Keep Plant in Georgia
</P>
<P>
   MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) -- Lockheed Martin has decided against moving
final assembly of the F-22 stealth fighter from Marietta to Fort
Worth, Texas, preserving 1,000 jobs at the suburban Atlanta plant.
Marietta plant chief Tom Burbage said ''financial implications'' of
the studies did not support such a plan. In February, the Bethesda,
Md.-based company announced 2,800 layoffs, 2 percent of its work
force of 140,000, which it said would generate $200 million in
annual savings.
</P>
