<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan, Illinois winners in $366 million Big Game drawing  </HEADLINE>
By A.J. DICKERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA , Mich. (AP) --Winning tickets in the Big Game lottery were
sold in Michigan and Illinois, officials announced today, dashing
the hopes of millions whose frenzied buying in seven states pushed
the jackpot to a record $366 million.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate details on who the winners are, though
Michigan Lottery officials say they were contacted this morning by
a man they believe holds the winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
   A ticket matching the numbers drawn Tuesday night in the
multistate lottery was sold at Mr. K's Party Shoppe in suburban
Detroit, Michigan Lottery Commissioner Don Gilmer said from
Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   About 9:30 a.m., a man who did not identify himself called the
Michigan Lottery office, where validation numbers he recited from
his ticket apparently matched those the winning ticket should have,
spokeswoman Sarah Lapshan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pretty confident this is the winning ticket. I just don't
like to say this is the winner until they're here,'' Lapshan said.
''We don't consider it validated until it's in our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   She described the caller as ''remarkably quite calm'' for a
potential jackpot winner. He divulged nothing about himself.
</P>
<P>
   The other winning ticket was bought at Sweeney's Citgo in the
northwestern Chicago suburb of Lake Zurick, Ill. Assistant manager
Ginny Gallagher said lottery officials called her at 7 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ''I screamed at the girl on the phone, I was so excited,''
Gallagher said. The store has sold about $100,000 worth of Big Game
tickets in the past few weeks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The holder of the Michigan ticket chose the annuity option but
can change course and go with a lump-sum cash payment, Gilmer said.
By Gilmer's calculations, the annuity before taxes would pay $7
million a year -- $135,000 a week -- over the next 26 years. The
lump-sum payment would pay the Michigan winner about $61.3 million,
after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're glad it's over with,'' Gilmer said. ''The jackpot got to
almost unrealistic heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. K's Party Shoppe is in a small strip mall with two other
businesses -- a tanning parlor and a hair salon -- in Macomb County's
Shelby Township near Utica, about 20 miles north of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Owner George Kassab and four sons who work in the store were so
thrilled that they opened up shortly after 6 a.m. today, three
hours earlier than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very excited -- I'm happy for the winner,'' he said. Still,
there was a tiny bit of disappointment: ''I was hoping it was me. I
bought a few tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Kassab, 49, is a former General Motors Corp. assembly line
worker who immigrated to the United States from Iraq 34 years ago
and saved enough to buy the store seven years ago. His sons are
Mark, 27, Marvin, 25, Melvin, 23, and Matthew, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Kassab said his mother answered the phone when a
television station called early this morning. ''She didn't believe
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   George Kassab said he has no idea who bought the winning ticket.
On Tuesday, he said, he sold about 5,000 Big Game tickets compared
with an average of about 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   He said Michigan Lottery officials told him he will get the
maximum $2,000 bonus for selling the winning ticket -- what Gilmer
called ''very fair,'' given the ''enormous amount of publicity''
the store will get.
</P>
<P>
   ''They'll just be mobbed,'' Gilmer said. ''Most stores are more
than happy. In essence, they had to push three buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmer said ''the most important winners'' in Michigan were the
state's school fund, which will get $29 million in proceeds from
the jackpot that began nine weeks ago at just $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gonzales was the first customer of the morning at Mr. K's,
arriving around 6:35 a.m. She often buys lottery tickets there, and
quickly checked her six tickets this morning when she heard the
winning ticket was sold there.
</P>
<P>
   News that the winning ticket was sold in her community came as a
shock.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know a lot of people who buy tickets here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaarina Maul stopped by the store this morning to buy snacks and
$10 worth of lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ''I come in every day. My husband woke me up and I kept my
tickets. I didn't win anything. I'm upset he didn't sell it to
me,'' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   While the drawings are held in Atlanta, results are handled by
the individual state lotteries participating in the Big Game, in
Georgia, Illinois, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey
and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   By 7 a.m., officials had confirmed that the only winning tickets
were the two sold in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The winning numbers were one, two, 12, 33 and 37, and the Big
Money Ball number was four. To win, a ticket had to match the five
numbers and the Big Money Ball.
</P>
<P>
   The $366 million jackpot tops the previous American record for a
lottery. That was a $295.7 million Powerball jackpot split by 13
machinists in Westerville, Ohio, two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The world lottery record is $1.2 billion, set in December by
Spain's El Gordo lottery, or the Fat One. But that game spreads
itself thin by awarding thousands of prizes.
</P>
<P>
   The odds that a $1 Big Game ticket will have all five winning
numbers and the matching Big Money Ball are one in more than 76
million.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Holland, a bartender at the East Atlanta Restaurant and
Lounge in Georgia, said he knew the odds were stacked against him
when he bought his ticket. The odds of having all five winning
numbers and the Big Money Ball were one in more than 76 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''At least I only lost a dollar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others weren't as lucky. Some players plopped down hundreds of
dollars in the hopes of becoming instant millionaires. Others
pooled their money with coworkers and friends to buy more chances.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Big Game: http://www.theofficialbiggame.com
</P>
</TEXT>
