<HEADLINE> Visteon To Keep Indiana Plant Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONNERSVILLE, Ind. (AP) -- Visteon Corp.'s top executive tried to
ease fears of autoworkers here by saying he is committed to keeping
the plant open when the company is spun off from Ford Motor Co. in
late June.
</P>
<P>
   ''This plant isn't going to suffer because of the change,''
Visteon Chairman Peter Pestillo said Tuesday after meeting with
workers in the 3,203-employee plant.
</P>
<P>
   Pestillo recently stepped down as a Ford vice chairman to become
the chairman of Visteon, an auto parts manufacturing arm of Ford.
Pestillo and his senior staff are visiting Visteon plants worldwide
to discuss the company's future.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders said many workers fear Ford intends to spin off
Visteon only to shop for components made by suppliers that pay
lower wages -- that has raised concerns the plants could lose
production and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Pestillo said the spinoff could make the 1.7 million-square-foot
plant more dependent on the international auto market.
</P>
<P>
   He said Visteon is trying to win new business from Volkswagen AG
and other international automakers. Automotive heating and cooling
components made at the Connersville plant could wind up in VWs
overseas if Visteon lands the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to have an aggressive sales mentality rather than a
service mentality,'' Pestillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Visteon operates two other Indiana plants -- a steering assembly
plant in Indianapolis that employs 2,893 and a Bedford components
plant employing 1,164.
</P>
</TEXT>
