<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bayer May Settle Drug Pricing Probe  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- German pharmaceutical company Bayer AG confirmed
today it has begun settlement talks with state and federal
officials over allegations it overbilled for years for some drugs
covered under Medicare and Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   A Bayer spokeswoman said the company has opened settlement talks
with the U.S. Justice Department, the Inspector General's office of
the Department of Health and Human Services, and several state
prosecutors who jointly are pursuing the case.
</P>
<P>
   The government is trying to reach a settlement with Bayer in the
hope of prodding other drug companies to seek similar agreements
that would bring about more-accurate pricing practices, according
to a story published in today's Wall Street Journal. Others under
scrutiny included Abbott Laboratories, Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.,
Glaxo Wellcome PLC's U.S. unit, and SmithKline Beecham PLC, the
Journal reported.
</P>
<P>
   The House Commerce Committee also is investigating, and sent
letters last Friday to seven companies requesting detailed records
on the pricing of certain drugs, including SmithKline's Kytril,
Baxter International Inc.'s Gammagard, and Glaxo Wellcome's Zofran.
Other companies that were sent letters included TAP Pharmacautics,
Day Laboratories, Aventis Behring and Warrick Pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has asked the drug firms to respond by May 26.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the inquiries is a practice that allows doctors and
other medical providers to bill Medicare and Medicaid for more than
they actually pay for some drugs and keep the difference. The
medical providers can do that because the government health
insurance programs reimburse them based on the drugs' average
wholesale price set by the companies. But the companies often sell
the drugs to suppliers at deep discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare is the federal health insurance program for the
elderly. Medicaid is the state-federal health insurance program for
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The Bayer spokeswoman said representatives from the company's
West Haven,.Conn-based Bayer Pharmaceuticals division have met with
the government officials, most recently on May 1, and discussions
are continuing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
