<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shakespeare Co. Offers Regal Fare  </HEADLINE>
By MATT WOLF, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Don Carlos, an impetuous young prince, must
compete with his fearsome father, King Philip II of Spain, for the
affections of the woman who has been made queen.
</P>
<P>
   The plot echoes ''Hamlet'': Both plays share a level of
conspiratorial intrigue that is rare indeed. But there's a twist:
In ''Don Carlos,'' it's the boy's stepmother, not his mother, who
excites the young man's ardor.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as the new Royal Shakespeare Company staging of ''Don
Carlos'' proves, Friedrich's Schiller's 1787 play -- done well -- has
its own power to entertain and excite, as American theatergoers
will discover later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The German Expressionist classic is infrequently staged in
England, let alone in the United States, but it is by no means the
only talking point of the collective show that the RSC -- one of
Britain's two largest state-funded theater troupes -- is taking on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   After some years of mixed fortunes, the RSC is now thought to be
on a roll. On its home turf, several productions are selling out
and receiving critical acclaim and even the occasional standing
ovation, which is a rarity in England.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few weeks, no fewer than five of these shows will
be testing the waters abroad. The transatlantic traffic marks the
decades-old company's largest simultaneous presence in the United
States to date.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to Kelsey Grammer, the theater-trained TV
star who tackles Macbeth on Broadway this summer, his Thane of
Cawdor is unlikely to better Antony Sher's fiery and frightening
star turn in the role for the RSC.
</P>
<P>
   That staging, directed by Gregory Doran (Sher's real-life
partner), plays the International Festival of Arts and Ideas in New
Haven, Conn., June 15-24. A subsequent Broadway run isn't out of
the question. (If New York can play host to two ''Wild Party''
musicals in one season, why not two versions of ''Macbeth'' the
next?)
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the production is on view through June 3 at
London's Young Vic Theater. There, audiences are proclaiming Sher
and co-star Harriet Walter as the finest inhabitants of the
murderous roles since Ian McKellen and Judi Dench trod the boards
together over 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Headed further west is director Lindsay Posner's touring
production of ''The Taming of the Shrew,'' which reaches San
Francisco's Herbst Theater June 22-July 2 as part of the city's
Shakespeare Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart McQuarrie plays Petruchio, the none-too-subtle
domesticator of Katharina (Monica Dolan), the ''shrew'' who is
eventually -- if sometimes violently -- ''tamed.''
</P>
<P>
   But is there life still to be found in a play in which, or so it
seems, women exist merely to be put in their place?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the ideal play in terms of sparking debate about sexual
politics,'' Posner says. ''It's about power and empowerment and
abuse within those terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly ''The Taming of the Shrew'' is an enduring play and
the most enduring plays don't date; they merely reveal different
shadings and hues over time.
</P>
<P>
   That's one way of accounting for the phenomenal impact of the
RSC revival of ''The Family Reunion,'' T S. Eliot's eerie 1939 play
that is one of three RSC productions now playing at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music. (''The Family Reunion'' debuted Wednesday and the
production runs through Saturday.)
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an extraordinary satire on the one hand, an extraordinary
post-Freudian drama on the other,'' says director Adrian Noble,
whose staging may remind New York theatergoers that Eliot did more
than just provide source material for the musical ''Cats.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes Margaret Tyzack, a Broadway Tony-winner for
her role in ''Lettice and Lovage,'' as the ailing matriarch of a
family of country swells and Greg Hicks as her errant son.
</P>
<P>
   Also headed for BAM is ''Don Carlos,'' which looks set to make a
star out of its dashing and talented leading man, Rupert
Penry-Jones. The 29-year-old actor's matinee idol good looks
couldn't be further from the part's disfigured 16th-century
prototype, who died at age 23.
</P>
<P>
   ''This seems to have done my career a lot of good,'' Penry-Jones
says of ''Don Carlos,'' speaking before a performance of an
inferior RSC production, ''Timon of Athens,'' which is not leaving
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a heavyweight part,'' Penry-Jones says. ''I feel like I'm
up there with the other guys playing the big classical roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Completing the BAM trio is one of Shakespeare's best-loved
plays, ''A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' in a notably saucy new
production from Michael Boyd. This version leaves no doubt about
the precise nature of the intimacy between Bottom and the fairy
queen Titania, while its conclusion is one of the RSC's more joyous
of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, says Noble, who is also the Company's artistic
director, it's hard to lose when you're working with Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very privileged to have this great playwright'' as our
namesake, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the 21st century, Shakespeare ''seems to articulate
every human experience,'' Noble says. ''He finds the words for
every human emotion and knows the exact language for the many
colors of life.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Shakespeare Company's touring schedule in the United
States:
</P>
<P>
   ''Don Carlos,'' BAM Harvey Theater, Brooklyn, N.Y., May 16-20.
</P>
<P>
   ''A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' BAM Howard Gilman Opera House,
Brooklyn, N.Y. May 21-27.
</P>
<P>
   ''Macbeth,'' Long Wharf Theater, New Haven, Conn., June 15-24.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Taming of the Shrew,'' Herbst Theater, San Francisco, June
22-July 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 1202 </TRAILER>
