<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews  </HEADLINE>
Audio reviews from The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   Selected new releases:
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Fair Weather'' (Compass) -- Alison Brown
</P>
<P>
   Alison Brown is a major talent on the banjo who, like Bela
Fleck, pushes the instrument into places it rarely goes. Brown has
ventured into jazz and even world music on previous albums. Her
excellent new disc, ''Fair Weather,'' represents a return to her
bluegrass roots. It's melodic and fluid, occasionally lovely and
frequently surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has assembled a crack supporting cast for ''Fair Weather''
and it shows in the excellent playing, which ranges from
straight-ahead, traditional bluegrass to a more modern ''newgrass''
style. She also harnessed guest vocalists for some interesting
covers, including a wonderful bluegrass version of Elvis Costello's
''Every Day I Write the Book.''
</P>
<P>
   -- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Tanto Tempo'' (Six Degrees) -- Bebel Gilberto
</P>
<P>
   On ''Tanto Tempo,'' Bebel Gilberto gently updates the bossa nova
sound her father, Joao Gilberto, helped make famous. It's a lovely
album, understated and sensuous, as romantic as a summer rainstorm
enjoyed from a porch swing. Although she occasionally ventures into
trip-hop grooves and orchestration, this is still very much a bossa
nova album, hushed and restrained but simmering with passion
underneath. Gilberto has a famous last name, but deserves to be
judged -- and enjoyed -- in her own right.
</P>
<P>
   -- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Real Time'' (Howdy Skies) -- Tim O'Brien and Darrell Scott
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever sat around a living room or porch while a couple
of excellent musicians had a blast playing together, you've got an
idea of how much fun ''Real Time'' is. The album was recorded in
Scott's living room and the production has an almost live feel to
it. What sets it apart from most living-room jam sessions is that
these are two of the finest musicians on the acoustic scene,
top-notch multi-instumentalists and songwriters. Through nine
originals, two traditional songs and two Hank Williams covers, what
comes through is this duo's passion for American roots music and
talent at playing it.
</P>
<P>
   -- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
