<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Many Lives of Sherman Alexie  </HEADLINE>
By HILLEL ITALIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- In his young, in-your-face career, Sherman Alexie
has taken on men and women, whites and Indians, academics and
fellow authors. But on this day, before some 200 students and
teachers at North Seattle Community College, he's having it out
with his own poster.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   SHERMAN ALEXIE:
</P>
<P>
   Writer.
</P>
<P>
   Storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Politician.
</P>
<P>
   Activist.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   That first one he'll go along with. Yes, he's a writer. The
second one, storyteller, is a myth, a stereotype, the folksy Indian
passing on tribal wisdom. Gimme a break.
</P>
<P>
   The third doesn't work because he doesn't claim to speak for
anybody. The fourth is kind of sweet but an ambassador is supposed
to be nice. Not Sherman. The fifth is ridiculous; he's too honest.
The last he'll consider, but don't call him after hours.
</P>
<P>
   The auditorium is small, crowded and open to a hallway on one
side, where passers-by occasionally stop and join the laughter. The
people love Alexie. You expect the author to talk about books, but
he wants to talk about everything -- everything! -- except books. He
sounds off about sex (loves it), Republicans (hates them), Jesus
(''a liberal''), white people (''crimson necked,'' ''pigment
challenged''), Indians (horny guys), life (a tough gig).
</P>
<P>
   It's a performance, a writer playing off the idea of a writer,
and an Indian playing off the idea of an Indian. He strikes
statuesque poses, easy when you're 6 feet 2 inches, with a thick,
handsome build, like a prime block of marble. ''I must speak
slowly,'' he says at one point, his voice deepening, Tonto style.
''I must always look off into the distance, as if receiving a
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 33, Alexie has fallen into the long-running
job/privilege/burden of playing Sherman Alexie. The acclaimed
author of four works of fiction and several volumes of poetry, he
has more than half a million books in print. Last year, he was
named by The New Yorker as one of the best writers under 40. He's
also the principal creator of ''Smoke Signals,'' the first major
feature film to be written, directed, produced and acted by
American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am a commodity,'' he likes to say. Alexie has a business
card, an office, an office assistant, a fan club, a Web site, a
schedule board. He's a bad boy with nice clothes (today, a gray
microfiber shirt and black jeans), an overachiever who brags he's
the first Indian to move into a white neighborhood and actually
raise real estate values.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a certain injustice in what I do,'' Alexie observes
later. ''I'm a celebrity who's an Indian who's mad at the world
who's making money off being mad at the world. Where do you go with
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie's works include ''Indian Killer'' and ''Reservation
Blues,'' both novels; ''The Business of Fancydancing,'' which
includes poems and stories; and the story collection ''The Lone
Ranger and Tonto Fistfight in Heaven.'' His most recent publication
is another book of stories, ''The Toughest Indian in the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, especially since the release of ''Smoke
Signals,'' he has emerged as the Indian writer most sought after to
give readings, speak on campuses or appear on a panel. He's
attractive, quick-witted, and, not always to his benefit, direct.
As one of his characters puts it, ''confrontational banter'' is a
veritable flag of indigenous culture.
</P>
<P>
   ''He loves giving people new ideas, but sometimes he's more
confrontational than tactful about it,'' says Thom Chambliss,
executive director of the Pacific Northwest Booksellers
Association, for which Alexie has appeared at several events.
</P>
<P>
   At this morning's talk, Alexie criticizes the late mother of
Elian Gonzalez, the Cuban boy who became the center of an
international custody fight. Alexie wonders how she could just put
her kid on a raft in the ocean. A woman in the back row objects.
She's Asian, a boat person, and she's in tears. Her own mother
risked her family's lives to get them to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''That comment was bad,'' the woman says.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I offended you I'm sorry,'' Alexie responds. ''But that's
how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   More often, however, Alexie has the gift of making admirers out
of the people he insults. He tells the audience about sharing a
televised panel with President Clinton on race relations. During
the broadcast Clinton mentioned that his grandmother was Cherokee.
Alexie replied that white people were always telling him their
relatives were Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   At a gathering later, Clinton walked right up to Alexie and
placed his big hands on the author's solid shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   The president told him he was funny.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Will that cell phone ever ring?
</P>
<P>
   Alexie drives through Seattle in his rented Buick (the old car
died), down hills as steep as water slides. He's waiting for word
on a film project, and if nature's an omen, the author has a deal.
For the first time in days the sun is out, as if the sky just
finally ran dry. Look up and all you see is the biggest, brightest
blue, not a bad color when the future is on your mind.
</P>
<P>
   He has a lunch meeting at the Painted Table, a quiet,
lounge-like hotel restaurant where the paint you really notice is
the modernist swirls on the plates. Arriving shortly after Alexie
are two film producers and a soundtrack composer. They were all
part of the ''Smoke Signals'' team and they now await the ''green
light'' from Miramax Films for his next project, a screen version
of ''Reservation Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   Over salmon burgers, they talk about the proposed movie, the
story of an Indian rock 'n' roll band. Alexie already has an idea
for the trailer: Two Indians, the leads in ''Smoke Signals,'' meet
Christopher Columbus when his ships first arrive and shoot him
dead. One turns to the camera and says: ''Gee, Victor, imagine if
we had tougher immigration laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours go by and the call doesn't come. Alexie thinks it
never will. The producers smile; they've heard this before. They
joke that he quits the movies every day only to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   The author recalls a night last fall at the University of
Minnesota. He had gone there for a reading and the program included
a screening of ''Smoke Signals,'' which came out in 1998. All was
well until the sound suddenly went dead.
</P>
<P>
   The audience, with near-scriptural faith to the screenplay,
proceeded to fill in the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why I'm still doing this,'' Alexie says.
</P>
<P>
   There's a show biz angle as well. When the author saw John
Irving pick up an Academy Award for his own adaptation of ''The
Cider House Rules,'' he reacted like the honest man he wants to be:
He was jealous. He wants the prizes, the fame, the applause. Having
more than the average writer doesn't mean Alexie has enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just as insecure as any other artist,'' he says. ''I like
the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie once seemed fated for nothing but early death. A Spokane
Indian raised on a reservation about 50 miles from the Washington
city, he was born hydrocephalic, with water on the brain. At six
months, he underwent surgery and wasn't expected to live. When he
did survive, doctors predicted he would be severely retarded.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he became a prodigy. By age 2 he could read and by
kindergarten he had completed (if not understood) ''The Grapes of
Wrath.'' In high school, he was prom king and captain of the
basketball team. He was also the only Indian.
</P>
<P>
   ''I went to a white, Christian high school and I really had to
wear a lot of masks,'' he says. ''I remember people saying things
like, 'He doesn't care what other people think.' ... I guess people
didn't realize how much of an actor I was.
</P>
<P>
   ''To be successful, I had to be better than everyone else at
everything. I worked myself into the ground. I was working 19 hours
a day. It was my job to be popular and successful.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   It's 3 p.m. and Alexie is seated at a small kitchen table in his
office, an attic flat just off the main road in central Seattle and
a short drive from the house he shares with his wife Diane and
3-year-old son Joseph. The walls are covered by ''Smoke Signals''
posters, framed magazine covers and book jackets. An assistant
works in the other room.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie, who already has had a cappuccino and a 20-ounce latte,
drinks from a can of Diet Pepsi. He talks fast and laughs hard. He
has long boasted of an immunity from writer's block and appears
spared from talker's block as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sherman brings a real strong energy and language to Indian
literature and that energy was needed,'' says James Welch, author
of such acclaimed novels as ''Winter in the Blood'' and ''Fools
Crow.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Before Sherman, Indian literature was a bit on the sober side,
including my own writing. There were certain themes being played
out again and again -- going out into the world and coming, the
culture clash. These themes were valid, but we maybe took it a
little too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie writes as much about pop culture as about Indian culture.
His characters play basketball, watch television and listen to rock
'n' roll. One early story is called ''Because My Father Always Said
He Was the Only Indian Who Saw Jimi Hendrix Play the Star-Spangled
Banner at Woodstock.''
</P>
<P>
   Like William Faulkner, Alexie documents a community on the
losing side of a war, people whose pasts are so much larger than
the present. The humor is survivor's humor, bitter but resilient.
In the ''Lone Ranger'' collection, an Indian boy is diagnosed as
being a slow developer. ''They've been saying that about Indians
for five hundred years,'' Alexie writes.
</P>
<P>
   But the author has been criticized for spending too much time on
the ''negative'' side of reservation life. ''He always seems to
write about family battering, drinking and long-haired, shaggy,
dirty Indians,'' complains Vernon Bellcourt, an official with the
American Indian Movement.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie's response is that he simply describes what he's
observed. The author wishes there had been a Sherman Alexie when he
was kid, a successful, sober Indian (he's an alcoholic, clean for
10 years) whose best weapon was his imagination. A line by the
Indian poet Adrian Louis turned him on to writing: ''O, Uncle
Adrian, I'm in the reservation of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie wants to share what he's learned, to spread the good
news. Young people don't just talk to him about books, but about
their lives. His friend and fellow author, Craig Leslie, recalled
the time Alexie spoke to some ''at risk'' teen-agers at a community
college in Oregon City, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ''After the talk was over he sat down with these kids and talked
to them for an hour,'' Leslie said. ''Before it was over, he had
won them all over. It was a wonderful connection he established.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie can be cynical about changing the world, but he does his
best to change how Indians are perceived in the world. His great
crusade is for the right of Indians to be portrayed as they are and
not as whites -- well-meaning or otherwise -- want them to be. He
believes Indians are still romanticized, simplified. At worst,
they're bloody savages. At best, wise men in beads.
</P>
<P>
   The most common villains in his books are not soldiers or
cowboys, but whites who claim expertise about Indians. In ''Indian
Killer,'' a 1996 novel, one unsympathetic character is a white
professor who teaches a class on Indian literature. In ''Dear John
Wayne,'' a story from his new collection, an Indian woman warns an
anthropologist: ''You've colonized Indian land but I'm not about to
let you colonize my heart and mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie also has attacked fellow writers, including such best
sellers as Barbara Kingsolver and Tony Hillerman. A recent target
is Ian Frazier, a highly regarded author whose latest book, ''On
the Rez,'' tells of his time with the Oglala Sioux on the Pine
Ridge Reservation in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ''(H)e is ... guilty of objectifying the entire Oglala Nation,''
Alexie wrote in a recent review for the Los Angeles Times. ''He
admires the Oglalas because of who he believes them to be, not
because of who the Oglalas believe themselves to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Half-kiddingly, Alexie calls for a 10-year moratorium on whites
writing about Indians, just to give Indians a chance to catch up.
Even among Indians this is not a universal desire. Both Welch and
fellow author N. Scott Momaday said that anyone should be allowed
to write about anything. Both writers also defended Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   ''I read Ian Frazier's book and I think very well of it. I think
Frazier knows a good deal about Indians,'' said Momaday, winner of
a Pulitzer Prize in 1969 for the novel ''House Made of Dawn.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If a person spends as much time around a group of people as
Frazier did,'' Welch added, ''he will obviously observe things and
get to know people. And I don't think he would profess to know more
about Indians than he really does.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie's standards are highest for himself. He wants no distance
between his life and his work, a tough call when you get paid to
make things up. Like Alexie, his characters have moved from the
reservation to the city. They're making more money these days. In
the story ''Assimilation,'' a woman wryly includes herself among
the ''twenty-two American Indians who had ever felt even a moment
of privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   If Alexie were to write a piece about today, it would end like
this: Successful young Indian learns from assistant that his new
book got a good review from Publishers Weekly. After finishing an
interview, he picks up the phone, calls his wife and reads her
every word.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Smoke Signals,'' written by Sherman Alexie and released in
1998, was the first major feature film to be made entirely by
American Indians. In a recent interview, Alexie named five favorite
(excepting ''Smoke Signals, which he would have included) and five
least favorite movies/television shows/pop culture images. Because
Alexie didn't give specific rankings, listings are in alphabetical
order.
</P>
<P>
The Best
</P>
<P>
   --''Exiles'' (1961): ''I saw this once when I was in Boston. I
don't think it was ever released and I don't know much about it.
It's about Indians being relocated from the reservation to Los
Angeles. It's all improvised, and shot beautifully in black and
white. It has stuff I still haven't seen in other films. There's a
scene where one Indian guy is shaving another Indian guy -- just a
tender moment like that.''
</P>
<P>
   --''Heat'' (1995): Michael Mann's crime thriller starred Al
Pacino and Robert De Niro, but also featured the Indian actor Wes
Studi. ''Wes looks very Indian, but it was never the point of his
character. He was just a cop. That kind of casting made me very
happy. It was a great movie.''
</P>
<P>
   --''Little Big Man'' (1970): Dustin Hoffman starred as the
121-year-old who claims to have been adopted by Indians. Co-star
Chief Dan George received an Oscar nomination for best supporting
actor. ''Chief Dan George's performance has the combination of
absolute irreverence and the aura of magic. It's a stereotypical
role, the Indian grandfather, but Dan George elevates it to
something special.''
</P>
<P>
   --''One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' (1975): The Academy
Award-winning adaptation of Ken Kesey's novel about an insane
asylum. ''I love this movie. They changed it a bit from the novel,
but I still think the Indian was the hero.''
</P>
<P>
   --''Soldier Blue'' (1970): Candice Bergen starred in this
antiracist Western about the 1864 Sand Creek Indian massacre.
''It's really good in its way. Some films like this are amazingly
self-congratulatory, but this one didn't do any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
The Worst
</P>
<P>
   --''Dances With Wolves'' (1991): Kevin Costner's Academy Award
winner about a Civil War officer transformed by his friendship with
the Sioux Indians. ''As great the movie is -- technically,
artistically -- it's just so much wish fulfillment and so much
revision of history. It does a historical disservice. 'Dances With
Wolves' would have been a great movie if the cavalry had caught
him.''
</P>
<P>
   --''F Troop'': ''It was 12 Sambos running around. 'F Troop' and
'Hogans' Heroes' I would put together as shows that denigrated real
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   --''The Searchers'' (1956): John Ford's acclaimed Western about a
man's years-long pursuit of his niece and the Indians who abducted
her. ''It's one of my favorite movies, and also one of the most
anti-Indian movies ever made. I have it on DVD. I watch it once or
twice a month. It's just another one of those contradictions.''
</P>
<P>
   --''Thunderheart'' (1992): Val Kilmer stars as an FBI agent with
Indian blood whose loyalty to the white world is shaken when he
uncovers evidence of abuses against the Oglala Sioux. ''It was a
good film until the last five minutes, when all the Indians come
out with the guns.''
</P>
<P>
   --Tonto: ''Tonto is the one who started it all. He was the first
really mainstream, pop culture Indian figure, the monosyllabic
stoic Indian stereotype.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 1204 </TRAILER>
