<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Falls 200, Loses 5.6 Percent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today, pushing the Nasdaq
composite index down more than 200 points, as investors fretted
about interest rates and continued their flight from high-tech
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were reluctant to enter the market while they awaited
next week's Federal Reserve meeting. Trading was light, forcing
sellers to drop their prices in order to find buyers.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, the Nasdaq was down 200.82 at 3,374.19. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 144.02 at 10,392.73.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was off 24.86 at 1,387.28.
</P>
<P>
   Investors punished Cisco, sending the stock down 4\ to 58{.
After the close of trading Tuesday, the Internet equipment provider
reported net income of $662 million, or 9 cents per share. That
beat Wall Street analysts' expectations by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   But shares of Cisco have been out of favor all week after a
story in Barron's magazine said the stock is overvalued and
acquisitions will prove increasingly difficult because of
escalating purchase prices of smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   IBM fell 5 13/16 to 103 3/16 a day after CEO Louis Gerstner made
his annual address to Wall Street. Gerstner said the company's
financial model calls for high single-digit revenue growth, not the
brisk double-digit expansion achieved in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Motorola fell 14 7/16 to 90{
after Salomon Smith Barney cut its rating on the stock to
''outperform'' from ''buy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology stocks are under pressure because they still have
extremely high valuations,'' said William Meehan, chief market
analyst for Cantor Fitzgerald. ''Six months ago, people said it
didn't matter what they cost; you had to own them anyway. Now
there's a sense that what you pay for a stock really does matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said investors were shying away from expensive technology
stocks because they fear that rising interest rates will compromise
their rapid growth rates. The Fed is expected to raise rates by as
much as a half-percentage point at its meeting next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of merger talks sparked buying in the paper
sector. Champion International rose 6 7/16 to 72] after both
International Paper and UPM-Kymmene of Finland raised their bids
for the company. The new IP bid values Champion at about $7.3
billion, and while UPM's bid would be worth about $6.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was fairly light, continuing a string of quiet sessions
as many market players stay on the sidelines awaiting the Fed's
next move.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the NYSE came to 425.96 million shares, slightly ahead
of Tuesday's pace. Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a
7-to-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 17.24 to
473.62.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
