<HEADLINE> Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was lower against most other major
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices rose.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted at 91.07 cents in late European trading, up
from 90.25 cents on Tuesday. Later, in midday trading in New York,
the euro traded at 90.92 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,
included 109.29 Japanese yen, down from 109.52; 1.7116 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7209; 1.4956 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4938.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound was quoted at $1.5154, down from $1.5305.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 109.42 yen, and
the pound was worth $1.5108.
</P>
<P>
   Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth 2.1471 German marks,
down from 2.1659; 7.2012 French francs, down from 7.2650; 2.4193
Dutch guilders, down from 2.4407; 2,125.67 Italian lire, down from
2,144.50
</P>
<P>
   Gold closed in London at $277.70 bid per troy ounce, up from
$276.80 on Tuesday. In Zurich the bid price was $276.85, up from
$275.90. Gold in Hong Kong rose $1.00 to close at $277.95.
</P>
<P>
   Silver closed in London at $5.01 bid per troy ounce, down from
$5.03.
</P>
</TEXT>
