<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of May
14-20:
<TEXT>
<P>
   50 years ago: Humphrey Bogart and Gloria Grahame starred in the
film ''In a Lonely Place.''
</P>
<P>
   And Spencer Tracy, Joan Bennett and Elizabeth Taylor starred in
Vincente Minnelli's ''Father of the Bride.''
</P>
<P>
   30 years ago: ''Deja Vu,'' the first Crosby, Stills, Nash and
Young album, topped the U.S. chart. It was certified gold on the
first week of its release.
</P>
<P>
   And the Beatles' feature film ''Let It Be'' premiered in London
and Liverpool one week after it opened in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   25 years ago: ''French Connection II,'' starring Gene Hackman
and Fernando Rey, opened at three New York theaters.
</P>
<P>
   20 years ago: Drummer Peter Criss quit Kiss to pursue a solo
career.
</P>
<P>
   And Trevor Horn and Geoff Downes of the Buggles joined the rock
band Yes. They replaced Jon Anderson and Rick Wakeman.
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: Daryl Hall and John Oates headlined a concert for
the reopening of the legendary Apollo Theater in the New York
neighborhood of Harlem. The show was to benefit the United Negro
College Fund.
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: Frank Sinatra crooned ''Bewitched, Bothered and
Bewildered'' for a sellout crowd at Radio City Music Hall in New
York City. Sinatra sang for nearly an hour. The crowd gave him
several standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   And the Chicago City Council gave landmark status to honor Chess
Studios, the two-story, brick-and terra-cotta building where Chuck
Berry recorded ''Johnny B. Goode,'' Howlin' Wolf cut ''Spoonful''
and Muddy Waters laid down ''I'm Your Hoochie Coochie Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: Connie Chung was ousted as co-anchor of ''The
CBS Evening News,'' ending an uneasy two-year partnership with Dan
Rather. The pairing of Chung and Rather had dropped the newscast's
ratings into the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   And Calista Flockhart and Billy Crudup won the Clarence Derwent
Awards, the New York theater's top prize for most promising new
performers. Flockhart played the fragile Laura in a Broadway
revival of Tennessee Williams' ''The Glass Menagerie.'' Crudup
portrayed a passionate young tutor in Tom Stoppard's ''Arcadia.''
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: ''Star Wars: Episode One -- The Phantom Menace''
opened in theaters nationwide. The film made a record-setting $28.5
million at the box office on its first day, breaking the one-day
mark of $26.1 million set by ''The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   And the first all-English album by Puerto Rican heartthrob Ricky
Martin was No. 1 in its debut on the nation's pop music charts. By
selling 661,000 copies, ''Ricky Martin'' became the best-ever album
debut by a Hispanic artist on the mainstream Billboard charts.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken 15 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, I'm rich. I'm famous. Maybe it's too much to ask to be
talented, too.'' -- Singer-actress Cher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 1320 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
