<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Kurt Elling  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES J. GANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Kurt Elling quit the University of Chicago
Divinity School just a few credits short of receiving his master's
degree in religion and philosophy when he found a new calling as a
jazz singer.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Elling, the son of a Lutheran church musician,
has made the bandstand his pulpit, delivering a swinging but
inspirational message that somehow hangs together even when he
filters Hermann Hesse through Herbie Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving graduate school in January 1992, Elling worked as
a mover and bartender while honing his skills at local jazz clubs.
His demo tape caught the ear of Blue Note Records president Bruce
Lundvall and the label released Elling's debut album ''Close Your
Eyes'' in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Elling's first three albums each received Grammy nominations,
but these studio recordings did not capture the surprising twists
and turns of his live performances. Elling remedies that on his new
album ''Live in Chicago'' (Blue Note) recorded at the Green Mill
club, once Al Capone's North Side hangout, where the singer and his
trio led by pianist Laurence Hobgood perform regularly. On the
album, they are joined by Jon Hendricks, the pioneer of vocalese,
the style of singing original lyrics to an instrumental jazz solo,
and some Chicago musicians who mentored Elling, including
saxophonists Von Freeman and Ed Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   The album presents some of Elling's different faces: as a
Sinatralike crooner on the ballad ''(I Love You) for Sentimental
Reasons''; a swinging master of vocalese on Wayne Shorter's ''Night
Dream''; a beat hipster reciting a spoken-word narrative on ''The
Rent Party''; and a jazz philosopher writing original lyrics
inspired by St. John of the Cross as a centerpiece to ''My Foolish
Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   1. Why did you quit divinity school to become a jazz musician?
</P>
<P>
   Elling: I just got burned out on divinity school. I didn't have
that mind-set. I was having a great time in clubs and being
encouraged all the time by established musicians on the Chicago
scene. ... After about a year of moving furniture and living in a
$150-a-month basement room, I just said, 'You know what, graduate
school wasn't right and I'm really happy doing this.'
</P>
<P>
   The jazz was much more the right fit for my personality and my
way of being creative in the world. ... I think it is a very high
calling. ... When you're delivering a sermon, that's a performance
experience; you want to enlighten and inspire people. ... And in a
lot of ways, I want people to have that experience in the club but
it will be a secular thrill. ... I can be proud to say I'm a jazz
musician and that I know where I fit in a tradition.
</P>
<P>
   2. How do you see yourself fitting into the jazz vocal
tradition?
</P>
<P>
   Elling: I'm firmly in the vocalese, straight-ahead jazz singing
tradition of Eddie Jefferson, Jon Hendricks, Annie Ross and Mark
Murphy. I hope to say that I've also learned from Frank Sinatra
about swagger. ... Sinatra had the ultimate mastery of audience
control, personal poise and was able to enjoy himself and swing
very hard. ... And I've really tried to learn from Betty Carter to
be an explorer, to be fearless and to try to be a bandleader.
</P>
<P>
   3. What was it like to work with Jon Hendricks?
</P>
<P>
   Elling: Jon was very gracious and generous to come to Chicago.
He's one of my most important antecedents on the jazz family tree.
... And it was a thrill to have him on my gig. Jon Hendricks
perfected the art form of vocalese which Eddie Jefferson invented.
He really showed how ingenious a lyric could be -- how humorous, how
articulate. He has just an incredible sense of wit and swinging
timing.
</P>
<P>
   4. What side of you does the new album capture that your
previous albums don't?
</P>
<P>
   Elling: With every record we've made, we have gotten the
response that as good as those records have been they haven't
captured how much energy and interaction there is with an audience.
... A lot of people have said they heard the first couple of
recordings and did not really get it, but when they saw us live
then everything fell into place. We do a lot of disparate creative
acts. ... When people are on the scene it makes perfect sense that
we would shift from the most far outside screaming howl of the soul
to the most simple pure melody of a beautiful standard ballad.
</P>
<P>
   5. Why do you choose to stay in Chicago rather than move to New
York, the jazz capital?
</P>
<P>
   Elling: New York is the most spectacular city on the planet. ...
But I get a lot of artistic opportunities in Chicago that I wonder
if I would get there. I've been commissioned by the Steppenwolf
Theatre to write new shows that involved a mixture of acting or
dance and my music. I wrote a show that is a critical exploration
of the work of Allen Ginsberg and the Beat poets. ... I was
commissioned by the city of Chicago to write and direct the
performance art segment of their millennium celebrations. ...
</P>
<P>
   We have a steady Wednesday gig at the Green Mill, and I'm able
to maintain a band. That's as much about staying in Chicago as
anything else. It means we can explore new music. ... I feel like
I'm still learning what it is to be a jazz musician.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The official Kurt Elling Web site is: http://www.kurtelling.com
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for Blue Note Records is: http://www.bluenote.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
