<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Makeup Tips for Not-So-Famous Faces  </HEADLINE>
By LISI de BOURBON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Victoria Jackson dreamed of becoming a Hollywood
makeup artist. And she's worked hard to make that dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from beauty school, Jackson went to work at the
Clinique cosmetics counter of a Westwood, Calif., department store.
There she learned that many women need help doing their own makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ''That has really been my motivation since I got into this: to
make makeup accessible to women,'' said Jackson, now 44. ''When you
use it, and if you use it the right way ... it really makes a
difference in the quality of your life and it can be a powerful
tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson worked as a free-lance makeup artist, enhancing the
faces of Katharine Hepburn, Brooke Shields, Rene Russo, Kate
Capshaw, Kathleen Turner and Jessica Lange.
</P>
<P>
   She adopted a ''less is more'' mantra, formulating her own
foundation to help clients achieve a more natural look.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted something that would make a person's skin look
perfect and that I could use for film, for television, for print,
and that kind of got me into (the) manufacturing mode,'' she said
in a telephone interview from Los Angeles, where she lives with her
husband and three children.
</P>
<P>
   She created Victoria Jackson Cosmetics, a line of color
cosmetics based on her ''no makeup makeup'' philosophy. She
promotes her products on a Web site (http://www.vjcosmetics.com)
and with infomercials, which began airing in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson taught a ''makeup for photography'' class at the
University of California at Los Angeles for eight years, which
enabled her to develop a blueprint for her infomercials.
</P>
<P>
   Though informercials have proven to be a successful advertising
vehicle for her products, ''I think because my line is sold through
an infomercial, it's been harder for the cosmetics industry to look
at me and decide whether I'm very credible,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   However, her natural approach to makeup has become a hit in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson shares the techniques she perfected on celebrity faces
in her new book, ''Make Up Your Life: Every Woman's Guide to the
Power of Makeup'' (CliffStreet Books, an imprint of HarperCollins;
$27.50).
</P>
<P>
   The book teaches women how to use concealer, mascara, lipliner
and blush.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to tell you how to do it and also tell you why it's
going to make a difference, and I want to give you a kick in the
pants and get you to the next level and feel good about yourself,''
she says. ''As long as we're stuck in always worrying about how we
look, we can't move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Jackson argues that makeup can help women stop
worrying about their appearance, boosting their self-confidence so
they can deal with weightier issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've learned that it's absolutely 100 percent true that when
you look better, you feel better, and when you feel better, you
have more success in life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One myth she wants to debunk is that women need ''perfect
features'' to be beautiful. Instead, she says, perfection exists in
how you feel about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ''Though I've never seen you, if you're comparing yourself to a
media icon, I know you're engaged in a losing battle,'' she writes.
''There's so much airbrushing and touching up of fashion photos,
the models in real life don't even measure up to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Successful women, regardless of how beautiful they are, radiate
a certain glow that reflects the conviction and confidence inside,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for Victoria Jackson Cosmetics is:
http://www.vjcosmetics.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
