<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Celebrities of the Past Return  </HEADLINE>
By BOB THOMAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Four weekends a year, in the ballroom of a
Holiday Inn just over the hill from Hollywood, vintage celebrities
-- or near-celebrities -- arrive to meet their public.
</P>
<P>
   And this is not just any Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, it's ''Beverly Garland's Holiday Inn,'' owned and
operated by the 1950s B-movie queen in a corner of the San Fernando
Valley known as North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Names from the past, who are seated along rows of folding tables
like exhibits at a trade show, greet hordes of adoring fans who
have paid $10 to file past them -- and up to $25 more for
autographed photos. Sometimes Garland sits at one of the tables.
</P>
<P>
   Don't have exact change for the glossies? No problem. These
one-time stars of stage and screen will give you change --
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Hollywood Collectors and Celebrities Show, where
retired actors, singers, even bit players, can return to the
limelight, if only for a Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The show is run by Ray Courts and his wife Sharon. Courts, 53,
grew up in Milton, W. Va., a town so small it didn't have a movie
theater. He compensated by watching films on television, especially
Westerns. He began attending Western nostalgia conventions, which
featured old-time cowboy stars but no memorabilia. He began
collecting Western paraphernalia and soon became a dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we started the show in 1991, everybody thought we were
crazy,'' said Courts. ''To build a show around celebrities?
</P>
<P>
   ''But you know something? I was a dealer for 23 years. I would
go out to California every now and then to do a show. I discovered
the promoters would not even let the celebrities come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   One promoter told Courts that celebrities were a distraction and
that he wanted collectors to spend all their time and money with
the dealers and the vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'You're crazy. I came 3,000 miles. I want to see
celebrities.' So my wife and I started this show,'' Courts
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The couple started their enterprise modestly, offering
celebrities and memorabilia relating to Western movies. As the show
grew, it attracted Mickey Rooney, Jonathan Winters, Dom DeLuise,
Gene Autry, Steve Allen and Jayne Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, the hotel parking lot is jammed, and all
the parking spaces for blocks around are taken. A few hundred
excited fans wait in line for the 10 a.m. opening, eager to find
their longtime idols.
</P>
<P>
   When the doors open, the crowd pours in. By the end of the day,
about 2,500 fans will have attended the show.
</P>
<P>
   Courts stands by the entrance, attending to myriad matters,
including helping celebrities find their assigned tables -- and
perhaps check a little of their dignity at the door.
</P>
<P>
   This morning's most popular attraction is Don Knotts, 75, one of
the stars of the '60s sitcom ''The Andy Griffith Show.'' He is
signing his book, ''Barney Fife and Other Characters I Have
Known.'' The line extends out the hall and around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Knotts, wearing a cap and glasses, signs his name, leaning over
just a few inches from the books and photos. When asked if the
adoring crowd makes him nervous, he laughs indulgently and says:
''Not really. I'm here to sell the book. I'm having fun. I'd come
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Adams, Nanette Fabray, Linda Christian, Jon Provost
(''Lassie''), Morgan Brittany (''Dallas''), Susanna Foster (the
1943 film ''Phantom of the Opera'') and singer Gogi Grant are among
those in attendance. Charlton Heston and Penny Singleton (the 1938
film ''Blondie'') are due at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''This show's OK,'' Adams, 74, remarks. ''What else is there to
do on a Saturday afternoon except watch golf on TV?''
</P>
<P>
   With his white hair and full mustache, he is hardly recognizable
as the klutzy secret agent Maxwell Smart of the sitcom ''Get
Smart,'' which ran from 1965-1970. The show was revived briefly in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, the sultry singer of the 1940s and '50s, is seated behind
a sign that reads: ''Photos $5, CDs $20, vintage photos $3.'' She
is talking to a young man who claims to have collected all her
single records. He buys a CD of songs from ''The Helen Morgan
Story.'' Grant dubbed the vocals of the 1957 film for star Ann
Blyth.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love this show,'' she insists. ''What could be wrong with
somebody coming up and saying, 'I loved your records'? At my age,
75, it's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Does she still work?
</P>
<P>
   ''Once in a while. I don't have an agent, but if somebody calls
and wants me, I'll go. The voice is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is a famous face. But tiny Margaret Pellegrini,
wearing a starched fairy-tale dress, looks like a munchkin, the
role she played in the 1939 film ''The Wizard of Oz.'' She is one
of three munchkins attending the show.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was 15 when I did the movie, I'm 76 now,'' she declares in
her midget voice. ''I didn't keep working after 'The Wizard.' I got
married and had two children. Now I have four grandchildren and
seven great-grandchildren. They're all big people.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the wall of the big room, concessionaires sell movie
photos, advertising posters and other collectibles. Five other
areas in the hotel offer posters, photos, books and a variety of
memorabilia. Concessionaires pay for the space; celebrities don't.
</P>
<P>
   The Courts conduct business from their home in Spring Hill, Fla.
The couple will take the show to Chicago on May 20-21 and again on
Oct. 7-8, then it's on to San Francisco Nov. 18-19. The Courts pay
for air travel and hotels for the 30 to 40 celebrities who attend
the out-of-town shows.
</P>
<P>
   Down one of the aisles this Saturday sit William Sanderson, Tony
Papenfuss and John Voldstad.
</P>
<P>
   Who?
</P>
<P>
   Fans remember them as Larry, Darryl and Darryl, the bumbling
handymen of the ''Newhart'' sitcom, which ran on CBS from 1982 to
1990. Larry spoke on the series, the two Darryls didn't. This is
their third appearance at the show.
</P>
<P>
   Have they been working since ''Newhart''ended?
</P>
<P>
   ''Intermittently,'' admitted Voldstad. ''People didn't know
whether we could talk. They bring us in to auditions just to hear
us talk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 1323 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Stocks Down on Tech Weakness  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks ended mostly lower Wednesday,
dragged down by falls on the tech-heavy Nasdaq, which looked to be
headed for its third consecutive weak close.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Stock Market fell 5 percent in morning trading in the
United States as investors continued to punish Internet equipment
maker Cisco Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell
7.66 points, or 2.0 percent, to 378.71, with the technology sector
the worst performer, down 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, was down 8.75 points at
424.90. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 116.90 to 5,065.9,
while the Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Index was 111.7 points lower at
4,815.5.
</P>
<P>
   The media sector was hit by disappointing third-quarter results
from British heavyweight BSKyB, which posted a third-quarter pretax
loss of 28.4 million pounds ($44 million), from profit of 16.0
million pounds ($25 million) a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 0.4 percent to 6,100.6.
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index was down 2.2 percent to 7,120.86, the
Paris CAC-40 Index was 1.7 percent lower to 6,263.34, Milan's
MIBtel Index was down 0.3 percent to 31,214 and Amsterdam's AEX
Index fell by 0.9 percent to 657.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
