<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yo-Yo Ma Teaches Cello in Taiwan  </HEADLINE>
By MARCOS CALO MEDINA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Whether it's his choice of performance
music or his teaching methods, cellist Yo-Yo Ma likes to challenge
his audience.
</P>
<P>
   During a master class Wednesday at the start of a weeklong visit
to Taiwan, Ma duck-stepped and goose-walked around the stage to
illustrate what romantic music shouldn't sound like. A student
cellist could barely hide her giggle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Relax! Don't hold your arms too close to your body. Let the
energy build!'' Ma said in fluent Chinese, his arms flailing in
wide arcs.
</P>
<P>
   But when he took the student's cello and played a brief passage
from the 19th-century showpiece -- the Saint-Saens A minor concerto
-- it was apparent the instrument was being cradled by a virtuoso.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to draw the energy from all the sounds around you,
and focus that on your instrument. Then make your statement with a
bang!'' Ma said, his fingers a blur on the fingerboard as the
cello's sonority flooded the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ''You must be one with the audience. You must enlarge your space
and interact with the audience as one,'' Ma said as his audience of
mostly music students was held in rapt silence.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Ma takes a break from his patrician performances of
Bach and Beethoven and brings his acclaimed hybrid interpretations
of chamber music and American fiddle tunes to Taipei's National
Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   He calls his latest offbeat project ''Appalachian Journey,'' and
he teams up with fiddler Mark O'Connor and double bass player Edgar
Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Paris to Taiwanese parents in 1955, Ma took his first
cello lessons from his father at the age of 4. At 5, Ma gave his
first public recital, and went on to the Juilliard School of Music
in New York to study with cello master Leonard Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Since establishing himself at 19 as one of the world's most
sought-after cellists, Ma has challenged both Taiwanese and
mainland Chinese audiences, whose musical tastes are traditionally
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate Hong Kong's return to China in 1997, Ma played
Symphony 1997 by leading mainland Chinese composer Tan Dun. He also
plans to take his ''Silk Road'' project -- where he plays
traditional folk music on his 1712 Stradivarius -- to China later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The project is not the first of its kind for Ma, whose appetite
for world music embraces the Argentine Tango, music from the bush
peoples of the African Kalahari Desert, contemporary American music
and jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just like journalism. You pay attention to interesting
things around you and make a mental note. Then you work on them
later,'' Ma said during an interview broadcast this week on
Taiwan's TVBS cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Ma has also played the music of composer John Williams on the
soundtrack of the 1997 film ''Seven Years in Tibet,'' in which Brad
Pitt plays an Austrian who scales the Himalayas and meets a young
Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   The film was banned in China, and Ma's involvement displeased
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Ma hasn't been heard in Beijing's concert halls since then. He
fell short of calling it a ban, but acknowledged that China has not
been part of his concert schedule for some time, the China Times, a
leading Taiwanese daily, reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ma said he was on good enough terms with Beijing to meet Chinese
Premier Zhu Rongji in the United States last year. During that
meeting, the cellist received the go-ahead to take his ''Silk
Road'' project on tour in China, the newspaper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 1417 </TRAILER>
