<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq, Dow Both Shed Nearly 200  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today, pushing both the Dow
Jones industrial average and the Nasdaq composite index down nearly
200 points apiece, as investors fretted about interest rates and
continued their flight from high-tech issues.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading, the Nasdaq was down 184.10 at 3,400.91.
The Dow Jones industrial average was down 192.13 at 10,344.62.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was off 30.06 at 1,382.08.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks bore the brunt of investors' distress today,
with several industry leaders falling sharply. Cisco fell 3\ to
59{. After the close of trading Tuesday, the Internet equipment
provider reported net income of $662 million, or 9 cents per share.
That beat Wall Street analysts' expectations by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   But shares of Cisco have been out of favor all week after a
story in Barron's magazine said the stock is overvalued and
acquisitions will prove increasingly difficult because of
escalating purchase prices of smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   IBM fell 5 15/16 to 103 1/16 a day after CEO Louis Gerstner made
his annual address to Wall Street. Gerstner said the company's
financial model calls for high single-digit revenue growth, not the
brisk double-digit expansion achieved in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Motorola fell 15 13/16 to 89[
after Salomon Smith Barney cut its rating on the stock to
''outperform'' from ''buy.'' Analyst Alex Cena said Motorola
recently lost a major customer to competitor Nortel, limiting its
potential for dramatic earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   The downbeat news on three technology bellwethers forced
investors to reconsider the high prices of many stocks in the
sector, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology stocks are under pressure because they still have
extremely high valuations,'' said William Meehan, chief market
analyst for Cantor Fitzgerald. ''Six months ago, people said it
didn't matter what they cost; you had to own them anyway. Now
there's a sense that what you pay for a stock really does matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said investors were shying away from expensive technology
stocks because they fear that rising interest rates will compromise
their rapid growth rates. The Fed is expected to raise rates by as
much as a half-percentage point at its meeting next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of merger talks sparked buying in the paper
sector. Champion International rose 5} to 72 1/16 after both
International Paper and UPM-Kymmene of Finland raised their bids
for the company. The new IP bid values Champion at about $7.3
billion, and while UPM's bid would be worth about $6.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was fairly light, continuing a string of quiet sessions
as many market players stay on the sidelines awaiting the Fed's
next move. On the NYSE, 644.89 million shares had changed hands as
of early afternoon, compared with 589.02 million at the same time
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two sessions, investors will receive some economic
data that could indicate whether the economy is growing fast enough
to merit a sharp rate increase. On Thursday, the Commerce
Department will report on retail sales in the month of April. On
Friday, the Labor Deparment will release its Producer Price Index,
which measures inflationary pressures at the wholesale level.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 18.92 to
471.94.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-3 margin on
the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
