<HEADLINE> Weather Lifts Grains, Soybeans Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices rose sharply Wednesday
on the Chicago Board of Trade after a federal agency said the
pattern of hotter, drier weather than usual may continue well into
summer.
</P>
<P>
   A rally that began on the strength of forecasts for warm weather
in the next few days accelerated when the U.S. National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration suggested the ongoing drought could last
months longer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a conflicting statement by the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration on Tuesday that indicated La Nina is over,
commodity funds leaped in to snatch up corn and soybean futures on
increased prospects for drought impact on row crops this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat followed higher in sympathy with the top two crops.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose 6{ cents to $2.75 a bushel; July
corn rose 5{ cents to $2.44\ a bushel; July oats rose 2\ cents to
$1.23 a bushel; July soybeans rose 14 cents to $5.70 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures declined on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .28 cent to 68.42 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle fell 1.45 cent to 83.87 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .63 cent to 72.82 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell the
limit 3 cents to 87.57 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
