<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elian's great-uncle and Castro's daughter speak at rally  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) -- A chilly wind blew in from New York
Harbor as about 200 Cuban-Americans at Liberty State Park cheered
speeches from Fidel Castro's estranged daughter and Elian
Gonzalez's great-uncle urging that the boy be allowed to remain in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez decried the ''injustice'' of the 6-year-old
being removed from the home of his Miami relatives: ''The people
who took Elian at gunpoint have betrayed America.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, ''I'm extremely proud to be next to the
Statue of Liberty,'' as the boisterous group faced the harbor
landmark a quarter-mile away.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd waved Cuban flags and held handmade posters bearing
reproductions of the photograph of an armed federal agent
confronting Elian in the Miami home.
</P>
<P>
   Alina Fernandez, Castro's daughter, said the rally is ''a big
opportunity'' to show people Cuba is a police state. ''This tragedy
would not have happened if Cuba was free,'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know all too well the drive to escape the suffocation of
repression,'' said Fernandez, who fled the country in 1993 and is
one of her father's fiercest critics. She lives in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was among those in more than a dozen cities around the
nation the day before a federal appeals court in Atlanta considers
a request by Elian's relatives to grant the boy political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Northern New Jersey is home to the second-largest Cuban exile
population outside of Florida, including Maria Cardenas, 46, of
Hoboken, who came to the Jersey City rally.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it was important to come here and support my Cuban
people,'' said Cardenas, who works at Morristown Memorial
Hospital's dental clinic as an administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Elian would have a better life in the United States than under
the Castro regime in Cuba, she said: ''You don't have any say in
your kids in Cuba. You don't have any control of your kids.''
</P>
<P>
   A coordinator of United Cuban Organizations, Clara Nibot, said
she attended to defend the freedoms that formed the basis for the
United States and for Elian to remain in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the child can be with his father, why can't he be where his
mother intended him to be?'' said Nibot, 55, of Bergenfield.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's mother and others drowned when they attempted to reach
Florida in a small boat in late November. Elian survived stayed
with his Miami relatives until taken by federal agents April 22.
Elian is now staying with his father, stepmother and 6-month-old
half-brother in Maryland. The father wants to return to Cuba with
him.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey event was sponsored by a Newark-based
telecommunications company, IDT Corp., to promote the launch last
week of its FreeAtLast.com service, which offers free Internet
access, e-mail, and Internet phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Posters for the service decorated the portable stage used by the
speakers, and an IDT van outfitted as a rolling kosher kitchen
distributed bag lunches.
</P>
<P>
   IDT paid the travel expenses for Gonzalez and Fernandez, and is
to make a contribution to a charity operated by Fernandez, company
spokesman Gil Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Company president Jim Courter, a former New Jersey congressman,
also addressed the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''That Statue of Liberty is not just for the people in the
United States,'' Courter said. ''The Statue of Liberty stands for
freedom for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jersey City Mayor Bret Schundler introduced the speakers,
decrying communism and Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just as we have freedom and human rights, the people of Cuba
deserve to have their human rights, too,'' Schundler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
