<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State court overturns Greenwich's beach restriction  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Greenwich's exclusive beaches must be
opened to out-of-towners, the state Appellate Court ruled
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's second highest court found the residents-only policy
at the town's parks and beaches violates a public trust doctrine
that says municipalities hold parks on behalf of all citizens.
</P>
<P>
   A resident of nearby Stamford sued the town of Greenwich in 1995
after he was denied access to Greenwich Point, a 147-acre park with
a beach on Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plaintiff claims that because he is a resident of this
state, he is entitled to access to the park ... regardless of the
fact that he is not a resident of the town,'' Judge Edward
O'Connell wrote in the unanimous decision. ''We agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich First Selectman Lolly Prince said she expects the
town's governing board Thursday to approve an appeal to the state
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has been the intention of the town to follow this as far as
we have to,'' she said. ''We felt the original decision was well
reasoned and legally sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenden Leydon, who filed the lawsuit, said he would object to a
hearing before the Supreme Court since he asked the high court for
a ruling -- and was denied -- when he filed the Appellate Court
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is confident, though, that the ruling would stand.
</P>
<P>
   ''At one point in the decision, there's almost a full page of
citations of cases where it was decided if a town holds a park, it
does so for the general public,'' said Leydon, 32, a Stamford
attorney. ''The string of decisions goes back to 1824.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Connecticut towns let nonresidents use their beaches, but
charge them exorbitant parking fees or require them to walk to the
waterfront. Greenwich, however, bans both walkers and joggers and
allows out-of-towners to use the beaches only when they are
accompanied by a resident pay a $6 fee.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich officials maintain a 1919 special act of the state
Legislature granted the town an exception to any public trust
doctrine. Residents say reversing the policy would damage beach
ecology and increase traffic at Greenwich Point, an already
overburdened area.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a limited amount of space that people can use and
still be able to protect the ecosystem,'' Prince said. ''It's a
delicate balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Leydon argued that banning nonresidents violates the First
Amendment right to freedom of expression. He claimed the town's
policy is rooted in an elitist attitude in this suburb known for
its celebrities and wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Edward R. Karazin Jr., after a weeklong
civil trial in 1998, sided with the town.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Court ruled the judge erred when he found the
public trust doctrine did not apply because of the 1919 act.
</P>
<P>
   ''The language of the act does not expressly limit use of the
public beach to residents only,'' O'Connell wrote. ''The language
clarifies that the town's parks and beaches are intended to exist
for the benefit of the public, including the town's residents.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling could potentially affect dozens of other shoreline
communities in the state. Only 30 miles of Connecticut's 78 miles
of sandy beach are public, according to the state Department of
Environmental Protection. The remaining 48 miles are under various
restrictions -- either privately run or under the control of
associations.
</P>
<P>
   The court declined to rule on Leydon's First Amendment claim
because the judges do not consider constitutional issues if they
can otherwise decide a case.
</P>
<P>
   Leydon said that when the case is over he will take advantage of
Greenwich's sandy shores.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wouldn't say this was solely to go to Greenwich Point; it
was more to establish a principle,'' he said. ''But I definitely
plan on going. I'm probably going to have a little party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-10-00 1555 </TRAILER>
