<HEADLINE> Bishop Egan, candidate for archbishop, celebrates Mass under mediaspotlight  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Bishop Edward M. Egan, a leading
candidate to become archbishop of New York, made light of the media
spotlight as he celebrated Mass Wednesday in honor of two longtime
parish priests.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters from Connecticut and New York crowded near the gray
stone pulpit at St. Augustine Cathedral to hear whether Egan would
address the successor to Cardinal John O'Connor, who died last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, in a deep and resonant voice, spoke of the first time he
met Pope John Paul II and the significance of the Mass to priests
and congregants.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing is more important to me -- nothing -- than to be united
with the priests of this diocese as a brother who stands at the
altar in the person of Jesus Christ,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He joked several times to the chuckles of parishioners that the
usually quiet noon service had some guests from the media.
</P>
<P>
   During the quiet ceremony, cameras clicked shots of Egan, who
was dressed in a white robe with gold trim and a reddish-pink
skullcap.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the Mass, Egan left the altar to wish peace
upon parishioners, then moved to the other side of the church and
stood before the cameras and reporters to say, ''Peace be with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank you to our visitors,'' Egan said at the close of the
service. ''We extend to all of them a cordial invitation to be at
the 12:10 Mass every day here at St. Augustine's Church. You are
always welcome here.''
</P>
<P>
   He left at the end of a procession of other priests and altar
attendants. He did not give a statement to the media.
</P>
<P>
   The service was arranged a year ago, in honor of the 25th year
of priesthood for the Rev. Robert G. Pohley of Sacred Heart Church
of Stamford and the Rev. Dennis Bludnicki of St. Ambrose Church in
Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who had been archbishop since 1984, died last week and
was buried Monday. Official word of his successor comes from the
Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners wished Egan well if he should go to New York. They
praised his work to strengthen Roman Catholic schools and draw more
young men into the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's done quite a bit for our parish here. He's given his all
for us,'' said Juan Hernandez, who gave Egan a thumbs up sign as
Egan shook hands with parishioners. ''New York is a big city. A lot
more help is needed over there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
