<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Uganda Near Confrontation  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Erstwhile allies Rwanda and Uganda edged
closer to serious confrontation Wednesday, as they accused each
other of setting off another round of fighting in northern Congo
and Rwanda's top army commander warned of a large buildup of
Ugandan troops on their common border.
</P>
<P>
   President Paul Kagame said he was hopeful that a meeting in
Tanzania this weekend with his Ugandan counterpart, Yoweri
Museveni, would prevent an escalation and resolve tensions that
soared after the two armies clashed in the northern Congolese city
of Kisangani last week.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting Wednesday in Kigali between Rwandan army commander
Brig. Gen. Kayumba Nyamwasa and his Ugandan counterpart, Maj. Gen.
Jeje Odongo, yielded no concrete results. Later, Nyamwasa said
efforts to calm tensions were seriously undermined by Uganda's
''warlike rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   Nyamwasa said the Ugandans had deployed troops along their
common border, but both he and Kagame ruled out an immediate
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We shall remain in our positions. As long as they deploy in
their own country, I'm not concerned at all,'' Nyamwasa said.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda's government-owned New Vision newspaper reported
Wednesday that about 1,000 troops were digging in 2 miles north of
the Kagitumba border crossing with Rwanda, and even more soldiers
were on the move along the mountainous frontier to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers from Ruhengeri, 60 miles northwest of Kigali, said
they had seen truckloads of Rwandan soldiers heading north toward
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial traffic across the busy border has virtually ceased,
and only a few cars were crossing, the travelers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has been no troop movement on our side of the border.
But troops have been moving on the Ugandan side,'' Kagame said
during a joint appearance with Clare Short, the British minister
for overseas development. She called the situation ''a little bit
worrying'' and said Britain, the major donor and a key ally to both
countries, would try to calm things down on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have to call each other enemies ... Underlying causes
of this are not clear to some of us. We have to find a solution,''
Kagame said.
</P>
<P>
   His adviser, Theogene Rudasingwa, said Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapathe would join the Rwandan and Ugandan presidents at
a meeting Sunday at the Lake Victoria port of Mwanza.
</P>
<P>
   The participation of South African President Thabo Mbeki had yet
to be confirmed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since last Friday, the two armies have battled in the northern
Congolese city of Kisangani, leaving at least 15 civilians dead and
100 wounded. At least 15 soldiers were also killed, including five
Rwandans, Nyamwasa said.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda and Rwanda back rival Congolese rebel factions opposed to
President Laurent Kabila. Troops from both countries are deployed
in Kisangani in support of the rebels, and both countries view the
city, with its two decaying airports, as a strategic rear base for
their units deployed elsewhere in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Some 5,500 U.N. troops are supposed to deploy in Congo to
protect unarmed U.N. military observers as part of the peace
process to end the 22-month civil war in which Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia are backing Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a U.N. Security Council team led by U.S. Ambassador
Richard Holbrooke helped mediate an agreement between Museveni and
Kagame to hand control of Kisangani, Congo's third-largest city,
over to a U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. team from the Congolese capital, Kinshasa, was expected
to land on Thursday at Bangoka airport where the Rwandans and
Ugandans clashed to inspect the logistical needs for the larger
U.N. force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
