<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President Weizman Collapses  </HEADLINE>
By DANA BUDEIRI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Days before he is expected to announce his
retirement, Israeli President Ezer Weizman collapsed due to
dehydration Wednesday but later recovered and attended an awards
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman, 76, collapsed on the lawn of his residence after
hosting the diplomatic corps at a reception marking Israel's 52nd
Independence Day. Two bodyguards picked him up and assisted him as
he entered his residence with faltering steps.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor diagnosed dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   ''The President feels good, it was only a fleeting moment of
dizziness,'' Dr. Felix Umanski said on Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Weizman stood erect and sang the Israeli
national anthem at the annual Israel Prize awards ceremony. He also
delivered the prize to the winners.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman said last month that he would step down this
Independence Day, which began Tuesday night, due to ill health. But
he said he was delaying his resignation while police investigated
hundreds of thousands of dollars in gifts he accepted from a French
millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Police recommended that Weizman not be indicted. He then said he
was waiting for the attorney general's report, expected next week,
before he announces his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman has admitted accepting cash gifts from French textiles
magnate Edouard Sarousi, but says he did nothing wrong. Police said
his failure to report the gifts constituted fraud, but that the
statute of limitations has run out.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman's second five-year term is supposed to expire in 2003.
The 120-member parliament, the Knesset, elects the president. In
informal polls, legislators have heavily favored former Prime
Minister Shimon Peres, currently a Cabinet minister, as Weizman's
successor.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman is known for his outspoken, plain language. He has
managed to offend women, gays, the Orthodox and Diaspora Jews in
his many tirades. Yet his very outspokenness -- and his tireless
work with the war-wounded and with bereaved families -- endear him
to many.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman has been an influential backer of Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's peace initiatives. There were calls for his resignation
even before the money scandal broke from hard-liners who said he
was undermining the presidency's impartiality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
