<HEADLINE> Nieman Fellows Named  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Harvard University has named 12 American
journalists to the 63rd class of Nieman Fellows for the 2000-2001
academic year.
</P>
<P>
   The Nieman Fellowships, the oldest mid-career fellowships for
journalists in the world, were established in 1938 by Agnes Wahl
Nieman in memory of her husband, Lucius, founder and publisher of
The Milwaukee Journal.
</P>
<P>
   They are awarded for an academic year of study in any school of
the university. More than 1,000 American and international
journalists have studied at Harvard since the program began in
1938.
</P>
<P>
   The American journalists will be joined by approximately 12
international journalists to be named later this month, university
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nieman fellows announced Tuesday are:
</P>
<P>
   -- Ken Armstrong, legal affairs writer, Chicago Tribune;
</P>
<P>
   -- Don Aucoin, television critic, The Boston Globe;
</P>
<P>
   -- Kirstin Downey Grimsley, staff writer, The Washington Post;
</P>
<P>
   -- Anne Fitzgerald, agribusiness writer, The Des Moines Register;
</P>
<P>
   -- Kelli S. Hewett, city hall/special projects writer, The Dothan
Eagle of Alabama;
</P>
<P>
   -- J.R. Moehringer, Atlanta bureau chief, Los Angeles Times;
</P>
<P>
   -- Mark Pothier, executive editor, Memorial Press Group in
Plymouth;
</P>
<P>
   -- Linda Robinson, Latin America bureau chief, US News &AMP; World
Report;
</P>
<P>
   -- Ron Stodghill II, midwest bureau chief, based in Chicago for
Time magazine;
</P>
<P>
   -- Andrew Sussman, senior program producer, ''The World,'' a
co-production of the BBC World Service, Public Radio International
and WGBH Boston;
</P>
<P>
   -- Peter Turnley, photojournalist based in Paris, Newsweek; and
</P>
<P>
   -- Nuri Vallbona, photojournalist, Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
