<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Fights Over Elderly Drugs  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Democrats closed ranks Wednesday
behind President Clinton's plan to create a new Medicare
prescription drug benefit, preparing for an election-year wrangle
with Republicans who prefer expanding access to private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides were calling for a bipartisan push to resolve the
issue, but many observers say chances for a compromise this year
are low.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very good issue in the election; it will be tougher to
enact and make the plan work,'' said Bob Blendon, a Harvard
professor of health policy and political analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Blendon predicted lawmakers ''will get a more consistent
proposal that they're going to run on. We'll have two divergent
views, but they're not going to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, about 60 House and Senate Democrats came to the
White House to announce that they had solidified party support for
legislation based on Clinton's year-old proposal to add drug
coverage to Medicare that any senior citizen could get for about
$25 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prescription drugs are an integral part of medicine today.
They ought to be an integral part of Medicare,'' said Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are pitting their plan against an alternative
being developed by House Republicans, which would help senior
citizens get private drug insurance and provide subsidies for those
with the lowest incomes and highest bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's enough to stop at $15,000 income limit to
give help on prescription drugs,'' Clinton said of the GOP plan.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans made it clear in a letter sent to Clinton on
Wednesday that they are equally troubled by the Democrats'
approach. They have scheduled a hearing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are concerned that the government would have too heavy a
hand in controlling the drug benefit, denying some seniors the
right to choose the coverage that best fits their needs,'' said the
letter, signed by Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, and
Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., who heads the panel's health care
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans deny the charge that their plan would help only
retirees qualifying for direct subsidies. They say that the
government would also provide financial support to help insurance
companies develop new drug policies that would result in more
choices and lower prices for all senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies continue to criticize the Democrats' plan as
''Washington command and control of health care,'' while the
insurance industry has raised concerns about whether private drug
insurance policies of the kind Republicans envision would be
affordable.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare benefit outlined by congressional Democrats on
Wednesday would pay for 50 percent of the cost of the first $2,000
in prescriptions annually, rising to $5,000 by 2009. Low-income
beneficiaries up to 135 percent of the government's poverty level
would receive subsidies, and beneficiaries with slightly higher
incomes would receive a slightly reduced subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Democrats said the plan envisions catastrophic
coverage after out-of-pocket expenses exceed a certain level,
likely $3,000 to $4,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan left out proposals favored by some Democrats to
directly curb prescription prices -- such as by requiring drug
makers to sell to pharmacies that serve the elderly at discounts
received by other federal programs, including the veteran's health
care system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
