<HEADLINE> Bush Winks At Linguistic Failings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Linguists rejoice. There's hope yet for
George W. Bush, who when at a loss for a word to describe Israel
once labeled the important U.S. ally a ''buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor and Republican presidential candidate joked
Wednesday that he had ordered a batch of ''Verbal Advantage''
vocabulary tapes, which promise users ''a Harvard graduate's
vocabulary in just 15 minutes a day.''
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Bush jokes with his traveling press corps
that he has no chance in the general election against Democrat Al
Gore because the vice president graduated from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush graduated from Harvard Business School, he has an
undergraduate degree from Yale, an Ivy League rival to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   In a note written across a Verbal Advantage magazine ad, Bush
told a television producer who graduated from Harvard: ''I have
just ordered several. What do you think? Do I have a chance to have
a Harvard vocabulary?''
</P>
</TEXT>
