<HEADLINE> Swiss Principal Held on Abuse  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- The principal of an exclusive Swiss
school that Britain's Princess Beatrice is to attend is being held
in prison on charges that he abused his own children, an
investigating judge said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Richard McDonald, the principal of Aiglon College, has been
arrested and charged but has yet to appear in court, Judge Jacques
Antenen said, confirming a news report in the Lausanne daily 24
Heures. Antenen gave no further details and declined to specify the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Aiglon spokesman Frank Klein said McDonald took a sabbatical in
January and did not return to his job in April as planned because
of ''domestic circumstances'' that made it impossible for him to
continue at the school.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is the latest to hit the $26,300-a-year school.
</P>
<P>
   In March, three teen-age girls were sexually assaulted at Aiglon
by an unknown man. The school confirmed the attack, but denied
there had been a sexual element.
</P>
<P>
   Investigating magistrate Pierre Veillon told 24 Heures he could
not understand why Aiglon issued the denial. ''The victims have
been reinterviewed, and sexual acts did indeed take place,''
Veillon told the paper.
</P>
<P>
   All three girls are now back in classes, the school said. There
was no link to the case involving McDonald, who was already in
custody when the girls were attacked, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   A Buckingham Palace spokesman said Prince Andrew and his
ex-wife, Sarah, still plan to send Beatrice, 11, to the school in
September, despite the headmaster's arrest. ''The allegations are a
matter for Mr. McDonald and the Swiss prosecutors,'' the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Aiglon is one of a group of international schools that subscribe
to the Kurt Hahn education philosophy, which focuses on practical
as well academic work. It has 300 pupils ages 9 to 18 from about 50
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
