<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Paper Cos. Boost Champion Bids  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The paper industry, which has not been known for
high-stakes takeover battles, is suddenly heating up.
</P>
<P>
   In separate moves revealed Wednesday, the two rival bidders for
Champion International each sweetened their offers raising the
stakes for the Stamford, Conn.-based company to more than $7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper is hoping to be the spoiler of a deal
reached in February between Champion and European paper giant
UPM-Kymmene of Finland.
</P>
<P>
   UPM's all-stock deal was originally worth $6.6 billion but later
fell to $5 billion because of a decline in the UPM's shares.
</P>
<P>
   IP, which jumped in two weeks ago with a surprise cash-and-stock
bid of $64 a share for Champion, upped the ante to $75 a share late
Tuesday and increased the cash component of the offer to from $43
to $50.
</P>
<P>
   UPM also increased its offer, bidding $70 per share in cash. The
total value of IP's offer is still richer at $7.3 billion, but UPM
has until Friday to make another offer.
</P>
<P>
   UPM's current offer values Champion at about $6.7 billion.
Champion also has about $2.3 billion in debt that would be taken on
by the company that acquires it.
</P>
<P>
   Champion's shares jumped after news of the rival bids hit the
market. Champion shares were up $6.06\ at $72.37{ in trading on the
New York Stock Exchange, while IP was off 43} cents at $36.81\ and
UPM's New York-listed shares were up $1.87{ at $30.25.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding war comes shortly after another sizable merger in
the global paper industry. Just five days after UPM's merger accord
with Champion was announced in February, the Finnish-Swedish forest
products company Stora Enso announced a deal to acquire
Consolidated Papers Inc. of Wisconsin for about $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper is the world's largest paper maker with
$24.6 billion in revenues and 99,000 employees. Champion has $5.3
billion in revenues and 18,000 employees, while UPM has $9.7
billion and 32,000 employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
