<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Watchdog Plan Gains Support  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A proposal for a watchdog commission to
monitor human rights in China appeared to be gaining ground
Wednesday as backers of a landmark China trade pact worked hard to
build critically needed support.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed side language was being refined as the top
Republican House vote counter, Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas,
suggested GOP support for the pact appears weaker than hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have to do our traditional hand-to-hand
combat,'' DeLay told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The House will vote the week of May 22 on the
administration-supported measure to extend permanent normal trade
relations to China and ease its entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Given the large number of lawmakers from both parties who remain
undecided, supporters conceded they do not now have the votes to
pass the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, DeLay predicted, ''I think in the end we will win.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission plan by Reps. Sander Levin, D-Mich., and Doug
Bereuter, R-Neb., drew tentative backing from both the White House
and key Republicans as possibly the best chance to shore up needed
support.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality is we need some more votes,'' said GOP Rep. Bill
Archer of Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Archer and other Republican leaders suggested the language would
have to be carefully worded to attract wavering Democrats without
losing GOP support.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic and Republican leaders expect the House vote to
be extremely close. Passage requires 218 votes in the 435-member
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay would not discuss details of a GOP head count done by his
office this week. Other GOP officials, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the tally suggested Republican leaders are looking
at from 140-145 Republican votes -- not the 150 widely circulated
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Democratic supporters said they doubted they
could line up more than 70 to 80 Democratic votes. But DeLay said
Democrats need to furnish between 85 and 90 votes for the measure
to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill is expected to face a much easier time in the
Senate, which will not consider it until June. The Senate Finance
Committee will vote on it next week, said the chairman, Sen.
William Roth, R-Del.
</P>
<P>
   The commission plan likely will be voted on this month when the
House considers the underlying China trade bill. A similar plan is
expected to be proposed in the Senate by Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont.
</P>
<P>
   The commission -- jointly appointed by Congress and the president
-- could recommend trade sanctions against Beijing if abuses of
human rights or worker protections continued.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will place an ongoing and focused spotlight on China,
rather than the temporary and diffuse spotlight of an annual
review,'' Levin told the House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Congress currently considers China's trade status annually.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and congressional sponsors preferred
legislation without any such side agreements -- but said they might
have to support such a mechanism as the price for passage.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it addresses some of the human rights concerns some of
the members have talked about, some of the trade-compliance
concerns,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic supporters suggested the commission proposal could
make the underlying China trade legislation more palatable to
wavering members, especially Democrats under pressure to vote
''no'' by organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan was greeted with skepticism -- from an unusual
alliance of conservatives, organized labor and human-rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney called the commission plan ''a
toothless paper tiger solution to a flesh-and-blood problem.'' Rep.
Christopher Smith, R-N.J., a member the International Relations
Committee, called it ''a cover, a fig leaf.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kernaghan of the National Labor Committee for Human
Rights scoffed at the monitoring idea, saying Chinese workers have
been imprisoned as long as 15 years for activities such as passing
information on working conditions to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   His group released a 115-page report Wednesday detailing what he
said were ''brutal ... sweatshop conditions'' in Chinese factories
making export goods.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House working group on China:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop China trade bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
