<HEADLINE> Germans Debate Custody Issue  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department offered strong support
Wednesday for an American father's efforts to regain custody of his
two children, who have been living in a German foster home for
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   A German court ruled in 1995 that the children had bonded with
their foster family and would suffer severe psychological loss if
they were to be separated from the family.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Joseph Cooke, of New York City, had been granted
custody of Danny, 10, and Michelle, almost 9, by a U.S. court. He
has been fighting for years to be reunited with them.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke believes he is entitled to custody under terms of the
Hague Convention of 1980, which requires member states to ''secure
the prompt return of children wrongfully removed to or retained
in'' another member country.
</P>
<P>
   It also calls for respect of custody arrangements and says the
courts in the country of habitual residence are better able to
determine custody issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking forward to a renewed commitment by Germany to
respect its treaty obligations in connection with that (the Cooke)
case,'' State Department spokesman Philip Reeker told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Cooke children were taken by their German mother to Germany
in 1992 during what was supposed to a three-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she remained in Germany, then turned the children over
the Germany Youth Authority as she sought treatment for mental
illness.
</P>
<P>
   The youth authority placed the children in foster care in the
fall of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said the United States expressed concern to German
authorities about the court ruling not to return the children.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ''We have no authority to overrule judicial
decisions in another country.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright raised the issue during a
meeting Sunday with German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer.
Fischer said he was ''deeply impressed'' by Cooke's plight, based
on an account of his case that appeared in the Washington Post last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said the State Department places the highest priority on
the issue of children who have been abducted or wrongfully retained
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   But Cooke told the Post that the support he has received from
the U.S. government for his efforts was ''as close to nothing as
you can get without feeling spit in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said there has been a continuous increase in services to
parents whose children have been abducted overseas. He said U.S.
officials spend long hours negotiating visitation with the children
by consular officials, and helping parents get assistance from
appropriate U.S. and foreign agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 1703 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: UN Reforms Make Progress  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reforms made by the United Nations so far have
strengthened the work of the world body, but more needs to be done,
a report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United Nations has substantially restructured its
operations, and we found this has provided more cohesive and
unified leadership for the organization,'' said the report by the
investigative arm of Congress, the General Accounting Office.
''However, while progress is being made, overall objectives of the
reform have not yet been achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan unveiled a sweeping plan to
reduce expenses and streamline the United Nations in July 1997
after the United States said it would withhold its dues to the
organization without changes.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said himself at the time that the organization -- which
carries out activities ranging from peacekeeping to human rights
monitoring to developmental and social works -- had become
fragmented and inflexible.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO said weekly meetings started in 1997 among U.N.
department and program heads -- as well as other efforts -- ''to
reduce competition among various U.N. agencies and to foster more
coordinated actions.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of how reforms have made a difference, it said,
the senior management group was able to come up with a coordinated
U.N. response during the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ''We also found reforms are still in process,'' the report said,
''and that U.N. agencies do not fully coordinate their
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   It said that although information-sharing had improved at the
organization's highest levels, the same didn't appear true in
''day-to-day activities at working levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The report was prepared for the Senate Foreign Relations
subcommittee on international operations and released at a hearing
Wednesday before the subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the GAO suggested that the U.N. Secretariat
''implement results-oriented budgeting.''
</P>
<P>
   And to ''help ensure ... momentum'' in the reform program, it
said, the Secretary of State should report annually to Congress on
the status of the U.N. Secretary General's reform plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 1710 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
