<HEADLINE> Dollar Drops Against Euro and Yen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against most major currencies on
Wednesday, battered by a broad selloff in U.S. stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 91.87 cents, up
from 90.69 cents late Tuesday. The dollar was quoted at 109.39
Japanese yen, up from 109.45.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound fell to a four-year low of $1.5077, but
bounced slightly higher to $1.5115 in late day trading. That was
still below its rate of $1.5332 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar came under selling pressure as U.S. stocks plunged
for the second straight day, with the Dow Jones industrial average
falling almost 169 points and the Nasdaq composite index dropping
200.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also came under selling pressure against the euro
amid speculation that European authorities might soon intervene in
foreign-exchange markets to lift the troubled currency.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the euro has dropped to new lows as investors
predicted that European authorities would not take an aggressive
action to stimulate the economy and make investment there
attractive. The euro is the single currency of 11 European nations
and has been trading since January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But there was speculation Wednesday that European Central Bank
officials and other European financial officers may decide during a
meeting on Thursday to take some action to boost the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The pound sank on Wednesday after the release of a benign
inflation report dampened expectations of further interest rate
hikes in the Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 1.7150 Swiss francs, down from
1.7168, and 1.4927 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4913.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.1484 German
marks, down from 2.1566; 7.2055 French francs, down from 7.2329;
and 2,126.95 Italian lire, down from 2,134.92.
</P>
</TEXT>
