<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aetna Tries To Repair MD Relations  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Aetna Inc., moving to improve its tattered image
with doctors, ended some restrictions against physicians and
members in Connecticut on Wednesday and said it hoped to make the
same changes for its 20 million members nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford, Conn.-based Aetna said it will let Connecticut doctors
opt out of its ''all-products'' clause, which requires they treat
patients from all of Aetna's health plans rather than just picking
the ones they like.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, the nation's largest health insurer which has become a
lightning rod for public criticism of managed care, also said it
was expanding members' rights to appeal coverage decisions to an
external review board. For instance, members will now be able to
appeal drug coverage and emergency room coverage decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced that specialists will be able to
refer patients directly for laboratory or radiology services.
Previously, only primary care doctors could make such referrals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Aetna said its obstetrician and gynecologists would
have additional flexibility to work as a patient's principal
doctor. For instance, the ob-gyn's will be able to refer patients
to certain specialists, something previously which had to be done
through the primary care physician. Aetna already lets women have
direct access to their ob-gyn.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the recent past the relationship between Connecticut
doctors and Aetna U.S. Healthcare has been contentious, to say the
least,'' Aetna chairman William Donaldson told the Connecticut
State Medical Society. ''We simply can't let this continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna last month settled a lawsuit with Texas, promising to give
doctors more say over what medical treatments are necessary and
removing some financial incentives for doctors to limit care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
