<HEADLINE> Rebels Make Advances in Sri Lanka  </HEADLINE>
By HEMA SHUKLA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Tamil rebels captured a strategic bridge
outside the northern Sri Lankan city of Jaffna on Wednesday,
trapping thousands of government soldiers in a final assault to
retake their former capital, the insurgents said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent confirmation of the rebel claim.
Journalists are not allowed into the battle zone.
</P>
<P>
   But if the guerrillas control Navatkuli bridge, one of five
entry points into Jaffna, they can strike Jaffna's only airport at
Pallali with artillery and cut all escape routes for the soldiers.
Pallali is the military's main supply point.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the battle were delayed in Sri Lanka, where the
government has imposed censorship on news reports. In a fax that
reached New Delhi, however, the Sri Lankan government said the
Tamil Tiger rebels were attacking in ''human waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ariya Rubasinghe, the Sri Lankan information director, said
government soldiers turned back several assaults in what the Tamil
Web sites called ''Operation Unceasing Waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Announcing an assault on Jaffna, the rebels advised the half
million residents to get out of the way of the guerrillas' drive to
seize the peninsula they controlled from 1990-95 and which they
desire as a core for their state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our fighting cadres are moving toward Jaffna city. We advise
people in Jaffna to move to safe places so that they can avoid the
fighting,'' the clandestine Voice of Tigers radio said, according
to residents of the northern town of Vavuniya reached by telephone
by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Figures were unavailable for the number of soldiers trapped
between the bridge and former Sri Lankan army base at Killali.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen miles southeast of Jaffna, Killali was part of the
military's main defense line set up after the rebels overran the
Elephant Pass causeway April 21.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fierce fighting flared up in the vicinity of Jaffna town when
the combat formations of the Tamil Tigers launched a massive
offensive assault on three fronts in the early hours of the morning
today,'' the rebels said Wednesday in a statement from their London
office.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas, firing barrages of artillery and mortars,
''breached a few gaps in the army defenses at Ariyalai'' about six
miles southeast of Jaffna, Sri Lanka's information director said in
a fax received in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   Tamil Tiger Internet sites reported rebel assaults on the
Ariyalai and Tanankilappu seaside military bases. The rebels also
said commando units had blocked the highway that links the
peninsula to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice of Tigers rebel radio broadcast at 4 p.m. said the
army had imposed a curfew throughout the Jaffna peninsula and was
conducting house-to-house searches, said Vavuniya residents reached
by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels launched an offensive last month to force government
troops from the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the government rejected the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam's offer to allow 40,000 troops defending the city to
withdraw. The rebels said they would agree to a temporary
cease-fire to avoid ''a bloodbath'' around the city of 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Tuesday he was
''concerned about the possible humanitarian consequences of the
recent escalation of fighting in Sri Lanka. Thousands of civilians
are in danger of being displaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Ambassador Truls Hanevold said three Norwegian
diplomats, including special negotiator Erik Solhein, will come to
New Delhi on Thursday to discuss the Sri Lankan situation with
Indian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Tamil Tiger rebels have fought 17 years for an independent
homeland for the country's 3.2 million minority Tamils. They accuse
the majority Sinhalese of widespread discrimination in education
and jobs, a charge the government denies. More than 60,000 people
have died in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: government site, http://www.priu.gov.lk
</P>
<P>
   rebel sites, http://www.tamilnet.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.eelamweb.com
</P>
</TEXT>
