<HEADLINE> Accused Rail Killer Called Paranoid  </HEADLINE>
By MARK BABINECK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- The doctor who diagnosed Angel Maturino Resendiz
as paranoid schizophrenic testified Wednesday that the admitted
serial killer believed he was following God's will when he killed
nine people in three states.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Larry Pollock, who examined the freight-hopping transient
for 10 hours over three sessions last October, said Maturino
Resendiz also said that he could travel invisibly during his sleep
and cause weather catastrophes. Those statements led to his
diagnosis, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He felt an evil force pulling him into these homes and
directing him to people who were evil and deserved to be dead, and
as an angel of God he was doing God's will,'' said Pollock, the
defense's opening witness.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, 40, has pleaded innocent by reason of
insanity in the rape, bludgeoning and stabbing of Houston-area
physician Dr. Claudia Benton, who was found dead in her home Dec.
18, 1998. He could face the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Lyn McClellan noted that the defendant raped some
victims and appeared to have stolen and sold some property, all
possible motives for murder.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're trying to make this logical, and (paranoid
schizophrenia) is one of the most illogical diseases known,''
Pollock said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Maturino Resendiz's lawyers, the Mexican citizen
began a two-year rampage in August 1997 with the slaying of
Christopher Maier, a college student in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   In all, he is accused of six slayings in Texas, two in Illinois
and one in Kentucky before his arrest last July. Prosecutors have
not said whether they would try him on the other cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
