<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Audit: Adult care facilities need more oversight  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state needs to significantly improve its
supervision of adult care facilities, according to a state audit
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller H. Carl McCall said state officials were
inconsistent in verifying information on license applications and
inspecting the facilities, and were slow to respond to complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ''When people make a decision to place a loved one in a state
licensed adult care facility they should have the peace of mind
that the state has met its responsibility for licensing and
inspections,'' McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   Adult care facilities provide temporary or long-term,
non-medical residential care for adults who are unable to live
independently.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Health oversees facilities with five or
more residents. There are 529 such facilities housing up to 37,000
residents. The state Office of Children and Family Services (OCFS)
supervises family-type homes with fewer than five residents, and
there are 741 such homes for up to 2,100 New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors found that while both the Health Department and OCFS
require license applicants to provide letters of reference and
information of prior experience and financial resources, neither
conducted verifications or sought independent information on the
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, both agencies were also not devoting enough time
and manpower to track down unlicensed facilities, the audit
contended. Auditors said they were told about 800 family-type homes
were operating without a license.
</P>
<P>
   OCFS spokesman William Van Slyke denied McCall's charges and
said, ''Any reports we would get ... we would certainly
investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Slyke added that local Social Security districts that have
direct supervision of the homes already perform verifications of
the information submitted by license applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The audit) essentially suggests a number of actions we have
already taken,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department's log shows 30 possible unlicensed
facilities statewide that it is investigating, spokesman John
Signor said. He added that the department has ''adequate staff'' to
handle the investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The audit also found that the Health Department failed to
regularly inspect licensed facilities. State law requires
inspections every 18 months -- annually if a facility shows problems
-- but McCall said the department's computer tracking system was
unreliable, with information misfiled or missing.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors instead reviewed records of 10 facilities in the
metropolitan New York City area and another 10 in eastern New York
and found that two eastern region facilities and eight metro area
homes had overdue inspections.
</P>
<P>
   On-site inspections of the 20 facilities revealed that
inspectors at times did not provide complete documentation or were
unaware of state-set guidelines, McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At one facility ... auditors found an unlocked and unattended
medical cart in the kitchen area, food stored on the floor in open
containers, worn mattresses, moldy shower stalls and a missing
faucet in a patient's room,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The audit said state officials also failed to respond to
complaints on a timely basis. Out of 20 calls sampled from two
regional offices, six of 11 ''urgent'' calls were not responded to
within the required 24 hours. In one instance, the Health
Department waited seven days to address a complaint that a facility
had no medication available, McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   Signor the Health department has ''already implemented some of
the recommendations the comptroller office had made,'' including a
new tracking system.
</P>
<P>
   Signor said he was not clear which files the auditors examined
between April 1, 1997 to April 30, 1999, but added that some of the
files could be records from the Department of Social Services was
still in charge. He said the Health Department took over
supervision of adult care facilities in January 1998 after DSS was
dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   ''The comptroller's office has yet to share with us what files
were looked at,'' Signor said. ''We're not aware of any Department
of Health files that were deficient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
