<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Labor Federation Strikes  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW SELSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- South Africa's main labor
federation held a national one-day strike to protest joblessness
Wednesday, prompting half the country's work force to stay home and
more than 100,000 people to hit the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying placards saying ''Squash profits, not jobs,''
protesters filled the downtown streets of Johannesburg and other
major cities. They said big business is too eager to fire people in
a country with more than 40 percent unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   The trade federation is demanding that employers pay one month's
salary for each year of service to laid-off workers. It wants new
legislation to make it even harder for businesses to lay off
workers -- something current labor law already makes extremely
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   At least half of South African workers joined the strike,
according to the Chamber of Commerce. Students arrived in some
schools to find no teachers. Only half the commuter trains in the
Pretoria area operated because many drivers failed to turn up.
</P>
<P>
   Protests in Johannesburg, Cape Town and Pretoria were peaceful.
But near the coastal city of Durban, police released tear gas after
shots were fired from a crowd of protesters who threw stones at
passing cars.
</P>
<P>
   News of the unrest pushed the rand to a record low of 7.15 per
dollar by mid-afternoon. The South African currency has lost 16
percent of its value against the dollar this year -- 10 percent in
just the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The plunging currency will make imports more expensive, fuel
inflation rates and probably force the Reserve Bank to increase
interest rates, Glynos said. The prime rate is currently 14.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates would force some indebted companies to
fire workers to divert salaries to bank payments. That would
further slow an economy that grew only 1.2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   The snowballing bad economic news is pushing President Thabo
Mbeki's goal of bettering the lives of South Africans still
recovering from the racist apartheid regime further out of reach. A
potential rise in interest rates could further slow an already
creeping economy.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Wakeford, CEO of the South African Chamber of Commerce,
said foreign investors hold the key to South Africa's recovery and
should support the country that has peacefully made a transition
from apartheid to a multiracial democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The world should be, in fact, looking at bolstering South
Africa so we can cascade our success story into the rest of the
continent, instead of punishing us unnecessarily,'' Wakeford said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 1753 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
