<HEADLINE> BOC Takeover Bid Dropped  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TREXLERTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- Air Products &AMP; Chemicals Inc. and French
industrial gases company Air Liquide SA plan to let their bid to
take over Britain's BOC Group PLC expire Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said Wednesday they were unable to satisfy
antitrust concerns of the Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   BOC shares plummeted $10.75, or more than 26 percent, to $29.25
in trading at 4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Air Liquide and the Allentown-based Air Products said
they agreed to buy rival BOC for $11.6 billion in cash. They
planned to split BOC's assets between them.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies wanted to strengthen their positions in the
business of supplying carbon dioxide and other gases needed to put
the fizz in soft drinks, chill imported fruits and vegetables and
manufacture high-quality steel.
</P>
<P>
   Air Liquide is the world's largest producer of industrial gases.
BOC ranks No. 2 in the world, and Air Products is fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Air Products and Air Liquide said the companies
made several proposals to the FTC during 10 months of negotiations,
including the divestiture of BOC's U.S. gas businesses, but were
unable to win regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Air Products rose 87{ cents to $31.18}, while shares of Air
Liquide rose 1.10 euros to 151.10 euros ($137.50).
</P>
</TEXT>
