<DOCNO> APW20000510.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grossberg returns home from prison  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYCKOFF, N.J. (AP) -- Amy Grossberg, who admitted to killing her
newborn son with her high school sweetheart, came home from prison
Wednesday to an intensive parole regime that includes a nightly
curfew and weekly drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg, 21, served two years of a 2 1/2-year manslaughter
sentence for the 1996 death of her son in Newark, Del., where
Grossberg had attended college. She walked out of Baylor Women's
Correctional Facility in Wilmington, Del., at 8:15 a.m. Wednesday
and into a Jeep Cherokee in which her parents were waiting.
</P>
<P>
   She did not speak to reporters, but an attorney, Robert
Gottlieb, released a handwritten statement near her parents'
Wyckoff home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am thankful to be home with family and friends and I
appreciate all of the support that I have received,'' Grossberg
wrote. ''Today, I am still reflecting on the past, but I am also
looking forward to the obligations and opportunities that lie
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Police blocked off the street to Grossberg's home in the wealthy
New York City suburb. After Grossberg arrived, two women pulled up
and walked down Grossberg's street carrying three Mylar balloons.
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg went directly from jail to a meeting with her parole
officer in Clifton, said New Jersey Department of Corrections
spokeswoman Mary Ellen Bolton.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a very compliant person,'' Bolton said.
</P>
<P>
   She will be on parole for nearly six months before beginning two
years of probation and 300 hours of community service, Bolton said.
She will counsel pregnant teen-agers at a home for young mothers in
Ramsey, her attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg will need to visit her parole officer in Clifton one
to two times a week and the officer will also visit her at work and
at home ''as often as is deemed necessary,'' Bolton said.
</P>
<P>
   She will have to be at home every night between 9 p.m. and 6
a.m., submit to weekly urine tests for drugs, and undergo a mental
health evaluation, Bolton said.
</P>
<P>
   The nightly curfew and frequent officer visits are part of an
''intensive supervision'' parole, meaning Grossberg's case will be
assigned to an officer with a smaller caseload, Bolton said. State
corrections officials thought the extra supervision was warranted
because of the crime Grossberg was charged with and the time she
spent in prison, Bolton said.
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg and Brian Peterson, the infant's father, were college
freshmen on Nov. 12, 1996, when they went to a Newark, Del., hotel
room near Grossberg's University of Delaware campus and delivered a
boy.
</P>
<P>
   The newborn was found wrapped in plastic in a trash bin in the
motel parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said in court that they believed the baby was
delivered stillborn, but the medical examiner said the infant died
of skull fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors initially said they would seek the death penalty
against the teen-age sweethearts. The pair, both of Wyckoff,
appeared in early court hearings holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   But their defense strategies soon set them against each other.
Peterson pleaded guilty to manslaughter in March 1998 and was given
a two-year sentence, six months shorter than Grossberg's, after he
cooperated with prosecutors in Grossberg's trial. He left prison on
Jan. 4 after 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg pleaded guilty in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Dora Hairston, the Delaware corrections officer who escorted
Grossberg from prison, said Grossberg told her ''Thank you'' before
getting into the car.
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg was released early for time served prior to her
sentencing and for good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ''She did not have any institutional write-ups while she was
here,'' said Beth Welch, spokeswoman for the Department of
Correction in Delaware. ''She was a good prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg worked as a janitor and took classes while she was
incarcerated, including 21 credits of college correspondence
courses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
