<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witness says she came forward out of guilt  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) --Defense lawyers on Wednesday sought to
portray the prosecution's star witness in the murders of 8-year-old
Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother as a woman motivated by a
desire to get a lighter sentence.
</P>
<P>
   By testifying, Josephine Lee found a way to get out of jail
sooner and be reunited with her four children, who have been
removed from her custody, the attorneys contended.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're hoping to get this deal by testifying Russell Peeler
was involved in this double homicide?'' asked Peeler's lawyer,
William Koch. ''You've got a future because of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who has been promised a maximum seven-year sentence for
agreeing to testify, countered that she came forward out of guilt
over her role in the Jan. 7, 1999 slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't live with it,'' she said. ''It was eatin' me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who lived across the street from B.J. and his mother, Karen
Clarke, has said she was the lookout for Adrian Peeler and watched
as he killed the mother and son.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler is accused of plotting the killings to stop the
boy from testifying against him in an earlier murder.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. had witnessed a 1997 driveby shooting in which Peeler had
allegedly tried to kill Clarke's fiance, Rudolph Snead Jr. When
Snead was shot to death in a Bridgeport barber shop eight months
later, B.J. became the state's star witness against Peeler.
</P>
<P>
   Lee spent more than four hours on the stand Wednesday, her
second day of testimony in the weeklong trial. Throughout her
testimony, Koch attacked her credibility and sought to highlight
contradictions in her story.
</P>
<P>
   Koch asked her about a letter she wrote after the slayings to
her lawyer, Richard Reeves, which inadvertently fell into
prosecutors' hands. In the letter, written after Lee agreed to
testify, she denied any involvement in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, though, pointed to letters Lee wrote to Bridgeport
detectives around the same time in which she admitted remorse for
her role in the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew what I did was wrong,'' Lee said, crying as she read
from the letter. ''I get down on my knees every night and ask God
to forgive me for what I did to the boy and his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Jonathan Benedict, asked what she needed
forgiveness for.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got the Peelers into the house,'' she said. ''I got them
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch grilled Lee, who admitted smoking crack cocaine the day of
the murders and the day she claimed to hear the brothers planning
the killings, on inconsistencies between her testimony and earlier
depositions. Lee denied on the stand any desire to enter the house,
but under further questioning from Koch, admitted she told
authorities she wanted to watch the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also had trouble remembering some details of the crime,
including where in the house B.J. was shot and how many shots were
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from the prosecutor, Lee said she initially
lied to police out of fear of the suspects, who had threatened her
if she spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was scared my life was in danger,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several other witnesses were called as the prosecution tried to
track Adrian Peeler's movements around the time of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Peeler, who has also been charged with murder, is
scheduled to go on trial once his brother's trial is completed.
Both brothers face the possibility of the death penalty if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The killings sparked a public outcry and led to an overhaul of
the state's witness protection program.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony is scheduled to resume Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
