<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court rules woman can sue former psychologist for testimony incustody battle  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A psychologist who testified against a
former patient in a custody battle violated their confidential
relationship, the state Supreme Court ruled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That paves the way for the patient, who lost custody of her
children, to sue the psychologist for damages.
</P>
<P>
   The high court said the psychologist, Maureen Smith, failed to
meet the standards required in order to legally break the
psychologist-patient privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Trial evidence failed to prove that the children were in enough
danger to allow confidential information to be shared without first
meeting those standards, the court said in a split decision.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves a Saddle River couple, Diane and Guy Runyon.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1995, Diane Runyon got a temporary restraining order
against her husband. The next day, Guy Runyon contested the
restraining order, saying he believed his children were in danger,
according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Runyon failed to appear for that hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Runyon brought along his wife's psychologist, who testified
against her former patient.
</P>
<P>
   Smith told the judge that Diane Runyon had abused, both
physically and verbally, her oldest son. She said the woman had an
obsessive compulsive personality and was involved with a cult-like
group.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also testified that Guy Runyon was a good dad. A friend of
Diane Runyon backed up Smith's statements, while Guy Runyon also
said his wife had problems with the children.
</P>
<P>
   The testimonies convinced a judge to grant temporary custody of
the children to Guy Runyon. He later gained permanent custody.
</P>
<P>
   About two years after the first hearing, Diane Runyon sued her
former psychologist, claiming she violated the psychologist-patient
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court found in favor of Diane Runyon. The Supreme
Court upheld that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Both courts cited previous decisions that set a three-prong test
to determine whether the patient privilege can be violated. First,
there must be a real need for the evidence. It must be relevant to
the issue and it must be unavailable through less ''intrusive''
means.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's attorneys acknowledged that she violated the privilege,
but argued that she did so because she believed the children were
in danger.
</P>
<P>
   The court found, ''Nothing in this record demonstrates that the
children were exposed to danger of a degree that approached the
level of danger that triggers the statutory duty to warn,'' the
justices wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Daniel O'Hern, with Chief
Justice Deborah Poritz joining him, wrote that Smith's testimony
would have been admissible in the custody action if the judge had
required her to provide it. And, even if her testimony had not been
considered, the outcome would have been the same, with the father
gaining custody of the kids.
</P>
<P>
   So, O'Hern said, the mother has no right to sue the
psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   ''One thing is clear, there is no evidence that (Smith) intended
to do anything but that which was best for the involved children,''
O'Hern wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-10-00 1826 </TRAILER>
