<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Backs Insurance Tax Deduction  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Iowa (AP) -- George W. Bush proposed tax breaks of up
to several thousand dollars a person Wednesday to help elderly
Americans with nursing home insurance and those caring for older
relatives at home.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal was his latest move toward the political middle,
closer to traditionally Democratic positions, in his Republican
campaign for the presidency. Democrat Al Gore supports a Clinton
administration plan that would give people comparable tax help to
care for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor said his plan, at a cost of $7.4 billion over
five years, was an effort to steer people off ''a path to financial
ruin.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding for the Gore campaign, Health and Human Services
Secretary Donna Shalala dismissed the plan as ''a day late and a
dollar short,'' particularly criticizing the tax break ''to pay for
lousy long-term care insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, half of older women and a third of older men
are likely to need nursing home care eventually. An increasing
number of people will be affected as the baby boom generation ages.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to provide an income tax deduction to anyone buying
long-term care insurance. The deduction, now available only to
people who itemize and have big medical expenses, would apply to
everyone except those already on employer-subsidized long-term care
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of such plans -- and thus the potential deduction --
varies widely. An insurance plan for two years of nursing home care
could range from $358 for those aged 35-39 to $2,638 annually for
those aged 70-74.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign estimated the cost of that portion of Bush's
proposal at $5.1 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Bush proposed establishing an additional tax exemption for
each elderly spouse, parent or other relative cared for in
someone's home. That exemption is currently $2,750 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign estimated the cost of that second proposal at $2.3
billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ''My goal is to make long-term care available and affordable
instead of a path to financial ruin,'' Bush said to an audience of
about 60 senior citizens at the Ridgecrest Village Senior Center.
Some sat in wheelchairs; others used walkers. ''We have a system
today where a person goes into a nursing home and quickly consumes
their life savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Family caregivers, he added, ''deserve this country's
recognition, and they deserve a tax code that rewards their love
and affection.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore supports the administration's proposal to give a $3,000 tax
credit to some 2 million families caring for ill or disabled
relatives, and to expand Medicaid to cover in-home and
community-based long term care services that would help keep people
out of expensive nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is close to winning passage of legislation
setting up a long-term care insurance program for federal workers,
the first step toward setting industry standards and creating
quality insurance plans, Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four months after winning the Iowa caucuses, Bush's
speech marked the beginning of a series of addresses on improving
families' financial security, part of a plan by the Texas governor
to undercut traditionally Democratic themes like social welfare.
</P>
<P>
   It was also notable that he announced the plan in Iowa, a state
that has voted Democratic in the past three presidential elections,
but where polls have shown Bush running ahead of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in an interview with The Associated Press, said he remains
committed to keeping the Iowa Caucuses the first campaign contest,
although Republicans are considering a plan to change the calendar
</P>
<P>
   ''I told the people when I campaigned in the caucus that I
supported the system the way it was,'' Bush said. ''I still believe
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa Democratic Party Chairman Rob Tully held a news conference
Wednesday in Des Moines to accuse Bush and the GOP of breaking a
promise to support Iowa's status as the leadoff caucus state.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican Party committee is meeting Thursday and Friday in
Indianapolis to discuss recommendations for a primary calendar for
the 2004 presidential election. One GOP proposal would divide
states into four groups for election events to be held 30 days
apart. Under the plan, Iowa would be in the second group. A
Democratic plan would keep Iowa and New Hampshire's leadoff status.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
