<HEADLINE> AM-NY--Musicstock Lawsuit, 1st Ld-Writethru,0333  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) -- The organizer of a canceled music festival
filed a $250,000 lawsuit in state Supreme Court on Wednesday
against the owner of the proposed site for the event.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Nick Papatonis is seeking to recoup out-of-pocket
expenses and lost profits in his action against Cayuga County
Fairgrounds owner Glenn Donnelly. Papatonis also claims his
business reputation has been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ''We suffered damages putting this show together,'' Papatonis
said. ''We have been promoting this, we spent money on fliers, we
spent money on sound companies.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 65 local and regional bands were expected to play at
the event July 3-5 during the county fair. The bands agreed to play
for free and proceeds would have benefited local food pantries.
About 1,000 to 3,000 people were expected.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials, however, became alarmed when they found out the
show was being advertised on the Internet as ''the biggest indie
(independent) music festival ever.'' Officials said they feared the
event could turn into another Woodstock '99, which drew nearly
250,000 people to nearby Rome last summer and ended in a fiery
riot.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also said they have had past problems with rock
concerts at the fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting last week, local officials said promoters did not
apply for two state permits regulating mass gatherings and
overnight camping. They also said promoters needed a mass-gathering
permit and a zoning variance from the town.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel holding the concert is illegal,'' county attorney
Thomas P. Stopyra said. ''You know we have to try to protect the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   A deal under way last week to hold the outdoor concert at Snow
Ridge Ski Area in Lewis County failed, too, forcing Papatonis to
temporarily cancel it. He said Wednesday he still plans to stage it
sometime in August once he finds a suitable site.
</P>
</TEXT>
