<HEADLINE> Jordan Witness Implicates Defendant  </HEADLINE>
By JAMAL HALABY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- A witness in the trial of 28 men suspected
of planning terror attacks during millennium celebrations linked
one defendant Wednesday to a plan to pick up weapons in Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, Majed Badwan, testified that Khader Abu Hosher took
Badwan's passport last year, claiming he would use it to get Badwan
a visa to the United States. Badwan said when Abu Hosher was
arrested in December, he confessed ''in my presence that he had
tried to forge my passport to go to Syria to acquire weapons and
silencers.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, another witness testified that Abu Hosher offered him
training in military camps in Afghanistan belonging to Osama bin
Laden, the Saudi dissident wanted by the United States in the 1998
bombing of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. The bombings
killed 224 people.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian officials say the 28 accused Arabs, many of whom are
Jordanians of Palestinian descent, planned bomb attacks on U.S. and
Israeli tourists during New Year's celebrations. The targeted sites
were Mount Nebo, where tradition says Moses saw the Promised Land,
and a Christian settlement along the Jordan River said to be the
site where John baptized Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the 28 defendants are at large outside Jordan and
are being tried in absentia. The remaining 15 -- 13 Jordanians of
Palestinian descent, an Iraqi and an Algerian -- have been in
custody since December. They have all pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants have been charged with possession of explosives
and affiliation with ''an outlawed group'' involved in a
''conspiracy to carry out terrorist attacks'' in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The ''outlawed group'' has not been identified in the formal
indictment. Military prosecutor Lt. Col. Mahmoud Obeidat has said
that the suspects were linked to al-Qaida, or ''the base,'' a
terrorist organization allegedly headed by bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   One defendant, Issam Barqawi, 40, told reporters before
Wednesday's hearing that he and the rest of the accused had no
links with bin Laden, though they back his goals. He said weapons
seized from them were ''to be used in fighting the Jews, not
Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   ''None of us in the dock know bin Laden or have any
organizational link with or (financial) support from him,'' Barqawi
said. ''We praise him and beseech God to have him triumph over his
enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   In court Wednesday, the defendants interrupted witnesses with
shouts of ''liars!'' They accused the presiding judge of being a
''criminal'' and banged on the iron bars of the dock with their
fists when the judge attempted to bar a relative from the
courtroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
