<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dreyfus To Pay $950,000 Over Claims  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mutual fund company Dreyfus Corp. said Wednesday
it has agreed to pay $950,000 to settle charges related to the
first year performance figures of its Aggressive Growth Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission and the New York State
Attorney General's Office alleged that Dreyfus misrepresented to
investors how its Aggressive Growth Fund achieved stellar returns
in its first year of existence.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators charged that the fund's first-year returns were
inflated through the purchase of new stocks of companies that were
completing initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Many IPO stocks soar in value shortly after they begin trading
in the public markets and can have a big impact on small mutual
funds that include them. The stocks usually decline sharply after
that initial surge, but by that time, fund managers usually have
sold them.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus' Aggressive Growth Fund was very small in its first
months, making it highly susceptible to IPO increases. As funds
grow larger, however, they are less susceptible to volatile IPO
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, fund managers who own IPO stocks can apply the
early gains recorded by IPO shares to the yearend performance
figures of their fund. Those figures are then used to market the
fund to investors despite the fact that it's highly unlikely the
figures can be duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Dreyfus' Aggressive Growth Fund,
investigators charged that Dreyfus advertised the fund's stellar
first-year returns to investors without noting that IPO stocks were
responsible for much of the gains.
</P>
<P>
   The fund managers can apply the IPO stocks' early gains to the
yearend performance figures of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Dreyfus' Aggressive Growth Fund,
investigators charged that Dreyfus advertised the funds stellar
first year returns to investors without noting that IPO stocks were
responsible for much of the gains.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus settled the allegations without admitting or denying the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by Dreyfus Wednesday, the company, the
15th largest U.S. fund family, said the SEC and the New York
Attorney General's office ''did not find intentional wrongdoing by
Dreyfus or any of its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus has also agreed to reimburse the New York Attorney
General's for the cost of the investigation. The company also said
it will voluntarily donate about $1.6 million to the State
University of New York to enhance investor education and awareness.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to charges related to the first year figures of the
Aggressive Growth fund, the fund's manager, Michael Schonberg, was
under investigation for making improper trades.
</P>
<P>
   Schonberg, who allegedly benefited personally from directing the
fund to buy shares of companies he owned, has agreed to pay the SEC
$50,000. In addition, he was suspended from acting as an investment
adviser for nine-months.
</P>
<P>
   Schonberg, who resigned from Dreyfus in the wake of the
allegations, also settled the case without admitting or denying the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar case, the SEC last September fined Van Kampen Funds
$100,000 for failing to tell investors that the extraordinary
first-year performance of Van Kampen's Growth Fund was due
primarily to Van Kampen's liberal allocation of hot IPO stocks into
the fund. A former Van Kampen employee, Alan Sachtleben, who served
as the chief adviser to the fund, was also fined $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Van Kampen and Sachtleben agreed to settle the case without
admitting wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
