<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Brief Look at Los Alamos, N.M.  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Los Alamos and Los Alamos County arose from the
top-secret
Manhattan Project that built the world's first atomic bomb on the
mesa north of Santa Fe during World War II. The government took
over the area from a boys school.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After several years of functioning as a sort of government
reservation, residents, tired of being denied the right to vote in
local, state and some federal elections, petitioned the U.S. and
New Mexico governments for county status.
</P>
<P>
   A measure creating Los Alamos was signed into law on March 17,
1949.
</P>
<P>
   The county, with a population of 11,000, is home to Los Alamos
National Laboratory, the town's major employer. It is about 70
miles north of Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   The last major fire in Los Alamos County occurred in 1996, when
17,000 acres went up in smoke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
