<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gays Protest at Methodist Meeting  </HEADLINE>
By THOMAS J. SHEERAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Nearly 200 gay rights demonstrators were
arrested outside a United Methodist gathering Wednesday on the eve
of a vote during which the church leadership is expected to
reaffirm its stand against homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters briefly interrrupted an ecumenical service led by
Archbishop of Canterbury George Carey, leader of the world's 70
million Anglicans. Carey's sermon made only passing reference to
''issues to do with personal freedom and its limits'' such as
homosexuality and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   One of those arrested was Arun Gandhi, grandson of Mohandas
Gandhi, India's independence leader.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators were jailed for a few hours, then charged with
persistent disorderly conduct. Under a deal offered by prosecutors,
most pleaded no contest, were found guilty and then fined $100 plus
court costs.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those arrested were from the church's Northern
Illinois Conference, including the Rev. Gregory Dell, a Chicago
pastor who was suspended last year for presiding over a same-sex
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   If United Methodist leaders vote Thursday to keep a ban on such
ceremonies, Dell said more protests and arrests are likely.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be an attempt to interrupt the general conference,''
Dell said in a telephone interview after his release Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since his one-year suspension began last July, Dell has headed
In All Things Charity, a group aimed at persuading church leaders
to honor same-sex relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi said he had put aside anti-homosexual prejudice that
stemmed from his rape at age 10 by a gay man.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope this has brought an awareness to people,'' he said
after he was released. ''I hope this will help us get rid of
discrimination of all types.''
</P>
<P>
   The General Conference meets every four years and is the chief
policy-setting body for the church, the nation's third-largest
denomination with 8.4 million U.S. members and 1.2 million
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The United Methodist Church still opposes gay ordination and
same-sex marriages, claiming homosexuality is ''incompatible with
Christian doctrine.'' It is expected to take up the issue of
homosexuality on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen anti-gay protesters shouted insults at the gay
rights demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're not going to repent of something that you're downright
proud of,'' said the Rev. Fred Phelps of Topeka, Kan., who believes
homosexuality is anti-Christian. ''You can't mess around with sin,
especially this sin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
