<HEADLINE> Investment company settles in mutual funds case  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- An investment company accused of failing to
inform investors about the risks associated with some of its mutual
funds has reached an out-of-court settlement with the state, the
state attorney general announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Spitzer said as part of the settlement, Dreyfus Corp. in
Manhattan will contribute $1.6 million for an investor education
program at the State University of New York and pay the attorney
general's office $400,000 for the cost of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1996, Dreyfus ran advertisements stating that its
Aggressive Growth Fund had returns of more than 80 percent in its
1995-96 fiscal year. But the company did not tell investors that
much of those profits came from one-time investments in initial
public offerings or that a majority of the fund consisted of
''micro-cap'' companies -- those capitalized at less than $300
million.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, Spitzer said investors lost millions of dollars in the
Dreyfus Aggressive Growth Fund. The attorney general's office began
investigations after receiving complaints from investors.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement also requires that the fund's manager, Michael L.
Schonberg, be suspended as an investment adviser for the next nine
months. Schonberg is already on administrative leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''This case should serve as a warning,'' Spitzer said.
''Investors should do extensive research before they invest and
investment companies must be forthright in disclosing information
about products and services.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus also entered into a separate settlement with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, agreeing to pay a penalty of
$950,000. In addition to suspension, Schonberg agreed to pay the
SEC $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said Dreyfus admitted to no wrongdoing when reaching the
settlement with the state.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY spokesman Jon Sorensen said Dreyfus' contribution would be
used to create new business-related courses or expand existing
ones. Specific plans as to how the money will be divided among the
campuses has not yet been determined, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday, Dreyfus company officials emphasized
that the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Spitzer's
office did not find intentional wrongdoing by the company or any of
its employees and said they were pleased the matter had been
resolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
