<HEADLINE> Lindros May Practice With Flyers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Eric Lindros' post-concussion syndrome is
improving and the Philadelphia Flyers center could participate in
full team practices as soon as two weeks, his doctor said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barring any problems, Lindros would be cleared to practice with
his teammates on May 23 -- the day before Game 6 of the Eastern
Conference finals against New Jersey should the best-of-seven
series last that long.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Kelly, a neurologist and concussion specialist,
examined Lindros on Wednesday in Chicago and said there were signs
of improvement following Lindros' latest concussion, sustained last
Thursday when he collided with Francis Lessard of the AHL's
Philadelphia Phantoms during a practice drill. Lindros needed 20
stitches to close a cut on his lip.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said Lindros will gradually increase his workouts without
skating through Monday, and report to Kelly by phone from Toronto,
where he is undergoing acupuncture and other therapy.
</P>
<P>
   If his recovery continues, Lindros will participate in
conditioning on and off the ice. He will skate alone, on Tuesday
and Wednesday, and then practice stick-handling skills with a
goalie and one other player from May 18 through May 21.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros will undergo further tests and be examined again on May
22. If cleared by Kelly, Lindros could participate in full team
practices the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, the former Philadelphia captain, hasn't played since
March 13 because of a Grade II concussion sustained nine days
earlier from a check by Boston's Hal Gill.
</P>
<P>
   The latest concussion, also diagnosed by Kelly as being a Grade
II, was Lindros' third since January and fifth in two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
