<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Panels OK Spending Bills  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans slashed President Clinton's
proposals for hiring teachers and providing social services on
Wednesday as the biggest and most contentious spending measure of
the year began its long trek through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Despite warnings of an election-year veto fight, subcommittees
of the House and Senate Appropriations Committees approved similar
measures providing over $340 billion for education, labor and
health programs. The legislation is for fiscal 2001, which begins
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Both versions would boost spending over this year for many
programs including the Head Start preschool program, the Education
Department and biomedical research at the National Institutes of
Health. But the bills also cut spending for several Clinton
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton threatened a veto. He criticized the
House version more harshly, but also said the Senate falls short in
several areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''The House bill shortchanges essential initiatives and fails to
support our nation's children and schools,'' Clinton said in a
written statement. The Senate version ''does not guarantee funding
for critical education priorities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The House measure would completely ignore the president's
proposals for $1.75 billion to continue helping communities hire
elementary school teachers, and for $1.3 billion for school
construction and repairs. It would also shrink his plans for
after-school centers and retraining some jobless workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version cuts $1.1 billion from Clinton's $1.7 billion
request for grants to states for day care, home-delivered meals and
other social services. It provides $1.4 billion for hiring teachers
and $1.3 billion for school construction, but gives states more
flexibility in using the money.
</P>
<P>
   The bill shows the GOP's ''willingness to slash and burn so many
things'' so enough money is left in the budget for their treasured
tax cuts, said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis. He said the measure
''doesn't come anywhere near meeting the requirements for
presidential acceptance.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House subcommittee, Rep. John Porter,
R-Ill., conceded that the bill's total is ''very, very lean'' and
''just a starting point.'' But other Republicans heatedly rejected
Democratic assertions that amid economic plenty, Republicans were
skimping on programs for the needy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Compassion is on this side of the table, too,'' said Rep. Jay
Dickey, R-Ark. ''We're just worried about how we can afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., chairman of the Senate subcommittee,
said he had cut social services grants because states can use money
from their settlement against the tobacco industry. But he, too,
seemed to hint that more money will be needed before the measure
can become law.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope at the end of the rainbow to have a bill which will be
signed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the bill is for automatically paid benefits like
Medicaid. Clinton requested $106 billion for the rest of the
measure, covering the departments of Labor, Education, and Health
and Human Services. According to preliminary figures, the House
version falls about $6 billion below that, the Senate bill $2
billion short.
</P>
<P>
   The bill serves as an annual battlefield between Clinton and
Congress for issues including abortion, workplace safety
regulations and federal powers over schools. It has been so
controversial that in 1998 and 1999, it never even passed the House
until lawmakers and the administration negotiated a compromise as
part of autumn budget-bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   This year, GOP leaders want to move the bill early as part of
their effort to adjourn Congress early for the fall political
campaigns. Both versions contain extra money for some high-profile
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The House would match Clinton's plan to give the National
Institutes of Health $1 billion more than the $17.8 billion it is
getting this year, while the Senate increase is $2.7 billion. The
House would add $130 million to the $1.6 billion spent this year on
the Ryan White AIDS treatment program, $5 million more than Clinton
proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate measure has $50 million proposed by Specter and Sen.
Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, for the government to gather data on medical
errors and study ways to prevent it. A report last year said
mistakes by medical personnel cause up to 98,000 hospital deaths
annually.
</P>
<P>
   The full Senate Appropriations Committee plans to vote on the
measure on Thursday. The House Appropriations Committee will
consider it May 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
