<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devil Rays-Yankees Game Rained Out  </HEADLINE>
By JOSH DUBOW, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Putting his bats in Jorge Posada's locker didn't
help Derek Jeter. Neither did some friendly advice from Mom.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a day off will help New York's slumping All-Star shortstop
regain his hitting stroke.
</P>
<P>
   While Jeter and manager Joe Torre insist that sitting a game
won't cure hitting woes, heavy rain on Wednesday gave the All-Star
shortstop a day off.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can you correct it if you're not playing?'' Jeter said
before the Yankees' game against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays was
rained out. ''I'd rather take a day off when I'm playing well than
take a day off now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter is 0-for-12 in the last three games -- his first three-game
hitless streak since April 1997 -- and mired in a 6-for-39 slump
that has dropped his average to .268.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre says swinging -- not sitting -- is what Jeter needs.
</P>
<P>
   ''A day off would be counterproductive at this point,'' Torre
said. ''He'll fight his way out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre does admit that Jeter needs a different approach at the
plate. He says Jeter's left shoulder is flying open, making him
susceptible to outside pitches, and he's a little ''jumpy'' in the
batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   ''The big problem has been that he's not selective enough,''
Torre said. ''I know he is a free swinger, but there's a difference
between that and swinging at everything they throw you.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncharacteristic struggles at the plate, Jeter
hasn't lost confidence. In Tuesday night's 4-3 win over Tampa Bay,
he came up with runners on second and third and one out in the 10th
inning and was certain he would deliver the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he was intentionally walked, setting up Paul O'Neill's
walk-off walk.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought I'd get the big hit,'' Jeter said. ''There's no
telling what will happen. But I said to myself there's no way
they're going to get me out. The law of averages have to come
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter's slump is in sharp contrast to his buddy Posada, who is
12-for-17 on the homestand and hitting .376 with eight homers and
20 RBIs overall.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter put his bats in Posada's locker before Tuesday's game and
rubbed them against him in the dugout hoping for some good luck.
All he got was another 0-for-4 night.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jeter's mother is getting on his case.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mom tells me to get a good pitch and hit it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter will apply that advice Thursday -- a game the Devil Rays
wish they didn't have to play.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay preferred to go home Wednesday and make the game up
when it return Sept. 26-28. But without on off-day around that
series, the Yankees decided to play Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem was the Yankees' decision to play at
7:05 p.m., instead of in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our first choice was not to play,'' catcher Mike DiFelice
said. ''If we had to play, we'd prefer to do it in the afternoon.
But it's not our choice. We'd rather spend the day with our
families, but we'll have to put that aside and play the game
whether we like it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay general manager Chuck LaMar requested that the Yankees
schedule the game in the afternoon, but understood their decision
to play at night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't say we wouldn't have handled it the same way because
you get a bigger gate at night,'' he said. ''But I owed it to the
players, because they are giving up an off-day, to ask to play in
the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
Notes: Steve Trachsel, who pitched a three-hitter to outduel
Boston's Pedro Martinez 1-0 last Saturday, will start Thursday and
Dave Eiland will be skipped. ''It gives me an extra arm in the
bullpen and after that last outing, I wanted to keep Steve on his
regular turn,'' manager Larry Rothschild said. ... Orlando
Hernandez (4-1) will start for the Yankees. After starting the
season 3-0 with a 1.74 ERA, Hernandez is 1-1 with a 9.18 ERA his
last three starts. ... Rothschild said Wilson Alvarez will likely
need surgery on his injured left shoulder after the season, but
will try to pitch through it and return in three weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 2005 </TRAILER>
