<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Chiefs RB Faces More Charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- A federal grand jury on Wednesday
indicted former Kansas City Chiefs running back Bam Morris and two
associates on drug and money laundering charges.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, 28, Dewayne Calvin Bryant, 28, of Dallas, and Robert
Corey Myers, 22 of Warrensburg, Mo., are charged with one count of
conspiracy to distribute at least 220 pounds of marijuana and one
count of conspiracy to commit money laundering, according to the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Morris and Bryant also were charged with one count of
distribution of marijuana and Myers with one count of possession
with intent to distribute marijuana, Assistant U.S. Attorney Mike
Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said Wednesday's charges replace a one-count criminal
complaint that had charged the three with conspiracy to distribute
more than 220 pounds of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's indictments resulted from an investigation by the
FBI and the Internal Revenue Service. Morris, Bryant and Myers are
accused of conspiring with others since at least January 1998 to
distribute marijuana in western Missouri and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Morris and Bryant are being held without bond, while Myers is
free on bond pending further court appearances. If convicted on all
counts, the three could be sentenced to a maximum of 40 years in
prison without parole and up to $3.5 million in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who retired from the Chiefs at the end of the 1999
season, was on probation for a marijuana conviction in Texas when
he was arrested in Kansas City. Texas authorities have issued an
arrest warrant for violating terms of the probation.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who pleaded innocent to the earlier complaint, was
denied bond last month by U.S. Magistrate Judge John T. Maughmer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have any particular confidence you will follow my
conditions (of release) any more than you've followed the
conditions from Texas,'' Maughmer said in denying bond.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' participation was allegedly financed by former Chiefs
kick return specialist Tamarick Vanover.
</P>
<P>
   Vanover, who is cooperating with the investigation after
pleading guilty to his role in selling a stolen car, was cut by the
Chiefs after it was revealed that he admitted to an FBI agent that
he gave $40,000 to Morris to buy drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' attorney, William Rork, said last month that the charges
against Morris were based solely on the words of Vanover and his
personal assistant, Gregory D. Burns, who has also been charged in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   An affidavit filed earlier this year in connection with drug
charges against Burns refers to Morris, stating that he was a
passenger in a vehicle that was found to have marijuana residue in
it after it left Vanover's driveway. His agent said then that
Morris was ''an innocent party.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens signed Morris in September 1996, but he was
suspended for four games for violating the NFL's substance abuse
policy.
</P>
<P>
   He also was suspended for the first four games of the 1997
season after an offseason NFL test revealed he had used alcohol.
When he missed several meetings with his probation officer, he was
sentenced to four months in jail. Morris was released by Baltimore
after his sentencing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Committee OKs Cuba Food Sales  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican-controlled House committee voted
Wednesday to allow sales of food and medicine to Cuba, over the
objections of Majority Whip Tom DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   By a 35-24 vote, the House Appropriations Committee preserved a
provision in an agricultural appropriations bill that would license
such sales so long as they are not subsidized by U.S. taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would prohibit the president from including
food and medicine in future embargoes of other countries without
congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who successfully blocked a similar measure after it
passed the Senate last year, said that trading with Cuba was ''at
odds with the national interest'' and would bolster the government
of Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ''Trade cannot come at any price to our freedom ... and to
freedom in other countries,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   But agricultural groups are lobbying heavily for easing the
decades-old embargo on Cuba, and farm-state Republicans allied with
Democrats on the committee to defeat DeLay. Democrats said it was
hypocritical for him to oppose sales to Cuba when he is working to
win permanent trade relations for China.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a double standard here. Let's call it what it is,''
said Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee added a similar Cuba measure
Tuesday to its version of the agricultural appropriations bill. The
House Appropriations Committee narrowly defeated such legislation
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the embargo say Cuba cannot afford to buy U.S.
food unless it is subsidized by the Agriculture Department. Farm
groups insist Cuba may save enough in shipping costs by buying
American food to make up for the lack of federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   The embargo is strongly supported by Florida's politically
powerful Cuban American community, so the legislation is likely to
get tied up in this fall's presidential campaign between Vice
President Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush, said Rep. Jose
Serrano, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is still not free of Bush and Gore trying to win
Florida,'' said Serrano, who voted for easing the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has objected to the provision in the
legislation that would give Congress a say in future embargoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Suffers as Violence Grows  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- A stock-price plunge on Wednesday
deepened economic woes in Zimbabwe, already reeling from a surge of
political violence that has claimed at least 18 lives.
</P>
<P>
   A stock plunge of 22 percent fueled by panic selling over two
days came amid reports that Zimbabwe had defaulted on major foreign
loans, and the labor-backed opposition said it was considering a
campaign of strikes and an election boycott to protest escalating
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's agriculture-based economy was already suffering more
than 50 percent unemployment and 70 percent inflation before armed
black squatters began occupying white-owned farms in February,
sparking clashes that have killed 18 people.
</P>
<P>
   The occupations and violence have led to sharply lower
deliveries of tobacco -- the country's major hard currency earner --
and have crushed the lucrative tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   Banking officials said Wednesday that the government had fallen
into arrears on repayments of World Bank loans to the state power
and telecommunications utilities.
</P>
<P>
   However, World Bank officials in Washington said Zimbabwe has
until Monday to make payment on a loan. If it defaults, then all
other World Bank loans to the country will be suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund last year
froze new loans to Zimbabwe, citing lack of fiscal controls by the
government, deteriorating human rights and the costly deployment of
11,000 troops to back President Laurent Kabila in the distant Congo
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The economic crisis is further exacerbated by the government's
refusal to devalue currency that is being kept artifically high to
slow the rate of inflation, independent economist John Robertson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is hard to see a way out of our currency crisis unless
order is restored on the farms and the currency is allowed to find
a realistic level,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leader Morgan Tsvangirai, a former head of the
nation's powerful labor federation, said Wednesday his party is
considering a program of strikes and a boycott of parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition is seen as the first real challenge to President
Robert Mugabe's rule since he led the nation to independence from
Britain in 1980.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine turns table on Florio, takes dramatic lead in poll  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A new poll by Quinnipiac College concludes
that Jon Corzine's heavy spending has given him a dramatic surge in
voter support heading into the June 6 Democratic primary for U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing former Gov. Jim Florio 2 to 1 in a poll taken in
late March, Corzine has now turned the tables on him and leads
Florio by the near-landslide margin of 15 percentage points,
48-to-33, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   But both campaigns denounced the poll numbers, and Steve
Goldstein of the Corzine campaign said their internal polling
showed a much closer race, with Florio still holding a slight lead.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Jim McQueeny said the failure of the poll to
screen for likely primary voters makes the outcome almost
worthless. The poll instead interviewed residents who identified
themselves as registered Democrats. ''The screen is too loose,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The poll by the Hamden, Conn., college based its results on
answers from 347 residents surveyed last week who identified
themselves as registered Democrats. It has a margin of error of 5.3
percentage points, which when used to adjust both returns, still
places Corzine out front by at least 5 percentage points and
possibly by more than 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac political analyst Scott McLean said the change in the
past five weeks is unquestionably caused by Corzine's $1
million-a-week TV commercial blitz, especially the two-week
campaign of harshly negative ads about Florio's career as governor
that ran during the week of the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, McLean said the turnaround is so severe, he too
questioned whether these numbers reflected reality. ''I am
convinced that this race is much closer than their numbers
suggest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio has yet to air his first TV spot, and the candidates will
engage in the first of four debates Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McLean also said this poll -- the last before the June 6 primary
-- is not valid as the predictor of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Corzine's lead is a mile wide but his loyalty is an inch
deep,'' he said, noting that many Democrats who said they would
vote for him evidently do not have a clear idea of who he is.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, while 48 percent of the Democrats said they would
vote for Corzine today, 55 percent said they did not know enough
about him to form an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   This outcome is explained in part by the fact that 30 percent of
the Democrats said they had an unfavorable view of Florio, and 45
percent concluded his 1990 tax increases were not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Corzine can get this far ahead in one month, spending $8
million unanswered, certainly it can go back the other way in a
couple of weeks with the debates and with Florio's ads,'' McLean
said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio aide Walter Fields said the Quinnipiac Poll results ''are
laughable to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We put no value on this most recent poll. Not only our own
internal polling, but we know those (polls) of the Corzine
campaign, reflect a very close race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, remarkably, agreed, though he said the Quinnipiac
Poll did confirm their assessment that Corzine has the momentum
that will bring him victory in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our own internal polling shows (Florio) to be running stronger
than the Quinnipiac Poll indicates, and in fact shows the opponent
is in the lead,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed with McLean that Corzine's ads attacking Florio's
record as governor have increased the negative assessment of him.
''They build on what people already know to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   McQueeny said primary voter turnout will be low and that Florio
can never be counted out because his base of support among
Democrats is traditional and probably reliable, while Corzine's
support might be shallow.
</P>
<P>
   ''The battle is going to be over who turns out to vote in a
boring Democratic primary, and that number is going to be low, and
the lower the turnout in the primary, the bigger the advantage for
Florio,'' McQueeny said. ''Corzine is relying on the outsider's
long-range artillery to wake up the voters and draw them out. That
is a risky proposition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-10-00 2009 </TRAILER>
