<HEADLINE> Taliban, Opposition Sign Pact  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban and
opposition groups signed an agreement Wednesday to exchange
prisoners and ensure safe passage for humanitarian aid officials.
</P>
<P>
   The International Committee of the Red Cross will be in charge
of the prisoner exchange through contacts with the Taliban and the
opposition, the United Front, according to Mohammed Jawad Zarif,
head of a peace committee on Afghanistan set up by the Organization
of the Islamic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was ironed out in talks held under the auspices of
the OIC in Saudi Arabia's Red Sea port city of Jiddah -- the OIC's
headquarters -- with the aim of reaching a comprehensive settlement
to the Afghan problem.
</P>
<P>
   Zarif, also Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister, said the agreement
is ''an important achievement as a start for confidence building
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   OIC officials said Tuesday that the agreement would immediately
put into force a cease-fire, but Zarif's remarks referred only to
ending attacks on civilians.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a statement attributed to a spokesman for U.N.
Secretary-general Kofi Annan said the two sides agreed on a
comprehensive exchange of prisoners only.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement comes just days after the United Nations warned of
heavy fighting in coming weeks in Afghanistan. On Thursday, the
U.N. Security Council expressed fears that the warring groups were
preparing for new offensives.
</P>
<P>
   But the Taliban said that they were committed to peace and would
not initiate any fighting. The hard-line regime accused the
opposition of wanting to destabilize the government and continue
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Taliban's representative Amirkhan Muttaqi told reporters that
his government was ''ready to free all the prisoners whenever the
opposition did likewise.'' He said his government will soon
announce the number of prisoners it holds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
