<HEADLINE> Judge Rules on Crazy Eddie Family  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Shareholders in the failed Crazy Eddie
electronics chain should get $72.7 million from three of the
company's principals who engaged in stock fraud, a federal judge
has ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Investors lost at least $145.9 million when Crazy Eddie
collapsed in 1987 in one of the nation's largest swindles. The
chain was known for frenzied pitchman Eddie Antar, who touted
''INSAAAAAANE'' prices.
</P>
<P>
   If collected, the $72.7 million would be in addition to $120
million the investors already received in compensation, most of it
from bank accounts that Antar kept around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by U.S. District Judge Harold Ackerman comes in a
civil case against three of Antar's family members -- his father,
brother, and brother-in-law -- brought by the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ruled in 1998 that the three relatives sold
artificially inflated stock in the chain from 1984-87. His judgment
on the amount of restitution was entered April 27.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer who represented the three Antars, Bruce Goldstein,
declined to comment on the ruling. At trial in 1997, he argued his
clients were unaware of the schemes that made the company look more
profitable than it was.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Antar fled the country about February 1990 after the
chain's collapse, and was arrested two years later in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He and another brother, Mitchell Antar, were convicted of stock
fraud at a criminal trial in 1993. Their convictions were
overturned in 1995, but both pleaded guilty before a retrial. They
have since finished prison terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
