<HEADLINE> Canada, U.S. Push for Security  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Faced with increasingly sophisticated crime rings
and terrorist networks, Canada and the United States are working
together to increase security across North America.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials of both countries said Wednesday the goal
was to prevent illegal immigrants and other undesirables from ever
reaching the continent.
</P>
<P>
   By sharing information and coordinating efforts with other
countries, the North American neighbors can operate more
efficiently and minimize security along their lengthy land border,
the officials told a teleconference on border issues from
Washington, broadcast in Ottawa, Toronto and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Border security concerns increased after the December arrest of
a suspected terrorist in Port Angeles, Washington, who was trying
to enter from Canada with bomb-making materials in the trunk of the
car he was driving.
</P>
<P>
   The case prompted criticism in the United States that Canada was
lax in enforcing immigration regulations. The suspect arrested,
Ahmed Ressam, was an Algerian who had been ordered deported after
his application for refugee status was denied.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being ordered to leave, he was never was deported, even
after getting arrested for theft in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The perimeter security thinking discussed Wednesday would focus
on people traveling to the United States or Canada from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we want to do is increase our effectiveness at
interdicting anyone who shouldn't be coming in the first place,''
said Michael Cronin, an acting deputy commissioner of the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   He called it a common-sense approach that best uses resources
and officers. For example, Cronin said, a Canadian officer in
Bangkok with information that a U.S.-bound traveler had a forged
passport would notify the airline to prevent the passenger from
flying.
</P>
<P>
   Working overseas to stop illegal or undesirable immigrants
''will give us greater confidence in terms of how we manage the
actual land border between our two countries,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 2032 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
