<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Economic Program Readied  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian government's economic program, months
in the making and shrouded in secrecy, will be ready by the end of
May, acting Prime Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Cabinet will discuss the document, make adjustments
and implement it in June, Kasyanov said after a meeting with other
ministers, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over when Boris Yeltsin resigned on Dec. 31,
President Vladimir Putin has said little about what the economic
program entails. But he has several liberal economic advisers
working on the plan, and it was expected to focus on continued
market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov's appointment as prime minister on Sunday was seen as
confirmation that the government would continue economic
liberalization. Kasyanov, who previously served as finance minister
and a deputy premier, has called for greater freedom for business
and overhauling the tangled tax system.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov's appointment must still be approved by parliament, but
wasn't expected to face major opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Ministry said Wednesday that a team from the
International Monetary Fund would come to Moscow on May 15 to
discuss a new loan program, according to Interfax.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF suspended its most recent loan program to Russia because
the government didn't meet several loan conditions, among them
making the central bank's operations more transparent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Russian consumer prices rose 0.9 percent in April, up
slightly from 0.6 percent a month earlier, the Russian Statistics
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation is currently at 11.4 percent, well below last year's
rate of 36.3 percent. The 2000 budget factors in inflation of 18
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Economics Ministry said Wednesday that Russian exports
jumped 41 percent in the first quarter of this year, reaching $17.8
billion compared to $12.6 billion last year. The increase was
partly due to rising prices for oil, the country's biggest export
commodity.
</P>
</TEXT>
