<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Chastises Member-States  </HEADLINE>
By DAFNA LINZER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan chastised
powerful U.N. member-states Wednesday for not sending their
better-trained forces to assist the embattled peacekeepers there as
they prepare for a possible rebel onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had hoped that some of those with the capacity would go to
the assistance of those who are in there doing the bidding of the
Security Council and the U.N,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 8,000 U.N. peacekeepers in Sierra Leone were
deployed to enforce last July's peace accord, which ended a brutal
eight-year civil war in the West African nation. The mission,
largely made up of troops from poorer African states, has been
hampered by faulty equipment and, some say, a lack of preparedness
for peacekeeping duties.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best peacekeeper is a well-trained soldier and we would
have liked to see some of the governments with capacity, with good
armies and well-trained soldiers to participate,'' Annan said.
''But they are not running forward to contribute to this force so
we have to take the forces we get.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Sierra Leone began to deteriorate sharply last
week after a regional African intervention force that was also
patrolling the country pulled out. Rebels of the Revolutionary
United Front began attacking the peacekeepers, taking more than 500
U.N. personnel hostage and disarming many others.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. has budgeted $265 million to cover the costs of the
peacekeeping mission from July 1999 through the end of June. The
proposed budget released this week for July through June 2001 is
nearly double that -- $476 million.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. member-states are obligated to contribute financially to
peacekeeping missions based on their abilities to pay. The United
States, which did not volunteer troops for the mission, is behind
on its peacekeeping dues.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said he had been speaking with the Clinton administration
on ways the United States could be more supportive of the mission.
The United States has agreed to ferry peacekeepers from other
countries into the war-torn nation.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, meanwhile, has sent troops to Sierra Leone to evacuate
British and other foreign nationals from Freetown, the capital.
British officials said the troops will not be fighting alongside
the peacekeepers, but Annan said their presence was helping secure
a vital airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''At least they have moved, they have done something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once fully deployed, the mission in Sierra Leone will be largest
U.N. peacekeeping effort currently in action in the world. Its
planned strength is more than 11,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Security Council discussed possibly revising
the mandate of the peacekeeping mission, council diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Several ambassadors asked what it would take for the mission to
become a more robust peace enforcement operation instead of a
peacekeeping mission. Others, however, said the focus must remain
on implementing the current mandate, the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication that any revision was immediately
planned. Ambassadors were waiting for the return from Sierra Leone
of the head of U.N. peacekeeping operations, Bernard Miyet, to
recommend next steps.
</P>
<P>
   But the council may wish to increase the authorized strength of
the 11,100-member mission to accommodate new troops that might be
contributed from the region, the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has approached Nigeria to send in extra
battalions, and on Wednesday it appeared discussions were focusing
on incorporating any new troops into the U.N. mission rather than
having them operate outside of the U.N. mandate, the diplomats
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Freetown, the U.N. dispatched a humanitarian assessment
mission to areas where fighting was reported. U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard said the mission would travel as far as security conditions
allow to investigate the situation for civilians.
</P>
<P>
   During the civil war in Sierra Leone, RUF rebels were
responsible for killing tens of thousands of civilians and maiming
many more. Limbless men, women and children are a frequent sight
there, and on Wednesday, thousands of people were fleeing into the
capital in hopes of escaping any renewed fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
