<HEADLINE> Charges Filed in Cyclist Shooting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Murder charges were filed Wednesday
against three young men who admitted shooting a 17-year-old boy as
he biked near his home because they were looking for somebody to
kill.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the three had been driving around for several days
practicing how to shoot someone, even pointing guns at people,
before they happened upon Tony Basta taking his nightly bike ride
on April 26.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects told police they drove past Basta, came around and
passed him again, and finally shot him once in the back. They told
police they watched him fall, then laughed and congratulated each
other on getting their ''first blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Basta died shortly afterward at Regions Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with second-degree murder were Daniel Angus, 18, Dale
Stewart, 19, and Jonathan McNeill, 19. Ramsey County Attorney Susan
Gaertner said she would seek grand jury indictments for
first-degree murder. Bail was set at $1 million each. Their first
court appearance was set for Thursday; it wasn't immediately clear
if they had lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Basta, an 11th-grader and aspiring photographer, was studying
media arts at the elite Perpich Center for Arts Education in Golden
Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
