<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Fall in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks plunged early Thursday, pushed down by
continued weakness on Wall Street. The dollar was higher against
the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 440.00 points,
or 2.49 percent, to 17,261.47 points in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Wednesday, the average closed down 143.07 points, or
0.80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 109.42 yen, up 0.06 yen from late Wednesday in
Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 109.39 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, prices moved sharply lower as investor
sentiment remained bearish following continued declines in U.S.
stocks, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 168.97 points
to 10,367.78 points at Wednesday's close. The technology-heavy
Nasdaq composite index closed at 3,384.73 points, down 200.28
points.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 37.98 points, or 2.29 percent, to 1,621.88
points. The TOPIX closed down 9.28 points, or 0.56 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar's strength was supported by
speculation the Federal Reserve may move to raise interest rates to
prevent the U.S. economy from overheating. The Fed's board meeting
is to be held May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates tend to make a country's currency more
attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 98.72 yen, down from
99.30 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell
to 1.7050 from Wednesday's finish of 1.7250 percent. Its price rose
0.17 point to 100.81.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
