<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Many Underestimate Hurricanes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many people vulnerable to the devastation of
hurricanes and related flooding underestimate their risk and are
not prepared for the storms, according to a poll released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, which was conducted to gauge residents' knowledge of
storm safety and damage prevention, questioned more than 1,200
residents of coastal states from Massachusetts to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Poll takers concluded that homeowners are concerned about
hurricanes and many have experienced them, but they perceive they
are not at risk and so many are unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many people do little to protect their homes from
hurricanes because they think the cost is much higher than it
actually is.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of preparation is also due in part to residents' low
''Hurricane IQ'' or knowledge about hurricanes, the poll said.
</P>
<P>
   ''People underappreciate the dangers that a severe hurricane
would really pose to communities because people just aren't able to
suspend their disbelief for a moment and say, 'We could really be
hit by a terrific hurricane,''' said Marty McGough, who
administered the poll for Penn, Schoen &AMP; Berland Associates in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Though nearly 80 percent of the people polled believed their
community is at either great risk or some risk of a hurricane, more
than half have not protected their homes and nearly two-thirds are
not protected against flooding. One-third of the homeowners do not
have an evacuation plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's one message we can take from this poll, it's the
fact that there's still enormous work to be done to help people
understand specific steps they can take to safeguard their
families' lives and homes -- as well as their communities,'' said
James Lee Witt, Federal Emergency Management Agency director.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted in April and May. The margin of error for
the study was plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
