<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Group of Chinese Migrants Sent Home
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Ninety Chinese migrants were
put aboard a plane Wednesday under armed guard to return to their
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Citizenship and Immigration Canada tried to quietly handle the
deportation of 75 men, 11 women and four children who were among
almost 600 migrants to arrive illegally off the West Coast last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Migrants were given scant warning about their departure.
</P>
<P>
   It was the largest deportation of the migrants since their
arrival in four decrepit boats beginning last July and was among
the largest in Canadian history.
</P>
<P>
   It brings to 113 the number of boat migrants returned to China
so far.
</P>
<P>
   Close to 400 Chinese migrants had been in custody in British
Columbia since four boats carrying almost 600 people from China's
Fujian province arrived off the West Coast last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Alberta MP Cleared of Unlawful Confinement Charge
</P>
<P>
   MELFORT, Saskatchewan (AP) -- Alberta MP Jack Ramsay walked out
of court Wednesday cleared of an allegation that he once ordered a
teenage girl to take down her underwear and threatened to shoot her
in the back.
</P>
<P>
   The former RCMP officer and onetime Reform justice critic had
been charged with unlawful confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Although Justice Gene A. Smith said she did not believe the
woman fabricated her testimony, she said her inability to pin down
a year when the incident occurred created reasonable doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Ramsay was sentenced to nine months in jail for the
attempted rape of a 14-year-old girl in the same isolated community
in northern Saskatchewan.
</P>
<P>
   He remains free on bail while he appeals that conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Experts Comment on Fetal Alcohol Syndrome Slim Defense
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- David Trott likely will have
a hard time using fetal alcohol syndrome as a defense against
accusations he abducted and murdered a nine-year-old girl, legal
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   But if he's convicted, it might open the door for her family to
sue the British Columbia government because Trott never got the
treatment he and his family wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Trott is charged with kidnapping and first-degree murder in the
death of Jessica Russell, the daughter of a casual acquaintance who
disappeared last Thursday on her way to school.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy on the girl's body, found Friday inside a charred,
vacant trailer, showed she had been strangled.
</P>
<P>
   Trott is being held in the Surrey Pre-trial Center until his
next court appearance May 23.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Women Eight Times More Likely To Die of Heart Disease Than Any
Other Illness
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- The top killer of women is
heart disease. Breast cancer and other cancers are way down the
list, Dr. Donna Stewart told an international conference on women,
heart disease and stroke Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Research shows women -- and doctors -- are not as aware as they
should be of heart disease and its potential impact on their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, of the University of Toronto, was part of a recent
study of 250 heart patients that found women approach heart
conditions less vigorously than men and that hurts their chances
for prompt treatment and better recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The women in the study reported having heart-condition warning
signs up to 30 days before seeking hospital treatment, said
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The signs include: pain radiating down the arms, nausea and
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said delaying a trip to the hospital can hurt a woman's
chances for recovery because many heart-saving drugs must be
immediately administered to be effective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
