<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three brothers who want to be a millionaire share secrets ofgetting on show  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Want a chance to play for a million
dollars? The Barbour brothers have a system.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers -- Paul, Mark and Mike -- are the first three
siblings to qualify for ABC's popular game show, ''Who Wants To Be
A Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Their secret: Bone up on geography and chronological lists,
review those old Trivial Pursuit cards and keep calling back.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are little things you can do to increase your chances,''
said Paul Barbour, a 38-year-old lawyer from Baldwinsville, N.Y.
''It's not just being lucky or smart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barbour connection on the hit game show began shortly after
it made its debut last August. Paul was picked to appear on the
second show Aug. 17, a show taped well before anyone had an inkling
it would become the newest national craze and television's
top-rated program.
</P>
<P>
   Mark, 43, who works with computers at Welch Allyn, a medical and
diagnostic equipment maker in Skaneateles, appeared on the show
March 30.
</P>
<P>
   Neither brother made it past the preliminary ''fastest-finger
round,'' the prelude to sitting in the hot seat answering trivia
questions from host Regis Philbin. However, they were able to pass
on some advice to big brother, Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Mike, assistant director of theater at LeMoyne College, finally
made the show in April, after several close calls. That show aired
Wednesday night and like his brothers, Mike Barbour did not make it
to the hot seat either.
</P>
<P>
   Mike admitted being driven by a certain amount of competition
and pressure when his two younger brothers could both boast about
appearing on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ''I absolutely didn't want to be the dullard of the lot,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike's appearance is generating national attention because it
marks the first time three siblings have been on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had a number of families. But the closest we've had (to
three siblings) was two brothers and a sister-in-law,'' said Pat
Preblick, a publicist for the show.
</P>
<P>
   An ''Inside Edition'' crew was to film the brothers at Mike's
home watching Wednesday night's show. A producer from ''The Rosie
O'Donnell Show'' also has expressed interest in getting the
brothers on that syndicated talk show.
</P>
<P>
   To apply to be on ''Millionaire,'' Mike Barbour called a
toll-free contestant line and followed recorded instructions for
answering three multiple-choice trivia questions. The questions
required the caller to put three items in order in 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Essentially, you can figure out what kinds of things to look
at to give yourself some help,'' said Mike Barbour. ''They either
have to be putting things in order geographically or
chronologically.''
</P>
<P>
   His brothers also told him that many of the questions were
similar or identical to ones posed in Trivial Pursuit, the board
game that captivated Americans in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The real secret, though, is to be persistent, said Paul, who
knows something about being resolute, having tried regularly for
nearly two decades to get on ''Jeopardy'' without success.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 250,000 people call to win their way onto each show.
Producers estimate that 3 to 5 percent answer all three questions
correctly. Those people then choose one of the upcoming tape dates
and enter a 5-question playoff round. Ultimately, 40 people are
selected for each show.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you get into the playoff, your odds are good. The trick is
to get to the playoff,'' said Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who is trying to get back on the show, is now writing a
book with tips on how to qualify as a contestant. Called ''Who
Wants to be a Contestant?'' the 200-page book will be published by
Harper-Collins and is due in bookstores in July or August, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was stockpiling all these tips and ran out of brothers to
train,'' said Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no more Barbour brothers to try out for the
show, they do have an older sister, Kathryn, a college dean in
California. She hasn't tried to qualify yet, but if she ever
decides to, she knows where to turn for those final answers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
