<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baby Hammocks Recalled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Colorado company is recalling about 350 baby
hammocks because they can suddenly become twisted around childrens'
necks and strangle them.
</P>
<P>
   Hangouts of Boulder has received no reports of incidents or
injuries related to these hammocks, the Consumer Product Safety
Commission said Wednesday. But the commission said that between
1984 and 1995 they received reports of 12 deaths of children in
other mini-hammocks.
</P>
<P>
   The ''baby hammocks'' are 6-foot-long mini-hammocks woven from
thin cotton strings with nylon end strings in solid or
multi-striped colors. The label attached to the end loop reads,
''Hangouts(r) from Bellartson'' and ''Woven by Hand in MEXICO.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hangout store in Boulder and its catalogs sold these
hammocks as model number MY-BB-1110 from January 1990 through
September 1999 for about $20.
</P>
<P>
   The safety commission advises consumers who bought one of the
hammocks to stop using it immediately, and return it to Hangouts
for a free, standard single hammock (model MY-SS-1130). For more
information, consumers can call Hangout at 1-800-205-4916.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission: http://www.cpsc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
