<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wooden Toys Recalled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Georgia toy maker is recalling about 9,000
hand-painted, wooden stacking toys because a peg in the base can
come off, presenting a choking hazard to young children.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Rabbit Creations of Atlanta has received four reports of
the pegs coming loose from the base of their Stacking King toy, the
Consumer Product Safety Commission said Wednesday. No injuries have
been reported.
</P>
<P>
   The stacking toys have seven interlocking multicolored,
doughnut-shaped pieces mounted on pegs. The pieces are green with
blue dots, orange with yellow stripes, and purple with green
swirls. The bases of these toys have black and white checked
squares. The top of the toy has a round, hand-painted face with a
wooden yellow crown.
</P>
<P>
   A label on the toys packaging reads ''Stacking King,'' ''Jack
Rabbit Creations'' and ''Made in China.'' Specialty and gift shops
have sold the products from February 1999 through April 2000 for
about $25.
</P>
<P>
   The safety commission advises consumers to take the toys away
from young children immediately and contact the company for a free
replacement base and a small toy. For more information, consumers
can call Jack Rabbit Creations toll free at 1-888-376-5225.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission: http://www.cpsc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
