<HEADLINE> Marlins 5, Braves 3  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN WINE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves twice loaded the bases with none
out and failed to score, and the Florida Marlins handed Tom Glavine
his first loss, 5-3 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine (6-1) had won eight consecutive decisions dating to
Sept. 11, but he fell to 6-11 against Florida, the only team he has
a losing record against.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves loaded the bases with none out in the sixth, but
Andruw Jones' baserunning mistake turned a flyout into a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Miceli loaded the bases with none out in the eighth, but
again the Braves failed to score. Armando Almanza retired Chipper
Jones on a flyout and Andres Galarraga on a strikeout, and Braden
Looper struck out Brian Jordan to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta left fielder Bobby Bonilla misplayed Cliff Floyd's line
drive into a two-run double in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lowell and Preston Wilson hit solo home runs off Glavine,
only the second and third the left-hander has allowed this season.
Jordan led off the seventh with his second homer for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine gave up nine hits and five runs in seven innings, hiking
his ERA from 1.73 to 2.29. Jesus Sanchez (4-1) allowed three runs
in seven innings and was helped by three double plays, including a
bizarre one in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 3-2, the first three Braves reached bases with the
heart of the order coming up. Chipper Jones flied out to right, and
Danny Bautista's throw home was too strong to score Glavine from
third.
</P>
<P>
   But Andruw Jones raced from first to second, thinking the
runners ahead of him would try to advance, and in the ensuing
rundown Glavine was tagged out at home for a double play. Galarraga
then hit an inning-ending groundout to end.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Alfonseca pitched the ninth for his 10th save, his first
since April 24. After Bonilla's one-out walk and Rafael Furcal's
infield hit, Alfonseca retired Keith Lockhart and Quilvio Veras on
grounders.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla led off the third with a triple and scored on Glavine's
single, but Bonilla gave the run back in the bottom of the inning.
Mike Redmond singled and Dave Berg doubled, and both scored when
Bonilla misjudged and failed to catch Floyd's liner, which glanced
off the left fielder's glove but was ruled a double.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell led off the fourth with his seventh homer, and Wilson hit
leadoff homer in the sixth, his fifth. Floyd's two-out RBI single
in the seventh put Florida ahead 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta scored in the fifth on doubles by Jordan and Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Mike Redmond went 2-for-3 with two infield hits against
Glavine and is 11-for-15 against the left-hander. ... Galarraga and
Chipper Jones each went 0-for-3 against Sanchez. Galarraga is
1-for-11 lifetime against the left-hander, and Jones is 1-for-12.
... Sanchez is tied for the NL lead with three pickoffs. ...
Florida's Luis Castillo is 1-for-15 with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
</TEXT>
