<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Penalty Sought in Rwanda Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Prosecutors said Wednesday they're seeking
the death penalty for a Roman Catholic bishop charged with genocide
in the 1994 slaughter that left at least half a million people dead
in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Augustin Misago, 56, is the first senior church official to
stand trial on charges of genocide in connection with the 90-day
massacre that left more than 500,000 people dead, most of them
minority Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
   He has pleaded innocent to eight charges of genocide, complicity
in genocide and crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Chief prosecutor Edward Kayihura delivered his closing arguments
Tuesday. The defense will follow suit Thursday, before the court
hands down a verdict, expected next week.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning of the prosecution's request, Pope John Paul II
sent a telegram of solidarity to Misago, the Vatican said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the face of the painful news that reaches me about your
jail detention that has gone on for 13 months already and even more
in the fact of the request for capital punishment for you, I feel
the duty to renew yet again toward you, beloved pastor of the dear
diocese of Gikongoro, all my nearness, as well as that of all the
church,'' the pope's message read.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly publicized trial that has strained Rwanda's
relations with the Vatican, Misago is accused of sending three
priests and more than 10 schoolchildren to their deaths by denying
them shelter in his parish.
</P>
<P>
   When the massacres began in April 1994, he was the top church
authority in the southern Gikongoro diocese where tens of thousands
died.
</P>
<P>
   Misago is the ranking Roman Catholic cleric among more than 20
nuns and priests accused of participating in the genocide. Two
priests have already been convicted and sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   The government believes the Catholic church was complicit, by
keeping silent, in the slaughter. Most of the victims were hacked
to death in Roman Catholic churches where they had sought refuge.
</P>
<P>
   The killings ended with a victory by the Tutsi-led rebels of the
Rwandan Patriotic Front who ousted the extremist Hutu government.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic church is the only major religious
institution that has not apologized for the genocide. The Vatican
says only individuals can be held responsible.
</P>
<P>
   More than 125,000 genocide suspects are jailed in Rwanda. More
than 1,500 have been tried so far, and 300 have been sentenced to
death. The first 22 were publicly executed on April 24, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 62 percent of Rwanda's pre-genocide population
identified themselves as Roman Catholics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 2207 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000510.0264 </DOCNO>
