<HEADLINE> Wreck Kills Four Wis. Teen-Agers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAUKAUNA, Wis. (AP) -- A car carrying five teen-agers apparently
ran a stop sign on a rural road in southeastern Wisconsin and was
broadsided by a pickup truck, killing four of the teens,
authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The pickup driver and a girl in the car were injured in the
Tuesday afternoon wreck.
</P>
<P>
   The pickup driver told authorities he didn't see anything until
the teens' car was right in front of him, said Calumet County
Deputy Lt. John Byrnes. A marijuana pipe was found in the car and
drug tests were being conducted on the victims. None was wearing a
seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy J. Johnson and Philip J. Lauer, both 17, and Jennifer
Marie Laux, 16, were pronounced dead shortly after the wreck.
Charles E. Tinkham, 17, died Wednesday morning in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Another passenger, April M. Schmidt, 15, was in fair condition
Wednesday. The truck's driver, Michael A. Schultz, 34, was treated
and released.
</P>
<P>
   A crisis team has been working at Kaukauna High School since
Tuesday night, District Superintendent Tim Hansen said. All of the
students attended the 1,200-student school.
</P>
<P>
   ''From what I know of them they're nice kids. They have lots of
friends in the schools. They're well-known throughout the
schools,'' Hansen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
