<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, May 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. House Votes To Remove Flag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The South Carolina House voted tonight to take the
Confederate flag down from the Capitol and put a similar one up at a monument on
the statehouse grounds. The Senate has already approved a similar measure, and
Democratic Gov. Jim Hodges supports removing the flag. Lawmakers debated late
into tonight, with supporters of the bill pleading with their fellow House
members to approve the plan. A procedural vote will be held tomorrow before the
bill goes back to the Senate, which has to agree on minor differences in the two
versions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft Moves Against Gov't Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Calling it an ''adventurous proposal,'' Microsoft today asked
a federal judge to scrap a government proposal to break up the software giant.
In its legal response to the government's proposed anti-trust remedy, Microsoft
said there was no basis for a breakup and that the issues involved do not
warrant such a step. Microsoft maintains that no company that attained its
monopoly power through growth -- rather than acquiring its rivals -- has ever
been broken up.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Annan Speaks Out on Sierra Leone
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan chastised powerful U.N.
member-states today for not sending their better-trained forces to assist the
embattled peacekeepers there as they prepare for a possible rebel onslaught. ''I
had hoped that some of those with the capacity would go to the assistance of
those who are in there doing the bidding of the Security Council and the U.N,''
Annan said. The more than 8,000 U.N. peacekeepers in Sierra Leone were deployed
to enforce last July's peace accord, which ended a brutal eight-year civil war
in the West African nation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rough Hurricane Season Predicted
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal storm specialists predicted an above-average
hurricane season today, calling for stronger, longer-lasting storms this year,
and more of them. Hurricane season officially begins June 1, and the outlook is
for 11 tropical storms, seven of which will be hurricanes, three of them major.
''This puts coastal areas and the Caribbean islands at a much higher risk of
experiencing a tropical storm or hurricane,'' said D. James Baker, head of the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Bush Beating Gore in Florida
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has a narrow lead over Al Gore in Florida,
according to a new poll in a state that officials from both parties agree is
crucial for the Republican to build a winning combination of electoral votes.
Texas Gov. Bush had 47 percent while the Democratic vice president had 40
percent in the poll released today by the American Research Group of Manchester,
N.H.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jury Decides What Edwards Should Pay
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- A day after former Gov. Edwin Edwards was convicted
of racketeering, a jury today recommended that he and four co-defendants forfeit
nearly $2.6 million of the money they got from businessmen applying for
riverboat casino licenses. Edwards was convicted yesterday with his son, Stephen
Edwards, and the three others of racketeering and fraud for schemes that took
place during and after the elder Edwards left office in 1996. Two other
defendants, including a state senator, were acquitted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.K. Plans Cyber Spy Center
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The British government plans to set up a multimillion-dollar
spy center capable of tracking every e-mail and Internet hit in the country -- a
move it says will help fight cybercrime, but which civil libertarians contend
heralds the arrival of an Orwellian state. The new cyber-snooping base, which
will bear the unassuming title of Government Technical Assistance Center,
reportedly will be housed within the fortress-like London headquarters of the
MI5 spy agency.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks plunged Thursday, pushed down by continued
weakness on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average shed 440.00 points to
17,261.47 in early trading. On Wall Street Wednesday, The Nasdaq fell 200.28 to
3,384.73 and the Dow Jones industrial average fell 168.97 to close at 10,367.78.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IU Trustees May Widen Knight Probe
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Indiana University trustees will meet again behind
closed doors Sunday, apparently to decide whether to expand the investigation of
charges against basketball coach Bob Knight. University president Myles Brand in
March appointed two trustees to look into accusations that Knight grabbed former
player Neil Reed by the throat during a 1997 practice. Since then, other claims
have been made against the coach.
</P>
