<HEADLINE> Canada Deports Chinese Immigrants  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER (AP) -- Under armed guard, 90 Chinese immigrants who
came to Canada on ships last summer were flown back to their
homeland Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the largest deportation so far of the almost 600 Chinese
who arrived, many on leaking filthy vessels, on Canada's West
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants deported Wednesday included 75 men, 11 women and
four children, immigration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the immigrants would try to escape if they knew they
were being sent home, Canadian officials gave them little notice
and had armed guards accompany them to the airplane transporting
them, said Murray Wilkinson, acting manager of the immigration
department's Vancouver enforcement office.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Wong of the Vancouver Association of Chinese Canadians
called the deportation excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we had some other options for them,'' Wong said.
''Unfortunately, the Canadian government had chosen to forcibly
repatriate. It's purely a political decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
