<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-10 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Courts Military Veterans  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore courted veterans
Wednesday with $1.2 billion in new education money for them, their
families and their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who fight for our security should never have to fight
for the education they need to succeed,'' the presidential
candidate told about 150 veterans gathered at VFW Post 4548.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress agrees, monthly federal payments to veterans and
their families would increased by 25 percent, from $536 to $670
next year. Gore said that would be the largest increase in their
education funding since the program began 16 years ago as part of
the Montgomery GI Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Benefits also would be indexed to inflation and veterans could
use the money for other types of learning, such as high-tech
training, during school breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said no new money would be needed to pay for the increased
benefits since they will be covered by money available from the
veterans administration.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of Republican George W. Bush, Gore's presidential
rival, criticized the proposal as ''a day late'' and ''millions of
dollars short'' and noted that a former Clinton-Gore veterans'
affairs secretary had criticized the administration's budget cuts
for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ''America's veterans will clearly see through Al Gore's
election-year conversion as an advocate for veterans when they
examine budget cuts in veterans' benefits over the last eight
years,'' Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Al Gore's own Secretary of Veterans' Affairs criticized
Clinton-Gore for proposing massive cuts in veterans benefits, how
can veterans trust him on veterans' issues?''
</P>
<P>
   Military service is often a sensitive issue in presidential
races. President Clinton's lack of military service nearly damaged
his bid for the White House in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans issues got a higher profile earlier this year during
the insurgent bid of GOP Sen. John McCain, a Navy pilot imprisoned
for more than five years by the Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the son of a senator, served in Vietnam as an Army
journalist and likes to say he carried ''an M-16 and a pencil.''
Presumptive GOP nominee Bush, whose father was a member of Congress
and later was elected president, served in the Texas Air National
Guard during Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also touted administration efforts to improve health care
and military recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't give our veterans anything. You have earned what you
get with blood, sweat and tears,'' Gore said to his heartiest
applause of the event at the hall, which reeked of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's stop here in Clinton's home state is part of a
four-state, three-day swing through Arkansas, Texas, California and
Oregon before he returns home to Washington late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore helped raise $650,000 for the Democratic National
Committee at a reception and a dinner in Dallas. At the reception
at the mansion of lawyer Trevor Pearlman, Gore shook hands and
entered names of guests into his ever-present Palm Pilot. The
dinner, which brought in half a million dollars, was held in the
wealthy Dallas enclave of University Park at the home of Debbie
Branson, president of the Texas Trial Lawyers' Association, said
campaign spokesman Chris Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used the VFW appearance to repeat his criticisms of
Bush's proposal to shore up Social Security by allowing Americans
to invest a portion of their payroll taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am against raising the retirement age and I am against
privatizing Social Security and turning it into a game of stock
market roulette with winners and losers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore favors using interest savings from paying down the debt to
boost the retirement system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-10-00 2232 </TRAILER>
