<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Limits Hikers on Inca Trail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru announced plans Wednesday to limit the
growing number of hikers on the famed Inca Trail to the Machu
Picchu ruins to 500 a day in an effort to preserve the route.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-mile-long path is dotted with the remnants of Inca
culture as it winds through the jungle-cloaked Andes to Machu
Picchu, situated atop a craggy peak about 310 miles southeast of
the capital, Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Trains and buses have long carried tourists to the site, but the
Inca Trail has becoming increasingly popular.
</P>
<P>
   A recent U.N. report urged Peru to stem hiker traffic as the
number of trekkers ballooned 11-fold, from 6,000 in 1984 to 66,000
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the 500-person limit has not been broken. The highest
number of travelers on the trail in one day came last year when 494
made the trek, according to Miguel Castaneda, the National Cultural
Institute's director of maintenance and preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The plan drew criticism from Timothy Currie, manager of Lima's
South America Explorers, a nonprofit foundation that promotes
conservation on the trail. He called the plan a ''token gesture''
that didn't go far enough in protecting Peru's cultural wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The decree, published Tuesday in the government gazette, is
scheduled to go into effect within three months.
</P>
<P>
   Government-endorsed plans to develop the ruins and build a cable
car to the site have faced stiff international opposition from
scientists and conservationists who say overdevelopment of the 15th
Century ruins could destroy its serene, isolated quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
